text:
This ice machine does what it says it does; it makes ice, and it dispenses hot and cold water. It does have a few flaws, though.

First, it gives you indication as to how much ice is left. It will tell you when it's full, and indicate when it snot full. But it can be 95% full or 2% full, and the only way you will know when it's empty is when it stops dispensing ice. You can't look inside because there is no way to open it and look.

The ice is on the soft, wet side. It's not as cold as it could be; it's close to melting. This makes it soft for chewing, but it melts easily and waters down drinks quickly.

The machine is pretty noisy while it's making ice.

The ice has a plastic-like chemical taste to it even after running a couple of gallons of water through it. The instruction said that it should take several quarts of water to get all the dust and flavor out, so this may yet pass in time, but it's pretty strong and unpleasant.

Other than these issues, well, it is indeed an ice machine. It's far from perfect, but it makes ice pretty quickly and it can provide about 5 glasses full of ice at maximum capacity.
title: Makes ice, not the coldest though

text:
I have had this fridge for about four years (the same family of appliances, E522B), and the verdict is that its looks, efficient use of space and small footprint (which is a must if you have limited space) are almost outweighed by flaws that are unforgivable for this price range. First, the

PROs:
Small footprint
Great looks, clean, classy, angular
Efficient use of space
Lots of nifty features and nice touches you'd expect for the price
Acceptably energy-efficient

BUT here come the

CONS:
Dents easily - out of nowhere, it's enough for someone to walk by it
It's mechanically unreliable - the ice tray quit working years ago, the screen is erratic and either works, works partially or not at all, some compartment doors snapped out within the first six months, etc.
It's expensive to fix, even a service diagnostic call will cost you a bundle
Fisher & Paykel customer service is horrid

Bottom line: if you can find a similar size fridge from someone else, buy it - you'll save a lot of money, headaches and frustration. It is a shame really because I really do love my fridge - but it's been a thorn in my side for most of the time I've owned it,
title: Temperamental fridge with too many flaws for the price

text:
We have an older Maytag refrigerator that we inherited with our current house. I've kept the brand name Whirlpool filters in it for the last few years and all has been well. I became frustrated with the expense of the filters so I found these at 1/3 of the cost and thought I'd give them a try.

They are much lighter than the brand name ones, so I'm guessing that the filtration inside isn't as extensive. It installed fine, clicked into place just like the real ones do.

3 days later I woke up to a wet kitchen floor. After mopping up, I was able to trace the source of the water to the still-leaking filter at the foot of the fridge. That's bad news, and if it had gone undetected for any length of time, it could have caused some real damage to my kitchen and the room below. This is bad news and nightmare material for any homeowner, and I have zero tolerance for things that cause water leaks. I removed the offending filter, threw away the other 2 from the 3-pack, and I'll eat the cost of brand name Whirlpool filters instead. That cost pales in comparison to that of a ruined floor/ceiling.
title: Caused a leak

text: We love this range. There's something about the style, the ease of cleaning and the overall operation of this range that feels almost retro and more solid than any gas range I've owned. There are zero electronic panels, which I love because we live in a wooded, rural area and there are tons of power outages here which mess up ANY computerized panels and eventually kill them. This is very basic, electric starters for the burners and a standard "glow coil" for the oven. The entire thing is a joy to clean, no crevices and odd places that don't allow for easy cleaning. I don't know who designed this thing but it's a shame that GE has discontinued it's Artistry series. The only thing I'm taking away a star for is the clock. Two things about it seem a little off. The finish is chrome, but the handles and other accents are brushed steel, so it doesn't really match well. And the other, (which many other reviews elsewhere state) is how loud the clock is. It doesn't bother me and actually I've grown used to it, but there is a slight, low "grinding" noise that comes from it which sounds a little like tiny gears are grinding away which might get on the nerves of some people. Where I live is totally noise-free so it seems louder on a quiet day than normal. The white color has a blue cast to it, which doesn't necessarily match today's white cabinet styles well, so be sure and keep that in mind if you are doing a "white kitchen" look. It's a bit whiter/bluish look, the standard appliance white instead of cream.
title: Great Range, Little to Complain About

text:
Bosch Dishwashers are expensive, high quality, nearly silent dishwashers. But, over time, parts need to be replaced. If your power ON/OFF button has cracked and no longer in the right place (loose, or falling into the door) time to replace it. Do not let water get into the location as there some electronic components and switches under it in the the door. Order this part and replace it yourself and save having to pay at least $200 to repairman. Here is how to do it on a Bosch dishwasher where the cycle selection buttons are on top of the door.

Turn off circuit breaker to dishwasher. Open door. Use Torx T-20 screw driver. Holding both sides (Inner and outer) of door, unscrew the six screws closest to hinge on inner edge of door. Carefully and slowly as not to warp door and ruin stainless finish, lift door up and close and you will see there is some play to gently pull off the outer stainless panel of the door. Set aside so you don't dent it.

Along the outside of the door, there are 4 more of the same screws to remove along top, then the handle cover comes off and you can get to replacing the button. In my model, the button actually attaches to the cover. I put a little di-electric silicone grease on the button hinge points, hoping to extend the life. You may see some loose wires and foam insulation under the outer stainless steel door cover, I just used some electric tape to hold it in place while I reassembled.

Everything back in reverse. Make sure your screws are lined up properly, before you tighten them. The metal is thin and can be damaged. Turn power back on. Easy fix, don't delay replacing it, the power switch is much more headache and $$.
title: Perfect replacement for the on/off button on Bosch dishwashers. Save lots of money, DIY!

text:
If you have an existing door with a typical doorknob lock, this is *not* designed to replace it. I did manage to jury rig one of my doors replacing an existing doorknob with this lock but I would *not* recommend doing it.

This lock should be installed on a brand new door that doesn't have any existing holes cut in it. To mount this lock properly you need to drill top and bottom holes (10 mm for the securing screws) and a main hole for the bolt (this is *smaller* than a typical doorknob hole!).

This lock is designed to be locked at all times. There is a latch on the inside which you can slide which will keep it unlocked (however I believe this keeps it unlatched too (thus your door won't stay closed).

The instructions are weak, so if you aren't a professional you may have difficulty figuring out how to install it and getting everything "right".

Changing the combination is not a bad process but it does require dismounting from the door (which in my case I hope to never do!). Although you can use some numbers twice, the sequence of the code does not matter. Thus if your code is 1-2-3-4, anyone can enter by pressing 3-2-1-4 also! Note: there is no number zero nor nine, it has only eight buttons for the code plus the "clear" button.

The handle can be easily switched for left or right operation.

If you can get past the hassle of installing it successfully, the lock does work *very* nicely.
title: Beware - not a replacement lock

This is a pretty basic refrigerator, no ice maker, nothing can go wrong, right? Wrong. I am used to refrigerators lasting 30-40 years, this one died in 4. It has glass shelves, decent amount of space considering it is just a 16.5, it is deep enough that I have lost juice bottles in the back for a month or more. But after 3 years it started to knock like I had a poltergeist living in my condo. Service guy said it was the compressor and he would be happy to replace it for $340. New fridges cost $550, so would it have been worth it? I don't think so.
I dusted the coil, no improvement. The fan is still working so it looks like it is the compressor going bad.
Well, I haven't had an ice cube freeze for a week, fridge is still cool, but not cold and my milk isn't very cold any longer. Frigidaire is going to the curb tomorrow.

text:
When it works it's great. But I have had to repair this twice and am about to have to again. Something fell on the heating element and rather than the fuse working it burned all the way through..leaving a 1 inch gap in the heating element. Replaced that and found that the thermal link has probably burned through because of that incident...I say that because now the heat doesn't work - in spite of the new heating element. I understand why the link burned up..not how it burned up AND the heating element managed to destroy itself. You would have thought the link would have protected the element. Unfortunately not. Have heard people complain the unit is noisy...obviously they are used to some higher-end machines that I've never owned since this has been the quietest machine ever. It didn't cost much, parts are not expensive, but after owning a machine that never clogged (this one needs cleaned out annually or it will clog..and yes we scrape our dishes) - I am not overwhelmed with this one. I've owned more expensive machines and never had these issues. I suspect I will buy a little more upscale next time,but since this is in a house I'm selling in a few years....it's only my problem till then. I would not buy this model again based upon my experiences with it.

EDIT:
And now it has died yet again. Yep. If you buy this buy the extended warranty or you will be sorry. Taking away a couple of stars and going out for a new machine. Did not last 5 years...

text:
I have lived with this appliance for a few years now. I bought it because it was one of the only even slightly modern electric glass cook tops available for the very small space in my 1941 kitchen. And given the constraints, it works pretty well.
My complaints are mostly with the oven. It seems like it's always at least 50 degrees too hot. We burn everything we try to make. We have to watch it like a hawk and we can't trust recipes at all. It seems to bake unevenly as well, pizzas and cookie sheets tend to be overcooked on one side. I just haven't been able to dial in the right cooking mode.
The range top works well enough. I like the indicator that tells you it's still hot. I think the other reviewer missed that in the manual. It's not telling you it's on, it's telling you to be careful not to touch it until it cools.
It is very hard to keep looking new, any spills are basically instantly glazed into the finish and don't seem to scrub away, even with barkeepers friend or other similar products.
The knobs have a cheap feel, kinda wobbly and plasticky.
But overall it gets the job done and it's hard to beat it for looks. Just wish the oven weren't in beast mode all the time.
title: Too hot (too hot) too hot, lady.

text:
Here's my original review:
I've been happy with this hood. It's not wimpy, so your kitchen won't smell like bacon for hours and the grease/steam will be sucked up before it ends up on your kitchen cabinet. The filters are easy to take out for cleaning, but it is rather noisy. Houzz has a good article on how to select an extractor hood, which I'd suggest reading before you order one.
Here's my sadder, but wiser review:
The fan went out in late 2019 and was recently repaired (after numerous calls to Zephyr Tech Support). Here are the problems, according to our repair people:
1. Microfuse is of an inadequate capacity to handle the hood.
2. Motherboard failed. Unclear what happened, but best guess is that this was because of a power surge. However, you can't install surge protection for this hood.
3. Switch was also replaced. The switch has to PRECISELY line up with the windows on the outside of the hood or nothing works (this came from Tech Support; it's not in the manual). Unfortunately, there is a plate riveted behind the switch, which makes it extremely difficult to line up the switch (the plate should have been screwed in) because it's a space that's too small for fingers. This task took two experienced guys a couple of hours of contorting themselves, adding shims, taking the Lord's name in vain, etc.
4. Wires are too close to the motherboard, which we were informed might lead to more trouble in the future.
5. The duct cover had to be basically dismantled to do the repair work; there should have been an access panel.
6. This hood had been installed and then the drywaller/plasterer had done his work where the duct cover met the ceiling. This was unavoidably damaged repairing the hood. There should be a metal trim piece that could go around the duct cover at the ceiling, but Zephyr doesn't make one and this duct cover is a weird size, so you can't just buy one from another manufacturer (most of whom seem to make this part). We will have to have one fabricated.
title: I was happy with this hood - at first

text: Motor is Chinese, but runs EXTREMELY quietly.  We didn't even know our dryer could run without making noise before this.  There are no included wiring instructions, so be sure to take a picture of yours before you uninstall it, or draw a wiring diagram.  The Chinese motor has wiring ports which are slightly different than the original, and they ARE numbered 1 through 6 on the unit, so that gives you a general idea where they go, but there was some guesswork involved.  I got lucky and it worked the first time I tried it.  My only concern is longevity of the Chinese motor, but at this price I could buy another and still be okay.  I would recommend this to anyone who is able to take a picture, use a screwdriver and pliers and connect some wires.

text:
We put this in our kitchen remodel because we could not beat the price versus the other 36 inch ranges. For the most part it has worked well, but there are a few compromises you need to be aware of.

1) The broiler element takes a large amount of space in the upper part of the oven. Things like tall turkeys or hams may have an issue. The showroom only had the duel fuel model so we were not aware of this before purchase.
2) The ignitiors for the cooktop come on with the lightest touch, even if the knob is in the off position.
3) The burner covers and grills are easily susceptible to grease staining. Our old stove had porcelain coated elements for these parts, so much easier cleaning.
4) The oven knob is calibrated for Celsius, so the temp markings are odd. If you are going to make a different faceplate for the Fahrenheit market any, can we keep the markings in 50 degree increments?
5) The oven fan is as loud as a jet engine! This is our biggest issue with the oven. We then to use the wall oven more so we don't need to hear the damn thing.

Everybody loves the look and the price is great, but know the compromises you are making by choosing it.
title: Get what you pay for.

text: We love the Miele Dimension Plus G5705SC that we bought through a local dealer in January 2013.  I can't speak to the changes mentioned in the previous review, but our Miele fits all our dishes and washes them magnificently.  And we love the door popping open after drying is done--I don't know any other dishwasher that can do that.  But I suggest not trying to get an extended warranty.  I bought a Miele extended warranty through our dealer when we bought the dishwasher, and two months later the dealer gave me a full refund of the warranty.  Why?  Miele customer service insisted the warranty was not valid, and Miele would not work with me or the dealer to correct this.  Perhaps the dealer was at fault; I don't know.  But Miele never responded to my e-mails, and they were dismissive of me when I called.  When I sent them a customer review for their website just like this one, they did not post the review and did not respond to me personally.  I hate to imagine their response to an actual warranty claim.  I guess this just confirms that extended warranties are not worth getting no matter how wonderful and expensive the product.

text:
Had a brand new one installed by GE in 2017. One month out of warranty, it failed due to the water pump failing and it burned up (no fire, but you know what I mean). Repair was going to be $500.00. Such a high end machine should not fail! Customer care gave us 50% off of a brand new one and gave us a two year warranty, which was better than nothing.

New one was purchased an installed by GE in April of 2019. On December 15, 2020 the same thing happened, bringing 2020 to a totally sucky end. They could not send anyone until January 5, 2021 to even look at it ‚Äúdue to COVID‚Äù. Riiiiiight. Hand washed dishes through the holiday. Repair guy from ge showed up on Jan. 5, but did not have a pump on the truck to replace it. Scheduled another visit on Jan. 15. Another day off from work to let him in. Tells us that dishwasher is ‚Äúunrepairable‚Äù and gives us a number to call for customer service at GE. Great, I love sitting on hold for 55 minutes-AGAIN.

Finally get through to a rep who tells us that the service number for this GE dishwasher is not handled by her office. She puts me on hold to see if she can find someone to help. After a short wait she comes back and says that the service rep had not put his diagnosis into the computer system yet so there was nothing she could do to help me. She said someone will call me back on Tuesday because of course they don‚Äôt work over the weekend and Monday is MLK day. I put money down betting that nobody calls me on Tuesday because every call back I was supposed to get doesn‚Äôt happen anyway. Long story short, do not buy this model of GE dishwasher. If you search hard enough you will find that about 50% of the one star ratings out on the web for this machine or do the pump failures.

After spending over $1000 on a dishwasher and having two of the exact same machines fail in three years or less, coupled with the horrific customer service, should be a good indicator of avoiding this model like the plague. So today, as a RN, instead of volunteering in our local Covid vaccination clinic where I could‚Äôve vaccinated 100 elderly residents, I sat at home for this. I am pretty disgusted.
title: AVOID AVOID AVOID this machine!!

text:
In April of 2009 we purchased several Architect Series stainless steel KitchenAid appliances from a local authorized dealer including a diswasher, microwave, stove, warming drawer and a 36" cooktop and downdraft unit (~$10,000 of product). When the cooktop unit arrived it was installed by the local dealer's service technicians. During the installation we discovered that a number of pieces were missing from the cooktop including burner tops that prevented us from using the cooktop. After 3 to 4 phone calls to Whirlpool and about 2 weeks later we finally received the parts and discovered that Whirlpool (owner of KitchenAid brand) had sent the wrong parts. After several more phone calls we were finally sent what we thought were the remaining correct parts. After the technician arrived to install them he found that we were missing more burner parts from the high capacity burner and that using the burner without these parts had scorched the cooktop slightly. At the same time we discovered that the downdraft system activation button was not working correctly and more new parts for both items were ordered by the technician. A new cooktop was ordered and then installed about 3-4 weeks later by the local dealer. After the cooktop was installed we discovered that it was scratched badly and ordered another. About 2 weeks later the parts for the downdraft arrived and were installed by the technicians. The next day the downdraft system got stuck in the up and on position and could not be turned off. Another cooktop arrived several weeks later and was installed. I called the local dealer frustrated at having paid for a new cooktop in April and still not able to use it fully in late July and was told by the owner that we had to wait to have a Whirlpool authorized 3rd party technician come to our house to evaluate the unit before Whirlpool would do anything to replace or repair the downdraft unit. Meanwhile, after 4-5 phonecalls and being transferred around in Whirlpool's "customer service" bureacracy of divisions we tried to get a replacement unit and were told by Whirlpool that they would send us one but that they were on backorder and it would be mid-August before one could be delivered to our home. We asked them if they could find one at a distributor or retailer and have that unit sent to us and were told by the "customer service" person that they don't do that. They furthermore said that we could try to do that on our own but that they would only refund exactly the discounted price that we paid from the local retailer and not what we would have to pay to get one delivered from somewhere else in the country to our home.

I run a manufacturing business that sells products in the same price range as these appliances through distribution to retail stores. We occassionally make mistakes as do all companies. When a customer has a problem, our customer service ensures that the customer is taken care of immediately either through a local retailer or directly from us. We see a problem as an opportunity to have customers rave about our service levels to other potential customers and realize that service attitude and responsiveness pays for itself several times over in the positive word of mouth versus the negative that would occur if we didn't do this. Whirlpool had a huge opportunity to have my wife and I telling a wonderful customer service story that would have positively influenced other potential customers in an affluent community where many of our friends and neighbors are upgrading kitchens. Instead I will be telling as many people as I can both verbally and online about my experience and the impact to their sales will be 10-100 times what it would have cost them to be nice to us and try to solve our problem. I hope that someone in the management of Whirlpool someday gets this message and uses it to change the company for the positive. Meanwhile, I suggest that if you can, you should avoid buying any of the brands that are made and serviced by Whirlpool.
title: Quality and Customer Service Nightmare

text:
I recently purchased a Vent-A-Hood Under Cabinet Range Hood / Stainless Steel, Model Number B100 MSC, Serial No. ND 19737. The hood is relatively quiet and works well.

I have only one problem with the hood design. The hood lighting is provided by halogen bulbs which are in under the front of the hood along with the on low/on high/off switch for both the hood lights and fan. If the operator is not familiar with the hood or is in a hurry when turning the lights off or when turning the fan on while the hood lights are on, the operator can burn himself/herself quite easily on the halogen lights that become extremely hot. This seems to be a serious safety design flaw in the hood design.

We installed LED flood lights and removed the halogen bulbs. However, the light switch in the hood is not compatible with LED bulbs which causes the bulbs to rapidly flicker on low lighting. This design flaw could be readily overcome by installing a light switch that is compatible with LED bulbs and not shipping a unit with Halogen bulbs.
title: Very good fan, but watch where you put your fingers

text:
Have had a long and weird story with this range hood. Ordered one and it arrived. We were in the middle of construction and it was several months before we even opened the box. After opening it, we hung it the hood only to realize that a lot of the sheet metal underneath was completely bent and the fan motor was hanging by 2 bolts and vibrating substantially. Amazon took it back but didn't have another one at the same price (??) so I ordered another one from another place. The second came with a dead short somewhere inside the unit and nearly cost us our electrical inspection. The third one finally came with no damage or defects and was hung. Both of the first two units also had screws rolling around in the box.

On the bright side, the unit looks nice and can definitely move some air. On the lower speeds, it is indeed quiet. The lights are decent but having lights in the back too would have been nice. As someone who is tall, if I had it to do again, I would order one with front controls rather than under to avoid having to bend down to see the buttons.

I am definitely concerned about the longevity of this unit based on the first 2 units. If it does break down, I don't have a lot of confidence that I will be able to find parts for it. If I wasn't jammed up on the schedule, I would have looked to another brand.

I really want to root for these guys but this isn't a cheap hood and 2 out of 3 units being defective is pretty bad.
title: the unit looks nice and can definitely move some air but quality is lacking

We have been extremely pleased with both of our Whynter T-2MA SNO Portable Ice Makers and would choose to purchase another if needed.

The Florida weather is such that iced water, iced tea and iced coffee are daily staples through the year. This Ice Maker has been able to keep up with the daily demand even through the past two summers.

My husband calls this one of my best purchases from Amazon. I have recommended this unit to friends and have just purchased an additional unit as a wedding present.

text:
We bought this fridge primarily because we wanted a lot of ice and this had a good ice generation rating. BUT

The ice dispenser continuously dropped cubes on the floor and we had a number of slipping incidents. I ended up putting a small rug by the fridge to catch the ice and prevent slips to fix that. Minor problem. But ...

Within a week or two of installing the fridge, the ice dispenser jammed up. I took a look and discovered a block of ice had formed, from the dispenser chute into the removable ice bucket inside the door. I could not remove the bucket to get at the blockage because it was "glued" to the door with ice.

I ended up having to defrost the freezer to get the ice out. Within two weeks of doing this the same thing happened. For several months I developed a weekly routine of using a blow dryer to get the ice bucket out, dumping out all the ice in the bucket to melt out the block of ice at the bottom of the bucket, clearing the jam out of the chute, drying everything off and reinstalling. Takes about an hour each time.

I had assumed there was some sort of installation mistake. Turns out not. It is a known design flaw.

I finally called a Maytag repairman after a shelf broke in the refrigerator ( which appear to be cheaply made) and decided to have both taken care of while under warranty. The repairman explained this is a known design flaw and that what I had been doing weekly is considered the "routine maintenance" to take care of the problem. It's due to moisture and water building up in the chute each time you dispense ice. They recommend doing it every two weeks, although in our case we must be "heavy" ice users because we need to do it weekly. He said done properly you can do it in 20 minutes or so rather than the hour I've been taking.

However, he spend well over 20 minutes trying to remove the ice bucket and gave up. So I think his 20 minute estimate is optimistic.

He pointed out that they note this procedure in the owners manual. I pointed out you don't see this until after your purchase the fridge and I certainly wouldn't have purchased a fridge requiring this level of "routine maintenance."

Additionally, a plastic part had broken off in the dispenser apparently unrelated to this problem, according to the repairman, that requires replacement of the door. This is under warranty currently but is going to be an expensive problem if it recurs out of warranty.

I called Maytag directly and they confirmed that it is a known design flaw and the solution is the "routine maintenance" I am already doing. They said they are no fixes nor are they correcting the problem by offering a replacement ice maker.

So if you consider spending an hour a week on an ice maker "routine maintenance", Maytag is your company.
title: Avoid "Store N Door" !!!!

text:
My Whirlpool Duet front loading washing machine was getting the F03 E01 error code. Although the code would have you believe that the problem is with the water level, this is incorrect. The electronics have to be replaced. The old electronic control package in my washer was part W10693600. Sometimes I'd also get the F08 E03 code. Then you know for sure that the electronics have to be replaced.

Long story short, the replacement electronics package is part W11032117. I purchased this part (sold by Amazon itself). When I received the box, the part # listed on the outside is W11032117. However, the part in the box is W10908727 - which is apparently a discontinued part. Okay, so I returned the part and lo and behold, the next box was the same problem. Well, I couldn't wait any longer since my washer was pretty much out of commission, so I ended up having to use the discontinued part. Don't know where Amazon got these parts from, but the part in the box is not the part listed in the listing. Buyer beware.

The part seems to be working fine in the washing machine, so I guess I'm good with that. Anyway, just be aware that the part you get may not be what you were expecting. Also, the protective plastic wrap is pretty thin. The part arrived okay, but it probably wouldn't take much of a drop by UPS to cause some damage.
title: Actual Part is W10908727

text:
This is the only washer dryer combo that stacks in the front. If you are putting them on a pedestal you don‚Äôt have to assemble both together and lift both up. The ventless is good if you don‚Äôt have an existing vent. I preferred my old vented Axxis to this one but Bosch stopped making vented ones.
If you have pets regular maintenance is needed. You have the regular lint trap to clean and since the mesh is so fine and you use dryer sheets you have to scrub it periodically to get rid of the wax build up or it will, clog, overheat, and shut down‚Äîrequiring a maintenance call to pay someone a lot of money to take off a back panel and push a button. Then you have to periodically clean the condenser which builds up hair and lint. If you don‚Äôt, the dryer becomes inefficient and eventually stops drying. Washing the condenser in your sink or tub will wash a bunch of hair down the drain leading to potential clogs. Finally you have to clean the sump‚Äîwhere the moisture from you condenser goes. If not, the pump clogs and the water pools and your clothes don‚Äôt dry. This is the trickiest one to clean as it is in the way back and the sump cover is a pain in the butt to open. If you are not handy and own this dryer, you will be regularly paying someone a lot of money to do basic maintenance.
Note: the default dry setting are a bit damp for someone like me who has dust allergies. You can make it dry more by using the ‚Äúdry level‚Äù button. Be careful because your laundry can get hot and synthetics will off gas and cottons can smell burnt.
title: Takes some time to tweak, a pain to maintain. Drys well

text: If you have the infamous "dripping fridge" or frozen coils in your defrost on a Samsung refrigerator, this is the fix.  There are a few parts to get from other sites, like a new defrost coil and a new temp sending unit and then swap this board out.  Simple to install, a few screws at the back lower part of the unit and you're in.  Then a few more to take the white plastic housing off the left side of the fridge (from the back it would be on the right side).  Got me going.  For what its worth, the fridge has a little metal riveted tab that is supposed to act as a defrost for the water drain.  In my opinion, this part is too short and is the cause of this whole mess.  I used some metal strap and an aluminum rivet (you get these and a rivet gun at a car parts store for under 10 bucks) and I made a longer tab to go into the drain.  When the defrost coil comes on, the heat is then carried through this little tab and keeps the drain from icing up, hence your fridge stays dry!
title: Replace this part too, not just the coils and fix it once and for all!

text:
I really wanted to like this hood range... I ordered it based on other positive customer reviews. Unfortunately, I have had to return this item twice.

Pros:
- Looks great
- Lighting is awesome
- Very Powerful
- Matched my GE range perfectly

Cons:
- Distinct and noticeable wobble to the fan during operation. The first one shook my cabinets, the second one we didn't even install because it was noticably worse.
- Non-intuitive controls for the ambient light sensor. At first, I thought that there was a problem with the light sensor, however, we were putting into manual night light mode. You can actually change the light sensor sensitivity which is pretty cool, it was just hard to figure out.
- Non-standard rectangular vent size. 14.5" wide by 3.5" high. My contractor had to seriously mess with this thing to make it work because parts were hard to find, and I have to return it anyways... :/

Bottom line:
I can not justify the $499 price tag for a wobbly fan. Otherwise would have been great!

I will not complain about how long this little dryer takes because I am enjoying doing laundry in the comfort of my own home on cold, icy days. If you live someplace where you have to venture out on nasty, cold winter days and are considering this dryer, you should go ahead to get it. It beats going outside, even in rainy weather. Love the product its holding up well so far. Thank you. Will buy from again!

text:
Be wary you must know if your washing machine is "low flow" or "high flow". If you don't match the correct pureWash model to your machine, you're gonna have a bad time. So please do go beyond knowing if your machine is HE or not. Some HE machines fill faster than others and therefore will need a "high flow" model.

I have two pureWash units. One for my home and one for a home I rent out. The tenants of my rental property are thrilled at how their laundry becomes clean in only cold water with no use of detergent, thus saving them money. I'm thrilled because the rent they pay me isn't being spent on excessive hot water sucking up my profits.

You must pre-treat certain stains. Food coloring and ink stains need to be pre-treated. I have not found a food stain which needs pre-treating. I have not found any stains from hunting (blood, mud, etc.) which need pre-treating. The pureWash system is a boon for hunters who want to remove scents from hunting garb.

I also attached a "Y" splitter with valves so I can have "pureWash water on demand". I use this to clean surfaces and....though I am not advising one do this....I swish it in my mouth as a rinse. It tastes and reacts a lot like diluted hydrogen peroxide and studies have shown it to have many benefits. NEVER SWALLOW IT.

I am hoping the pureWash system may someday be integrated into a "cold water only" machine. With a pureWash system, all the extra 'bells & whistles' are no longer necessary. No more need for "Steam Washing" or "Sanitizing Cycles". I just want a very basic machine with about five wash options (Delicate, Normal, Bulky, Heavy Duty and Rinse/Spin), three spin speeds and large capacity. No more heaters, no more "Intelligent Laundry Aid Dispersal Units" and all that garbage we didn't have back in the 70s. I say a simple solution like pureWash demands the elegance of a simple, yet highly effective, machine.
title: Fantastic Product!!!

Quick arrival
Fits and Performs as expected

Cons:

text: I purchased this Empava 36" Stainless Steel 5 Italy Sabaf Gas Stove Top and had my contractor install it.  I am selling my home and wanted to install a new cooktop for the prospective buyer. Everyone who entered my home kept commenting that they were smelling gas.  I too, was smelling gas.  When the gas smell increased, I immediately called the Gas Co. who came out- with their gas meter read a 5 - 6 point gas leak.  The So. California Gas Co technician told me that it was a miracle that I didn't blow up the house, especially lighting a candle close by the stove during Open House.  I was chagrined that Amazon would sell such a product and only give a 30-day warranty.  It was a few weeks past the warranty and I called Amazon to tell them of this incident and how I could have killed my entire family because of this faulty gas leak in the stove.  I called Amazon to report this incident and they said because it was past a 30-day warranty, I had to purchase another stove top which I did, because I needed to have a stove top for Open Houses.  My plumber and Contractor both came out to install the replacement stove top that I had to purchase again...because the previous stove top was 30 days out of warranty.  After paying the contractor/plumber fees (2 Times) amounting to $800 - the contractor installed the replacement stove top and did a gas check to see if everything was working well after the installation.  When the burners were turned on the plumber/contractor smelled gas again.  They tested all of the gas lines and lines were fine...It was again, a gas leak in the stove and it had to be removed once again.  This is a very seriously dangerous product.  What are the chances that the 2nd replacement stove top that I had to purchase again, had the same gas leak in the stove?  Seriously Amazon....I would definitely take this product off the market before it kills someone.  It is very dangerous!
title: Very Very Dangerous Product.  Should be taken off the market! - Zero Rating.

text: Monday August 12, 2013 the water feed line to our Profile Fridge began leaking, all over our wood floor. We managed to ascertain the problem was the fridge hose supplying water to the ice machine. We called GE Service and made an appointment. The agent said a technician would call in advance between 1 and 5 pm the next day to tell us when he was coming. There was also some chance he could come earlier. We stuck around all day till 4 pm when I called the Service Center to ask when he'd be coming. The operator could not reach the tech, but assured me he'd come before 5. He did not. I then called again, this time the operator insisted we did not exist on the verification site. I asked to speak to her superior, who also had trouble finding us, but finally, when I suggested she check by name, she did locate our information, but not our service order. She implied that there was something wrong with us. I hung up. This was a ridiculous experience and I will make sure it doesn't happen again. I'm posting wherever I can.
title: Beware of service issues with any GE product

text:
I purchased this unit for the sole purpose of having in my shop to wash microfiber towels when I'm finished detailing vehicles, rather than taking them in to the house and fighting for the laundry with the rest of the family.

The packaging is fantastic and sturdy. The unit showed up intact without any issues, or damage to the exterior of the packaging or the unit inside.

Taking the unit out of the packaging revealed some minimal residual water coming from the unit. I'd thought I possibly gotten a returned machine, but chalked it up to a test at the facility before shipping out for quality control under more scrupulous investigation.

The instruction manual was written by, or translated by, someone whose first language is not English. It's understandable, and can be followed, but some of the grammar and terminology are not common.

The hose to connect the unit to the sink leaks that the straight end and doesn't seat correctly. But this is a relatively easy fix, or just get a new hose.

A set of lockable caster wheels would be a good addition rather than having to lift & carry to move the machine to use it.

The machine itself is very quiet, and looking inside the bottom appears to be relatively well built. I have run a few loads through it and it does a good job of cleaning everything.

Overall, I got a machine that is what I expected for the price paid. Thus far it has been a solid little washer, and operates very well.

text: Like several other readers, I purchased the Eco-Fill 2.0 Deluxe to work with my new Keurig K350 machine, and it only worked occasionally.  I contacted the Perfect Pod Support staff, and I have been very pleased with their persistence in resolving this issue.  After providing proof of purchase to verify I had purchased the Eco-Fill 2.0, they sent me a replacement right away.  The replacement was a slightly different color, and it didn't work either.  After reporting that back to Perfect Pod support, they sent me a second replacement which works great.  During this process, I started having trouble with my Keurig machine in that the screen would go blank and I would have to unplug the machine to reset it.  Keurig sent me a replacement machine.  When I received that machine, I tried the earlier versions of the Eco-Fill 2.0 and they worked fine.  So my take on this is that some of the Keurig machines are more sensitive than others which explains why many users had no problems with the Eco-Fill 2.0 and a few did have problems.  The bottom line is that Perfect Pod appears to now have an Eco-Fill 2.0 unit that works even with the sensitive machines.  So, if you have a problem, contact the support via the website listed on the package.
title: The Perfect Pod Support Staff Soved the problem with my Eco-Fill 2.0

text: My opinion do NOT  buy this ice maker.  I received my first unit and was at first impressed.  It was fairly easy to connect. The keypad and instructions are terrible but I figured it out.  It made ice well for about 6 months. When I say well I only use about 1 bag a week so it was not over used by any means.  I noticed it was empty and saw E2 on the display which is a Freon leak.  I contacted the company and they were very good at answering and sent me another unit.  I asked what to do with the old unit and they said whatever you want.  That is when i got suspicious.  Apparently the cost of goods to the manufacturer is less than the freight to get the unit back and re manufacture it. I installed the warranty unit and it did exactly the same thing. It worked about  6 months and 1 week and failed the same way...... E2.  Now its out of warranty and dead.  So for me the cost of the unit only provided good service for just over one year needing 2 units to accomplish it. Appears to be very low quality and built to just last long enough to be outside of warranty.  I would steer clear of this item.
title: First died under warranty then replacement died same way just out of warranty

text: I have had the machine for about two weeks. I like the way the machine looks.  I was disappointed to see that it arrived with a dent on the left backside edge of the machine.  The machine washes well. The clothes do come out clean as long as you don't load it over 11 lbs.  I wish the machine would move a little stronger and faster during the wash cycle. The machine will wash and stop during the wash cycle.  It is not a continuous washing movement.  I don't know if that makes any difference in how well it washes.  I guess I'm used to a larger machine with a stronger washing cycle. Also, I thought the machine looks a little larger than I expected. If you are looking to put it in a closet it would have to be a walk-in closet or a very long and wide closet. The machine does have two wheels on the backside, but if you are planning to move it a lot, I suggest a dolly. The machine is a little heavy, so it is easier to move with the dolly.  Again it washes well and does what I need it for. I was not happy with the dent, but because it is on the backside and not that noticeable, I took my husband's advice. We felt it wasn't worth going through the trouble of sending it back when the machine, up to now, is working well. Anyway, who's to say that we might not end up getting another machine that may have more dents and not work as well. Based on some reviews I read on receiving portable machines with dent through online shopping,  I knew it was a possibility that the machine might come with a dent. And it did. But not too bad. text:
After deciding to spend what anyone would consider to be a large sum of money on a coffee maker, I invested in the B70 Platinum. Like many other people writing reviews here, I was frustrated with the cost, lack of options and waste of traditional K-Cups. Having heard less than stellar things about many different types of reusable K-Cup filters I was ecstatic to hear about the EkoBrew. I immediately ordered a 2-pack in anticipation of using them daily - boy was I in for a surprise.

After unpacking the EkoBrews I immediately filled them up with DunkinDonuts Bold coffee grounds about 2/3 full, just as the instructions indicate. I properly closed the lid, ensuring a tight seal and no coffee near the o-ring which would potentially allow leakage. Popped it in the Keurig and pressed brew. To my dismay, water began leaking out all over the spout of the Keurig, luckily mostly landing in my wide mug. While watching the coffee dispense I noticed at first the color was dark, and appeared to look like coffee, however by the end it was nearly clear water.

Willing to accept some degree of mess (still probably easier than conventional brewing) I took a sip of the coffee and immediately poured it out. Watery and with a large quantity of coffee grounds was not what I had in mind. I then opened up the Kuerig only to find coffee basically everywhere, so I quickly attempted to wipe it down with a rag, but obviously was unable to get into every nook and cranny. On top of that, when I closed the hatch more coffee leaked out of the spout, getting my counter and bottom of the Keurig dirty - the phrase insult to injury comes to mind.

Needless to say I am disgusted with this product. Taking a risk on a 3rd party device to outperform an expensive, wasteful alternative is one thing, but the harm done to the (very) expensive device is an atrocity. I couldn't care less about not being able to return a worthless device, but I want my Keurig to be clean again. My only hope is that this is a function of this particular device, however, if you are using the B70 Platinum I encourage you to seek other products or stick to K-Cups.
title: Ridiculously Disappointed

text:
[[VIDEOID:fb709d6e659af043b7f00cdef5a8ac43]] We needed a portable stovetop for outdoor cooking -- or in case of a long power outage, since we have an all-electric kitchen. This Forimo single gas burner, surrounded by a dark tempered glass surface, is just what we need.

We already have a gas grill, but it's not practical to use a frying pan or cook a pot of chili due to the indirect heat source. This propane burner really puts out some heat on the highest setting to get you up and going fast.

The single operation knob is also the starter. When you push and turn it a quarter turn to the left, it clicks and the spark ignites the flame instantly. Turn it further to lower the flame to your desired setting.

The included hose connects at the lower rear of the burner exterior. The quick connect on the other end attaches to the propane tank. Easy as pie.

The rack on the stovetop keeps your pan or pot level and steady right over the flame.

Bottom line: simple, well built, sturdy and practical cooking device, and a good value.
title: Excellent Portable Gas Stovetop

text:
The new Samsung 6.3 cu. ft. Front Control Slide-In Electric Range with Convection & Wi-Fi in Stainless Steel is a great oven, but like with everything in life, it could be better.
Let me start by listing the Pros:
Fingerprint Resistant: It does minimize the number of fingerprints on the stainless-steel frame, but it may leave little smudges here or there.
Five heating elements: The power on the heating elements is awesome. It provides fast heat in just seconds. It also includes two dual ring elements to be used with multiple sized pots and pans.
Oven: large 6.3 cu. ft. oven is big enough to accommodate multiple large dishes at once, especially with the holidays coming up. Powerful convention decreases the time for baking, roasting and evenly cooking food. Compatible with SmartThings and any virtual assistance available.

Now the Cons:
Fingerprint resistant: smudges are still visible and will build up if not wiped. Touch screen smudges constantly and it is very sensitive to the touch. Any passing of a cloth on the touch screen will activate any of the features. The locking mechanism is available, but it also locks the oven door and if the sensors do not detect the door, it will take a while for the locking mechanism to work. Additionally, there are no instructions on the usage of the touch screen controls in either of the three manuals that come in the box. To get a detailed description on the touch screen features, you will need to go to Samsung‚Äôs website and download the manual for the range.
Cooktop: even after the hot surface indicator turns off, the cooktop still stays very warm and will burn your hand to the touch. It does take quite a while for the cooktop to be cold. Cleaning the cooktop has been an issue. Even with the warm surface cooktop, the cloth will stick to the cooktop and will leave a permanent mark on it.
Virtual Assistance: As cool as it is to have an oven that is controlled via Bixby, Google Assistance, Alexa, SmartThings, etc., it really is only good for utilizing the oven feature. The SmartThings App will let you control the oven light and the oven temperature, but you do not have any access to the cooktop. It will let you know that the cooktop is on, but you can not turn it off. If you do utilize any of the virtual assistance voice commands to pre-heat your oven, make sure that there is nothing inside the oven i.e. pots, pans, etc. I believe this feature is only good if you are out of the house and realize you want to cook a frozen pizza and need the oven to be pre-heated. Not sure how many times this feature will be utilized, but it is available.
**Testing the product as part of an Insiders promotion**
title: Slide in Perfection

One long edge of the gasket has fins intended to hold the gasket in place in a channel. The thickness of the old gasket was 0.16" at the fins. The thickness of this gasket was only 0.10". My Frigidaire model number LGBD2435nw0a was listed as one of the models for which the gasket should work, but obviously it did not.

text: Here's the deal-I am a coffee fiend. Not in the cutesy "OMG I just *have* to have my morning coffee or don't talk to me lolz" sorta way. Its a legitimately full-blown addiction and my brain is completely dead until I've hit the right caffeine intake. If you have the option-switch to green tea or something because having caffeine headaches and being mean without your fix isn't a cute look. However-if you're already hooked and need it, I don't have to tell you how expensive it is. Especially with cold brew-a Toddy cold brew from the cafe I used to work at was $6. A Starbucks Nitro cold brew is about the same. For awhile, I was using Chameleon (given up recently due to them being Nestle-owned) or buying the $6 jugs of pre-made cold brew from the grocery store (which would only last me a day and a half, at best). This filter has changed my game. I fill this filter with ground coffee and drop it in a 4-pint mason jar, then leave it in the fridge for ~19 hrs. I alternate it between a couple jars to keep a steady supply. Remove the filter, pour over some ice, add a pump of macadamia nut syrup and a splash of coconut milk and enjoy the savings. This has made a serious dent in my coffee budget and ensures that I never run out of fresh cold brew and become a monster of a human. Highly recommend.
title: Goodbye Expensive Cold Brew!

text:
Most of this review is not a reflection of the product but the issues with the installation and should not reflect badly on the quality of the product which is quite good. Due to where my washer and dryer are located, I had to disconnect both of them and physically move them out. I disconnected the dryer vent which actually needed to be replaced. Then I shut off the gas and disconnected the line. I removed the power and disconnected the water lines and drain hose from the washer which spilled a decent amount of water on the floor. Years of being in place yielded a lot of dirt and grime. So, I cleaned under and the back of both appliances and the dryer vent. Then a quick trip to the hardware store for a replacement vent hose. I was finally ready to place this product on my washing machine which turned out to be a little more involved as I was doing this by myself. It‚Äôs not that easy to lift up the appliance and try to place the pad on the foot of the washer by yourself. The pads gripped my floor pretty well too which made it difficult to move the washer back into place.

What seems on the surface like a 15 minute job, just pick up the machine and throw the four pads on, turned into an almost 5 hour ordeal. Again, not a reflection on the product but I do consider this as part of the installation. So, the moral of this story! This would have been much easier with two people. If I had another person I would have placed the pads after moving the washing machine back in place instead of before and struggling to get it in place. Plan on having to clean under, behind and around the appliances. On a good note, I did get two and a half pairs of mismatched socks. And, this is very important, if you have a gas appliance as I did and you need to move and/or disconnect it. Please know what you are doing, this is not for amateurs and can result in catastrophic damage and potentially loss of life. Call a professional. Also make sure that not only there are no leaks (gas and water) but that your dryer vent/hose are not bound or kinked and able to vent properly.

Unfortunately for me I only got one set which I put on my washer. I wish I would have picked up an extra set for the dryer at the same time. I‚Äôve only done two loads but have had zero issues. My washing machine actually seems a little quieter while operating. Nice product but depending on your circumstances may require some work to install.
title: Definitely a two person job.

text:
Bought this fridge last July from HHGregg and I am so disappointed in it.

Besides the fact it is extremly loud, you can't keep the doors open more than 10 seconds or it starts beeping at you. I've read about this and you can't change it.

Besides that, everytime we put the milk in the door - the molding around the milk drawer pops off. At this point, it has happened so many times that we can't get the molding back on.

The latest is the ice machine stopped working. I called Bosch and this was a joke. They didn't seem to care.

So I talked with HHGregg and they gave me a # to a service place they use.

text:
Tired of the constant lint from the Kenmore clothes dryer, I took a couple of remedial measures, one of which was to replace the ineffective 12-year-old OEM lint filter. The old one had a heavy felt gasket around it - so thick it often seemed to cause gaps, rather than prevent them. The felt on this one is less pronounced but seems to provide a tighter seal, forcing the expelled air through the filter rather than around it. Result: it catches more lint.

Overall though, let's cry shame on the manufacturers of electric dryers, none of which seem to be able to make a filter that truly catches even 50% of the lint. A special problem if your dryer for some reason has to be vented indoors (mine does); but still bad even if you're just pushing all that lint outdoors to flutter around and goop up the air.
title: An Improvement on OEM

text:
I purchased these for a friend who confided she would like to use some of her favorite coffees but they did not come in pods to fit the machine her daughters gave her a year ago at Christmas. I told her when I stayed in Hawaii in a condo on vacation and they had a Keurig I was wanting to use the coffee I got at the coffee plantation and found reusable holders at a local store. I used them during vacation them gave them to the daughter of a friend who just had her first shared apartment after college and it included a shared Keurig. She thought the pods were too pricey and did not include her favorite roast. She thanks me every time I see her.
So I told my friend I would check Amazon. I learned the ones I bought were for the first Keurig model and now there were some differences. Also the company now sold a single refillable option but it was pricey and why only one when sometimes you want to make several cups for guests. These seemed to have high ratings and would work on her 2.0, so I ordered a set. I liked that the company made a 60-day satisfaction guarantee, too. She called me this afternoon to say she just made her first cup of coffee and it was perfect. There was no hassle-- unless you count that she was so busy watching it start she forgot to put a cup under it. Quickly rectified and she is very happy with your product.

Update: (9.7.17) My friend has been using these now for several months and likes them so well she bought another pack to have ready when she has meetings at her house. I also got her the "Optional Disposable Paper Filters for Reusable K Cups (200/Box)" Delibru recently added to Amazon. [[ASIN:B072M61R6C Optional Disposable Paper Filters for Reusable K Cups (200/Box)]] She called the first day she tried them and said they are perfect for her "picky" guests who do not like the grounds sometimes in the coffee. When we got together yesterday she said they are so much help and keep her from spilling any grounds when she inserts the cup. She couldn't believe how accurately they fit the cups either. So I can update my review saying both DELIBRU CUPS AND FILTERS ARE AWESOME.
I can say from my view as purchaser the company sends emails and coupons and actively supports purchaser's needs.

Another update(8/15/18) I bought a Keurig following the trip to Hawaii and ordered my first Delibru reusable cups in January,2017 so knew I liked them before I got ones for friends. I wanted to note my cups are still in use daily and I have not had any wear out in any way. I noted someone felt certain the mesh would wear out but mine has not in over a year. I love the fresh taste and smell of freshly ground coffee when I fill them, then brew them. I can wash them out easily. My hint there is I use a Q-tip to remove any grounds from inner rim. I also have put an arrow with a permanent black marker to indicate where the cut out for opening the cup is located and a "D" on ones I use for decaf for when I prepare them ahead for a coffee gathering.
title: A perfect gift for coffee lovers with favorite roasts that supports environmental concerns at the same time

text:
We have had the PHS930SLSS GE Profile induction range about 6 months, and are generally very pleased with it. We finally took the plunge into induction cooking, and don't regret it a bit--much happier with it than with the glass top range it replaced.

Of course, you need induction-ready pans, but one thing we didn't realize is that all induction-ready pans are not alike! We noticed that some pans-usually lighter ones--heated up a lot faster than others, so I did a little experiment and found that to boil 16 oz of water took between 1.5 and 4.5 minutes. The fastest times were pricey, quality stainless-clad pans and the slowest were light, inexpensive pans from that Swedish household goods superstore. They work, but just are not as efficient or responsive. I'm assuming that it has to do with the amount of iron or steel in the bottom of the pan.

Here are the Pros for this range:
--Easy to clean top. Because it doesn't get nearly as hot as a radiant glass-top range, all that scraping and scrubbing is gone! Ten times easier to clean than any other range we've owned.
--Stylish, modern design. It's a beautiful appliance.
--Interface of the control panel is excellent. Very intuitive and quick and easy to set.
--Good convection oven. The temperature differential (called "Auto Conversion" in the manual) between convection (usually 25¬∞ lower than non-convection) can be adjusted or eliminated. I turned off the Auto Conversion and the baking times are more realistic. Baking is even, and preheating is not terribly fast but not a problem either.
--The Warming Zone, the middle back "burner," works well. It is thermal, not induction.
--Proofing feature of the oven is handy for bread making.
--The oven probe works well on cooking meats and is easy to set up.
--Visibility into the oven is good.
--Range has internet connectivity, but we do not see a need to turn the oven on or off and set the temperature remotely. A solution looking for a problem. Also, GE asks for a lot of personal information to use the app.

Cons:
--The beeps of the timer and oven preheat are way too soft. Even set at the loudest setting, they can be inaudible.
--The broiler requires that the oven door be closed. Many cooks like to have the door open a bit to broil.
--The glass control panel gets messy because of splatter, and must be turned off in order to wipe it clean...otherwise, the cleaning cloth activates the various controls. Not a big issue, but an inconvenience.
--The oven light stays on forever. I much prefer a time-out on the light after an adjustable time so you don't find the light on the next morning.
--The "soft close" drawer under the oven required some adjustment when we got the range, and it only works when the drawer is within an inch of closing. Just as easy to close it all the way yourself.
--Very few accessories are available. GE only offers broiler pans and more wire oven racks. I would love to see optional deluxe oven racks that have drawer-slide mechanisms which pull all the way out without tilting and maybe spilling oven contents. Many higher-end ranges have these, and I would like GE to offer these as an optional accessory.
--There is a slight hotspot in the middle of each induction burner. This may be the case with all induction ranges, but the evenness of the cooking area could be better. This is mitigated by a quality pan which evens out the heat across the surface of the pan.
--No printed manual. Come on, GE...this kind of money for an appliance and no printed manual?

Even with these cons, it's the best range we've ever owned.
title: Best range we've ever owned

text:
This filter is working out great for me. I got these along with my first AeroPress, and I was not sure if I should have bought the metal filter or if it was just as good to use the paper ones. In any case, I keep using the metal filter even though I have a pile of the little paper ones right there, so I guess I do prefer it! I use the inverted brewing method, so I do not have the issue some people have had with feeling like the coffee goes right through the filter. When I do flip the AeroPress over to press, I would say it is easier to press than with the paper filter, because it is true the metal filter gives less resistance. It still does a great job of filtering the coffee.

One other tip--I have found that if I allow the AeroPress to cool just slightly before cleaning out the grounds, then the grounds do not stick to the metal filter. You can easily just lift the metal filter off of the grounds, and then dump the grounds into your trash or compost. I know the AeroPress guide advises cleaning it immediately before you even take a sip of coffee, but I find it easier to wait just a short amount of time, and hopefully the AeroPress will hold up to that over time. If you are a firm believer in cleaning it immediately, you may find that the grounds stick to the metal filter when they are still very moist and hot.
title: Works great with inverted brewing method

I was looking at building a device from an Arduino that would do this exact thing. I figured if I thought of it, someone else would have too. Lo and behold, there are several options that will monitor temp and humidity and provide controls via relays. This was by far the most affordable option. Turns out, it was the least user friendly too.
I used cheap extension cords and cut them in half to provide the plug ins. This seemed to work well, but I'm not sure if the device is actually working. I think I have it programmed correctly, but without instructions included in the box, there is no way to tell for sure.

If you want to tinker with something and save a couple bucks, give it a shot. Otherwise, save a lot of time and aggravation by getting something that's a little more polished and ready to go.

text: We have had this for a year now. It is fantastic. I was a little concerned when I read the reviews, but decided to buy anyway. For the person who could not bake cookies, I don't know what to say. This over gets hot and cooks very fast. Two choices are either conventional or convection. The convection is 25 degrees less but heats at 25 higher. By that I mean if you would use 350 degrees in a normal oven, you type this on this oven, and it actually uses 325 degrees. I can use metal and foil inside. The inside cobalt blue color is so pretty. There was another review about being able to use burners only high or low. That is not true. You hit high or low and it starts at the highest or lowest temperature. Then you can use the arrows to increase or decrease the temperature from there. It does not come with a cord, so I purchased one because I want a new one. I could have used the one from the old oven, but opted for the new cord. To know which one to get. Look at your current oven and unplug it, then count the prongs. You need a 3 or a 4 prong based on the socket in your wall. Hope this helps you out. This is an outstanding oven and it was so much cheaper on Amazon from Best Sales.

text:
*Update*
I've changed my detergent and no longer see any residue after washing. I am loving this thing. It was a great purchase. I still stand by everything in my review as far as the capacity for regular dishes and regular use, but if you have a very little amount of dishes and keep up with it, you'll love the convenience. Also, if you're into canning, it fits an impressive amount of jars.

*Original*
I'm not entirely sure this purchase was necessary, but I'm enjoying my new toy. I live by myself and work about 13-15 hrs per day 6 days a week so, I'm not home much to create too many dishes. But, the few dishes I do dirty up tend to sit (rinsed) in the sink for a few days before I get the time or energy to wash them. So far, it's been really nice to just rinse and shove in the dishwasher until there's enough to run it. I also really love that I don't have to install it with a water line. It takes a very small amount of water ( I think under a gallon and a half) so it's definitely less than I would use hand washing. I have a very small kitchen, and I like that the footprint is reasonably small. I love that it heats the water internally and has a top and bottom sprayer, as well as a dry program. I had one in my cart that was only $50 cheaper and didn't have a top sprayer, heater, or dry function. I'm really glad I searched around a bit, because I think that $50 extra was well spent. I have noticed that my dishes tend to come out with a bit of a film that I have to polish off, which is why I'm not sure it's quite the time saver I was hoping it would be. Maybe I should just switch my detergent. I've seen reviews where they pile WAY more inside than I do and rave about the cleanliness of the dishes when they come out, so I'm a little confused at that. From my experience, you need to be very careful to position your dishes so the water can actually hit them.

Be aware, it's still just a small dishwasher. It's not a magic portal that zaps food particles into the ether. You will still need to rinse your dishes after using them. I work in a professional kitchen and even our commercial dishwasher isn't that magical. I think this product is for a niche market and will work well for some, but may not suit the average household. Overall, I'm happy. It works very well for my living situation.
title: Works well for me

text: I am very happy with the product. It works! Installation was straight forward. It's 2 screws. What I did was unplug the stove. Removed the door, 2 racks inside, and the warming drawer on the bottom. I had 2 1/4 inch sheet metal screws about 3/8 inch long, in back of the bottom . This is inside the stove. I lifted the back first while sliding the front out. Now you have access to the element. Where the warming drawer goes, toward the back is where it unplugs. Remove the 2 screws and slide the wire out. Place new element to match up screw holes. Reassemble in reverse order. Should take like 20 minutes. So nice to have a oven again. Hope this helps.

text:
We have a built in ice maker in our freezer but it has a very small capacity and it‚Äôs slow so I gave this one a try and we are very happy with the performance. It‚Äôs fairly easy to set up and use. We have a pull out faucet so it‚Äôs very easy to fill, it may be a little tricky to fill it with a pitcher but doable. It makes the ice quickly and quietly, you do hear it but it sounds like a quiet fan running in the background and then you hear the ice being dumped into the ice container, not bad at all. The fit and finish is very nice and appears to be well built. I have the black with rose gold and it looks very nice without too much of the rose gold. It makes 2 sizes of ice cubes, there isn‚Äôt a huge difference in size but there is a difference. It does take up some space on the counter but the dimensions in the description are accurate. The only negative thing is that it has 2 rubber feet in front to keep it from sliding but the rear feet are smooth rounded metal that leaves black marks on out light gray countertop, it does come off with a wet rag but it‚Äôs annoying that every time you move it the countertop needs to be cleaned.
Overall we‚Äôre very happy with the performance of this ice maker.

text: Purchased this several months ago for our small apartment that has shared coin-operated laundry in a dank basement. It has paid for itself more than once since then. The washer has small, medium, and large load marks on the inside. I usually fill it with clothes to the medium mark and then water to the large mark so that the clothes have enough room to move around. Otherwise its too cramped and the clothes will not spin in the washer. Half the clothes from the washer will fit into the spinner. The spinner gets most of the water out of the clothes, they do not drip when placed on a drying rack. This washer seems to get our clothes cleaner than a normal washing machine. If you have close neighbors it is a good idea to put a blanket or towels on the floor and a blanket on top of the washer while it is running so that the neighbors are not annoyed by the sound/vibrations. We live in a very cramped and old apartment building so you may not notice the sound/vibrations as much.
title: Perfect for 1 or 2 People

text:
I am not happy with this refrigerator because it does not refrigerate. I am a residential contractor and ordered this Bull 11001 Stainless Steel under counter refrigerator to use in an outdoor kitchen under a covered patio. Since I used the Bull Stainless gas grill and the Bull Stainless Steel two burner cooktop, I chose the Bull Stainless refrigerator because I mistakenly thought that it would be comparable in quality to the Bull cooking products and to maintain brand continuity. Not good thinking...this refrigerator DOES NOT GET COLD. It runs and gets cool but not cold.

The problem is that due to normal construction delays we did not even open the box until after the return period had expired. The refrigerator has been in use only about 1 month and does not work. Many clients want matching appliances so I may have to change out all of the outdoor appliances because of this poor quality Bull Refrigerator.

I hope Amazon and/or Bull reads this review stands behind their product. As a builder, I have to warranty every component of a new residence for one year...right down to the light bulbs.
title: Inconsistent Bull Quality

text:
Replaced fridge water pump ice maker, ordered and found when delivered that the part was not identical as the original.
Two problems found were the pump intake line fastener was not the same thread size and not the same brass material and the male wire connectors were to small so the fridge factory power plug did not stay on. I had to install new female connector plugs so a modification to my fridge had to be made. Also the intake water supply line was placed on the pump and the supplied fastener was likely missing the teflon ferrule so it leaked constantly. I had a spare ferrule installed it and used the supplied fastener. I did manage to make this work with modifications. Not always is what you see is what you get.
I would likely not do this again I would just shop locally at a brick and mortar store so I can avoid extra work and modifications to my appliances.

text:
For the price, you cannot beat this package of (12) count of Keurig charcoal coffee filters. For years... every time I would see the "replace filter" warning on my Keurig, I would ignore it. It's just too expensive to buy the OEM version of these! Then I found these on Amazon and couldn't pass up the price -- it comes with 12 for practically what you would pay for 1 of the Keurig brand!

Well I now replace my filters EVERY time I'm prompted and I don't feel like I'm throwing money down the drain to do it. I think it has made a marginal improvement in the taste of my coffee and I also feel good knowing that I'm doing "something" rather than "nothing".

Contract to other reviewers, they fit snug and securely in the Keurig attachment and seem to be made of a durable material. I purchased these directly from Amazon (not a third party seller) so that could be the difference between positive and negative reviews. I would DEFINITELY recommend these for anyone who is looking for a cheap alternative to the name brand version of coffee filters.
title: Economical replacement for OEM filters

text:
I, like others, dithered for nearly a year before making the decision to purchase this appliance. I'd been getting by with a hand-cranked "Wonder Washer" but an increase in weekly laundry made using that option a bit onerous. I read all the reviews here several times, and Lou's wonderful report with video is pretty doggone accurate and was the thing that finally pushed me over the edge (after reading/watching it five or ten times!).

The box containing the appliance arrived in good shape--it was purchased from Amazon and shipped via Target--but for those trying to hide their purchase from their landlord, the box had a large picture of the machine on it in full color. It wasn't an anonymous beige box, not by a long shot.

I followed the instructions (using tips I'd picked up from reading all these Amazon reviews) and got the thing set up toute suite. I agree that having an electric drill makes putting on the bottom plate much easier--it went on without too much fuss and lined up well, but I could see where doing it manually might be a bit of a 'drill,' pardon the expression. I had zero difficulty with the hoses--didn't need to move the discharge hose from one side to another, so that was a plus, and the washing machine 'fill' hose screws on with no drama. The fittings to hook the hose to the faucet went on an underused sink in the bathroom with no issues. The hose clips on the faucet fitting snugly with no leaks.

I have to say that I can't believe how WELL this machine works. Despite its small size, it can do a decent load of wash--just don't pack the stuff in and don't be greedy. A normal cycle is just over a half hour, and the clothes come out quite clean. For people who are complaining that their spin cycle isn't working or they have water remaining in their machine, I would suggest they ensure that their machine is level before assuming it's defective. My machine spins my clothing so well that everything is dry in no time on an outdoor line, and the polyester stuff is almost dry as I pull it out of the machine. My machine is also quite quiet--and I'm betting this is because I have it positioned on a level surface.

If I had anything to gripe about, I'd say the smell of the hose is pretty nasty at first blush. It smells like burnt 'something or other.' The stink does dissipate over time, though, and it's not enough of a sticking (or stinking) point to cause me to lower my five-star grade on this item.

The price of this beauty has come down a good deal since I first started coveting it, and the price I paid was around two hundred bucks plus state tax (the order fulfiller, Target, does business in my state). So far, I have no complaints as to the delivery, the way the machine works, or the price. I wish I'd bought this thing sooner!

I am editing this review to add that I've had this item about a month, now, and I am even happier with it today than I was after the first week! When I think of the number of times I threw ten to fifteen bucks at a fetid laudromat, I regret having dithered about making this purchase. The "hose stink" I mentioned above is totally gone, the machine is doing a dozen loads a week without breaking a sweat, and I am overjoyed with it. At this rate it will pay for itself in no time.

UPDATE: I've now owned this machine for five and a half years (my, how time flies). text: This is the second Capmesso pod I've purchased.  I have the original pod with screw top, which works good. First pic shows my first espresso made from nespresso pod, and the resultant crema in the cup.  I then tried the Capmesso top on the pod (which, btw, is a struggle to get the foil film off of!!), which I had filled with a Turkish coffee grind I had.  I got about 5 drips out of the cycle,  and realized the Turkish grind was too fine, water was not going through the pod.  So refilled with a regular, slightly fine, grind of my normal drip coffee.  Second picture shows the result.  Just slightly less crema, might be due to the grind, but worked great and the strength of the espresso was par with the actual nespresso pod.  Good on, Capmesso!
