text:
LG instructions are to reuse the flange nuts from the original rollers. Unfortunately they are the wrong size thread. They will bind up and the cheep axil meatal of the replacements will rip. I returned the broken set and purchased again. Kind of needed the dryer working again. When the next set came in I measured the axil thread and it is M10x1.5. If you buy this for your dryer double check the axil thread size and pitch of your original parts before reusing the original flange nuts.

The better option would be for the replacement part seller to include the correct flange nuts (and washers) in the package. Outside of that I do like the roller bearing verses the original axil and sleeve design. The second set of these are installed and working well.

Side note while everything is accessible vacuum out everything!!!
title: If you buy this buy four M10x1.5mm flange nuts as well.

text: Good price, fast shipping.

We put this in with our new kitchen cabinets and appliances. All in all, it's quite a deal. The fan is powerful and effective, and smooth running. The stainless steel is solid, as is the general construction. The lights, as everyone has commented, are a joke. Just for decoration really. Don't know how easy it would be to replace them as they are LEDs and in a sealed container.

The contractor had to get the upper sleeve trimmed down at a metal shop in order to fit our low (91-inch) Cape-style ceilings. I wanted the lowest part of the hood to be at least 69 inches off the ground to avoid collisions with my forehead. So some trimming was necessary. It contains a much more powerful fan (turbo-style) for far less money than the ones sold by the big-name appliance makers. And with a little ingenuity I think this hood can be adapted to almost any situation. The fan has a very smooth sound, and electronic controls are nice too. There are 3 clearly marked speeds. If you hit the off button, it gives you a 1-minute delay before turning off. If you want it off right away, hit the speed-button that you used to turn it on, or hit the off-button twice. Very simple and intuitive. The stainless steel is solid, but the usual pain in the A to keep clean. (Glad we got the new Smudge-proof stainless finish on our Frigidaire appliances. It shows a lot less fingerprints.)

I would have preferred a slightly less space-age style, but I didn't see anything more appropriate. We got cherry cabinets in a deep red/brown wood finish and stainless appliances for a kind of mixed traditional/modern style. Maybe the similar AKDY model with the flat glass would have worked better . . . Should'a, could'a, would'a. That's my refrain for the first 6 to 8 months on all home improvement projects. After a year I get used to it, and wonder why I ever wanted anything different. Same with new clothes.
title: Solid and works great, though lights are just for decoration

text:
Ok, so sometimes sure... I like just poppin' in a k-cup and havin' a cup of coffee. Sometimes, my budget disagrees with me and I get the bagged coffee. Sometimes, I can't find the K-cup in the type of coffee I want! So, this lil scoop is awesome. I've had absolutely no issues using it. I also use it as a measurement scoop to fill spice bags that I make. I need approximately 3 TBSP in those, (this scoop is 2 TBSP) so one and a half scoops with this of my seasoning mix and I can fill those bags.

TIP: The handle of the scoop has a hollow dip, so if you dip your scoop too deep into the coffee you are going to get grounds in that empty space. If you do all of that, when you flip it over to dump out the contents of the scoop you will spill. It's pretty easy to avoid though. Good luck!

text:
I ordered this filter back in February, 2016 as a potential replacement for a GE MWF filter in my refrigerator. I did not install the unit into my refrigerator until the beginning of July. Approximately 3 weeks after installation - my water dispenser began making loud, horrific, grinding noises whenever the water would flow - either to fill the ice maker or through the water dispensing unit on the door.

As I had never had an issue with this before I changed filters - I opted to purchase another genuine GE filter to see if it was the filter or the water mechanism itself.

This proved to be a great illustration of the line, "you get what you pay for..." Immediately upon installation of the GE filter - the noise stopped and has not been heard since!

This unit may be about half the price of the GE product - but it isn't worth the box it's shipped in!

I called support - spoke to a guy for 10 minutes. Carefully explained the issue. The guy had no clue how to do his job and couldn't tell me which $100+ part was failing. So his last ditch effort to get out of doing his job was was to send me a new blower assembly (even though my unit was out of warranty). He asked me, "how long have you had the unit." My response was, "about 2 years." He said since it was close to the 1 year warranty, he was going to send me the part free of charge... Great news! All I had to do was send him my receipt and a photo of the serial number. I sent him the Amazon receipt and the photo to his email address. I get a response about an hour later: "I'm sorry sir, but I will not be able to send out the repair parts for you. The range hood only has a one year warranty and I was stretching it when you told me that it was only two years old. The receipt shows it is actually just over 2-1/2 years old. The blower assembly is part number SV08097 and it includes the motor, blower wheel, scroll housing, & capacitor. You can get this part through our Customer Service Department at 800-558-1711."

Thanks for the support! So because he cant do his job, I should buy a $300 assembly and a $500 fan motor for a $600 hood I bought 2 and half years ago? Yeah, no thanks team Broan. They need to hire better support staff.

text: Makes a good strong brew. Unlike My K-Cup they fit directly into the Cuisinart Single Serve Brewing system. Also unlike the My K-Cup filter, they have caps which allow you to add more coffee in each filter without spillage resulting in a bolder brew. The caps also allow you to fill and store the loaded filters in advance. It is unfortunate that a convenient, sealable container that will contain six coffee filled filters is not available. As the filters are porous, if not kept in a sealed container, you can smell the coffee. The odour you smell is the volatile coffee flavor escaping. Not desirable and exacerbated the longer filled filters are left exposed to the air.

text:
Our dryer moves across the laundry room floor once in awhile, I‚Äôve narrowed it down to three things. 1. The cats are hiring movers help them get their toys out from under it. 2. Ghosts. 3. It‚Äôs walking because it‚Äôs unbalanced when overloaded. Though it hasn‚Äôt done that before moving to this house and it‚Äôs usually washers that do that‚Ä¶.Hmmmmmm

I ruled out the cats hiring movers with 100% certainty pretty quickly, and the jury is still out with the ghosts overall, so with number 3 as the logical explanation I ordered these to solve the problem and we‚Äôve had no more mysterious shifting of laundry appliances.

They were easy to install in relation to having to totally move the appliances and available space to work, which will vary for each buyer. All in all it was easy, hubs could have done it by himself but I wanted to use the opportunity to clean back there and reclaim all the colorful little plastic spring cat toys underneath while the appliances were moved, so I helped by installing them while he lifted the corners of the appliances. We could have just put them on the dryer, but since the set included 8 we put them on the washer as well.

text:
This filter is solid replacement for the original filter that came with our AirCare 1201 MA1201. It's easily installed and a perfect fit. We're on our second replacement filter this year using this exact brand and would tell you if your humidifier seems like it just can't keep up like it did when it was new, swap out your filter and see instant results. The only real knock I have with this filter is the longevity--the original humidifier filter (using the same tap water) lasted nearly a whole winter season. These replacement filters are luck to last a month before becoming mineral saturated to the point where water apparently doesn't wick very well. We are using a vinegar/water cleaning solution as other reviews have suggested to clean these filters which seems to work fairly good at restoring the filter to usability. We add a couple of cups of vinegar to approx. 3 gallons of water in a 5 gallon bucket and then totally submerge the filter leaving it overnight. Rinse, dry, and the filter is ready to use again.

All in all, this is a good filter despite its longevity issues at a fair price. The cleaning vinegar rinse is a good mitigation strategy to increase the filter's useful life but can be a hassle in the winter.
title: Great Initial Performance But Mineral Clogs Quickly Shorten Life Span

Stopped working within 24 hours.

Tried everything from restarting the unit, to letting the ice melt and restart from scratch, to forcibly pulling the ice with pliers. Same result.

Don't buy. Nothing of this is even mentioned in the troubleshooting FAQ. Called the manufacturer. LITERALLY told me that since this "error was not found in troubleshooting FAQ in manual, they could not honor warranty."

Luckily bought through Amazon and full refund. SO HAPPY IT HAPPENED WITHIN THE 30 DAY REFUND WINDOW FOR AMAZON. DO NOT BUY.

text:
I have mixed feelings on this product.

On positive side: It is made of 0.7mm stainless steel, has baffled filter, has rather good two squirrel cage 3-speed AC motors which are not as quiet as I expected, but OK compared to my NuTone range hood, it has quality mechanical design and good screws. Certainly NOT "Ultra Quiet", but acceptable.

On negative side: it has too dim, non-replaceable LED lights with a bit blue ("daylight") color that barely illuminate the range surface and make meats look a bit un-fresh - absolutely unacceptable for the kitchen. Certainly NOT "Ultra Bright". I thought that it comes with GU10 halogen bulbs which I can immediately replace, but... read entire review. Its baffle filter has mounting notches that leave to thin metal strip which breaks apart - one of the filters I got was broken, and another shows that it was broken and then welded in the weak place. And I expected it to be even a bit more quiet.

When I was looking for the range hood, I wanted the following features (scores for this hood in brackets): under cabinet (ok), sturdy nice looking stainless steel (ok), <40 dBA at 150cfm (close to OK), squirrel cage fans (ok) with brushless DC motors (not ok) and variable electronically controlled speed (not OK), with bright warm white LED lights (not OK) and ability to replace bulbs (not ok), and with complete disconnect on/off switch (not OK) and at price point of $250 (OK). All these features are doable today at the specified price point, but I could find only this one which was closest.

The first thing I did is replaced the LED lights with 7W 450 lm MR16 12V LED bulbs naively. It was possible although the seating for the bulb is made incompatible and the retaining ring cannot be used. I immediately had perfect illumination of the range. But it causes overload of the 12V supply transformer (? why they decided to use 12V bulbs when 120V LEDs are available?) and the power transformer burned out. These proud Cycene designers were not thinking enough. When I disassembled it (assembly quality was very good), I found that it has provisions for two types of bulbs - 120V AC and 12V DC. 12V DC max current is 0.5A total. So I did the work for them and upgraded it to 12V switcher supply for controls and relays, and used GU10 120V 7W warm while led bulbs now which ARE "Ultra Bright" and fit perfectly into the mounting holes and retaining rings, and have no limitation on power. It costed me $5 for sockets and $7 for bulbs. This upgrade eliminated design deficiencies and now I have a nice range hood.

The other thing is the clock - it runs away by 15mins a day. I did not pay attention to it first, but it is really annoying to have several clocks in the house showing different time. The deeper inspection shows that the microcontroller, BS82D20, does not have crystal oscillator enabled due to firmware bug(!), although the crystal is installed on the board. I think that these designers were D-graders in college or simply had no experience. Wonder how it went into production unnoticed!

Summary: If you are an electrical engineer and can do the some rework, you may buy it as a base kit to work on. If you want to just use it "as is", don't buy!
title: A kit for parts to do custom upgrade. Light is too weak for cooking and does not make meat look fresh.

My daughter bought me the 2.0 cup for Christmas that works almost perfectly - I've only once gotten the "error" message using it (I'll call it Version 1.) I wanted to buy a second one and so ordered it from Amazon. Version 2 is slightly different - it is a darker more purple color, the 'hinge' is noticeably wider, and it often (maybe 50% of the time) causes the dreaded Keurig error message. Version 1 fits snugly into the machine and once seated it cannot be rotated or twisted; Version 2 sort of sits on top of the insert and can be rotated about 20 - 25 degrees out of place. When it fails I have to reinsert it one (or several) times; the Keurig eventually cooperates but it is a bit frustrating. And yes, I've cleaned/cleared the camera repeatedly.

I'd have returned it had I known it was going to be problematic, but I'd already thrown out the packaging so I'm stuck with it and I find myself avoiding using it and using the "good one."

text:
Purchased this to overcome the dreaded "dE" error when I tried to start a washer cycle. Got tired of banging on the door/opening closing, pressing "start/stop" over and over to do a single load of laundry. This is the exact part replacement for my LG Tromm WM1812CW. So far, (with about 5 loads of laundry), I've not noticed any problems at all with the new part. So that either means that I had a faulty Door Lock sensor, or something else was going on. Either way, no issues with this part.

As someone mentioned, you can replace it by only unscrewing 6 screws total (4 for the top to slide the top of the washing machine off, and 2 that hold this part in place. However, it's a pretty tight space to reach down into. I'm 6'4 and didn't have any problems reaching the part to replace it, but it was fiddly to actually replace. The cable connector was the hard part. There's a small lever-lock on the connector, just make sure it's depressed before you start to separate the connector from the latch. It's fiddly, and I had to wiggle it for a few minutes, but be persistent, and it does eventually unlatch without problems. New part fit just fine, reinstalled, and no more "dE" errors. So, bonus!

It _might_ be easier to replace with the LG tool that is sold separately, but it's probably not required. As someone else said, un-doing the rubber gasket wasn't something I wanted to tackle. That seems like something I wouldn't want to mess with on this kind of device.
title: Exact part replacement for WM1912CW LG Tromm

text:
I read some of the negative reviews and gave this a try anyway. Fearing that I may end up getting a used repackaged product (as mentioned in some of the negative reviews) I made sure to pick up a TDS* water meter/tester as well. Not only to make sure I got a new filter from this seller, but also so I can test the various liquids used around my home.

As I'd mentioned in my review for the TDS* water meter/tester, my tap water is hard so I used the baseline measurement (PPM's) of a bottle of Poland Spring water. My main concern about this filter or my refrigerator water line in general, was that it wasn't going to make too much of a difference drinking water from the tap versus one that came out of this filter. After my baseline measurements, my concerns were put at ease.

Below are results from my tests:

(measurements in PPM)
0-50 = Ideal drinking water
50-100 = Carbon filtered water
100-200 = Hard water
200-300 = Marginally acceptable
200-400 = Average tap water
400+ Very high TDS contaminant level

--My household baseline--
Bottle of Poland Spring = 18
Tap Water = 281
Gatorade = 260
5 month old filter from my refrigerator water line = 240
New filter from my refrigerator water line = 200
Melted ice (4 hours) = 293

So what did I learn from this... My tap water isn't too bad, this particular filter can probably go another month or two, and I really need to clean my ice maker. The good news is that this filter removed 80+PPM's of TDS* from my tap.

*TDS* - Total Dissolved Solids are the total amount of mobile charged ions, including minerals, salts, or metals dissolved in a given volume of water.
title: Good, but could be better.

text: Well, if this is not the best ~$15 we've ever spent for acoustic peace!  The original kit (Kitchenaid KUDL02FRSS2) screamed its displeasure EVERY TIME the door was opened or closed.  How irritating!  The original part had ONE pulley and a solid, fixed cam with a channel in it that got so LOUD that it was driving us nuts!  This replacement part has TWO pulleys, how innovative of them... why wasn't it this way to begin with???  On install, we lubed both pulleys liberally with white lithium grease, along with the contact point for the washer end, string pivot, and VOILA! quiet, Quiet, QUIET!  Peace at last, peace at last... grateful, VERY grateful!!!

text:
I bought one pack for my Bosch dishwasher because I wasn‚Äôt sure if these would work. I have been having issues with the lower rack for years. The wheels are constantly falling off the track and no one in the family except for me was ever able to get the rack in the dishwasher. This is a known problem with the 800 series Bosch dishwasher and when I contacted them, their solution was that I needed to contact a servicer. I am not impressed with their customer service at all. Having to pay someone $100 to look at my dishwasher for something that is a hugely common and known issue with these dishwashers is not a solution in my opinion.

So I ordered a pack of these and installed them on the first and last wheel axles on each side of the rack. I noticed that these wheels actually are a little wider than the Bosch ones and now my rack no longer jumps off track! I can‚Äôt believe that this works so well! text:
A question about using this with a gas dryer was asked. A reviewer answered that is was ok for a gas dryer. It is absolutely not safe for a gas dryer. Combustion by-products are exhausted through the dryer vent, along with humid air. This is unsafe for use with a gas dryer! I have ordered this product for my electric dryer, and will update this review after using the product. My review is for use with a gas dryer only, not for the product itself at this time.

I received and am using the dryer vent. I works well, with only minor problems. There is the humidity/ humid type smell and the heat that is produced. It does allow
venting indoor of electric dryers. Summer would not work well at all with this item.
The screen is fine enough to filter the lint quite nicely. It is made of plastic, so there is some minor deformity from the heat, but very little dust/lint leakage. The screen cleaning rotating scraper works, and the small amount of water in the bottom does catch the lint. This can solve some problems, without making more problems. However, no one will want to use this in summer, without air-conditioner and a dehumidifier running at the same time.
title: NOT FOR GAS DRYER

text:
If your washing machine vibrates and "walks", you must get this product. We were skeptical at first, but it really does the job. The washer is MUCH quieter and doesn't walk a few inches with every load. The tricky part is the installation. Keep in mind that we are senior citizens and the install required my husband to tilt the machine while I'm on the floor with a grabber getting the cushions on the washer feet. Once we figured out the rear pads, the front ones were pretty easy. That's the reason for only 2 stars on installation. If you're young, it shouldn't be a problem.

We looked (on-line) at Lowe's, and they did have a similar product at double the price. I'm not into over paying for things.

I'm not sure if the product description or a review mentioned that the pads raise the machine about 2". Mine was about 1.5". If you're okay with that, it's not a problem. The single set will keep your washer from vibrating as much. We did order a second set to raise the dryer. My chest freezer is also in the laundry room and I use the tops of the machines as a staging area when I need to get an item from the bottom of the freezer. The baskets that I use work better on an even surface. But for the fact that I use the tops of my washer and dryer for other things, the slight height difference isn't a problem. It doesn't affect the ability of the pads to stop the washer.

We should have had these years ago!

text: For years I've been disgruntled at purchased de-humidifiers and their lousy humidity control.  The sensors in these products are sloppy at best and often fail over time.  The key to this controllers effectiveness is the very accurate sensor itself, the rest is just common sense digital control.  The available options and settings for controlling the dehumidifier are top shelf!  This also works with humidifiers so am looking forward to doing some testing this winter.  I FINALLY know exactly what the humidity level is in my basement and rest assured my power consumption to maintain my desired humidity is minimized.  (you can even "calibrate" this controller if you have a known good dry bulb kit or similar) Yes, the set-up is somewhat confusing, but if you have a basic understanding of humidity and hysteresis settings, it's a breeze, and easily adjustable at any time you desire.  For the price, this is an amazing control, and I would highly recommend it to anyone wanting better humidity control in any environment.  I've had it running for a month now 24/7 with no problems.
title: Sincerely Amazing Humidity Control Product!

text:
I'm not a fan of my samsung washing machine because it's broken down far too much since we purchased it 6 years ago. It was overpriced, often is unbalanced and this is the second time this year that i've changed the washer drain pump assembly. The last time i had to order the part and it cost twice the price. Probably because it was a samsung part. This doesn't seem like it is, however, it's half the price and so far works well. My last part lasted about 8 months so time will tell... I do a lot of laundry (at least 1-2 loads per day). I'll update this post should i have issues.

For folks wondering if this is a "big job" left for repair technicians - the answer is NO. I am a mom that works full time, watches some YouTube videos and with a little elbow grease, changed this myself. It took some time the first time (about an hour) so that i could clean up the water that spilled all over the floor from being stuck in the machine. The second time (last week) it took me 10 minutes to change this bad boy out (after the clean up). It is simple and to pay a technician $650 (yes - that is right... that is what they wanted to charge me for repairing my machine.

A little elbow grease and $50 and you should be set. Just know that you'll know its the drain pump when your washer turns on and you hear a buzz. Nothing happens to the water even if you just hit spin... Most times it's the pump but could be a clog (both times for me it's the pump). Good luck!!!!

I also will say that the package was shipped SUPER fast. I had it within 2-days. I do live in the same state it's shipped from - NY, however, it was shipped quickly, packed well and a seamless transaction.
title: Perfect for my failing washing machine

text:
Cost: $35.95 plus $9.99 shipping. Purchased seven months ago when our in-house filter no longer vented to the outside and we were unable to repair at that time. This was easy to install and sits on top of our dryer. It is made in China so is overpriced for what you get and subsequent issues. Was well-packaged and arrived undamaged.

Pros: works well indoors as it keeps lint from going throughout the house; use proper grade venting duct for safety reasons as the air gets very hot.

Cons: Plastic construction with wire mesh screen attached to inside of removable panel. Bottom drawer which holds water does not stay closed after a few months' use and I have to keep drawer in place with rubber bands. The handle does not remove most of the lint so I do it by hand.

Our laundry room is in the middle of our our home and our thermostat is located on the wall directly outside the laundry room. Poor planning on someone's part! I do not keep the laundry room door closed while the dryer is working and as the dryer now vents hot air inside the home, it causes false readings on the thermostat so we have to make frequent adjustments for heating/cooling.

My biggest issue is quality does not match high cost. It does the job which is to trap lint. That's the most positive thing I can say. If we are unable to eventually have the original up the wall, through the attic and outside vent replaced, and I find myself needing another indoor unit, I will check other options before purchasing this again.
title: Overpriced, but does an ok job

text:
We've had Aprilaire humidifiers for 15 years. Last September our contractor installed the 700 series replacing the 400 series. While the humidification is good
(35-37) on cold days in DC for a 3200 ft house the WATER usage is excessive
The contractor estimated 11 gal per day the actual usage has been 88 gal per day
Most of which is wasted down the drain
This is terribly wasteful and expensive
($40/mo) of wasted water here in DC.
I'm astonished that Aprilaire hasn't designed some sort of water saving but safe solution to this obvious engineering problem. While we don't want to go back to a reservoir style system that we had years ago we are looking at alternatives to replace the new Aprilaire 700 that are more environmentally (less wasteful) friendly but effective. I gave it 3 stars because it does the job but does it inefficiently and it's expensive to operate
By the way we had the water valve turned down to a minimum trickle but the install instructions call for a wide open valve
Which may use considerably more water

text: I foster dogs and cats, especially during the colder months. I used to bring their bed covers to the laundromat about 15-20' driving from my home. Also, we adopted one of our foster dogs, she is old and she gets jealousy with just about any other animals around us (including the cat we have had for 5 years). For all that reasons, I keep my foster baby at 1 or 2 only and they stay at the back house. I got this washer/dryer combo to wash their bed covers which usually are old bed sheets. This washer fits about 2-3 king sized bedsheets depending how thick the materials are. The dryer, though, would only be comfortable to fit just one king sized bed sheet. I expected that already so I don't mind. I hang dry them under sun anyway. We have 4acres lot so sun is everywhere even during the winter :) that was my intend from the beginning to save electric. Of course, buying a standard sized washer, maybe even an used one from the FB Marketplace, would be even cheaper than buying this whole set and fits a lot more to wash at one time BUT my back house is not designed to set up a regular washer so yes, that was the very main reason I chose these compact washer/dryer. They serve their purpose, though. They are very easy to use as well and do not take too much space, obviously. I have had them for over a month and they are still running great every week. text:
I have so many different flavors of coffee and teas it was hard to remember which row I had what flavor when filling. I didn‚Äôt think it was going to be possible for me to accomplish what I wanted without putting nail polish or paint on the plastic so that I would always remember what flavors were in the kcups. This solved almost all my problems. It comes with 7 colors and I was able to fill all of them and color coordinate so it‚Äôs easier for me to determine what I have. They have all worked nicely. Out of all the sets I bought I did have one that had a couple that came crushed, but Amazon was insanely quick to replace and took care of the issue.

The ONLY downside is my carousel holds 8 different colors and the set only comes with 7. But that isn‚Äôt the fault of the company and has nothing to do with THIS product. The brown ones pictures were the only ones I have found in this color and sadly those ones have not been able to seal after using only once. So I will still be on the lookout for one more unique color besides the traditional purple or black.

Overall I have been in love. This has solved the problem I had with organizing all my flavored drinks. Now I don‚Äôt have to guess or open one up every time to figure out what it is. I use a filter in them because teeccino is much heavier than coffee so it‚Äôs harder to clean these pods, but with a filter everything just comes right out easily. The flavor is nice and bold still and so far I haven‚Äôt had any issues with it fitting in my moms b40 kuerig nor in my K-elite. Once I get another carousel or if more colors come out, I will buy again. Maybe a set of 7 pastels? text:
I have a Whirlpool, Jenn-Air JGC9430BDB Gas burner cooktop. Over time, gunk causes the burners to spark and not ignite, or a different burner sparks. The screws on the burners simply broke off. Rather than pay $60 for a single Jenn-Air JGC9430BDB Head with Electrode, I purchased these ignitors. I had to grind off a portion (using a Dremel tool) to get the ignitor to fit. I had a hard time getting a screw in, because the old screw was broken off inside the burner. I tried drilling out the old screw with little success. I was able to get a few turns on a new screw, enough to create a ground for the ignitor. I was glad to find these ignitors and they saved me from buying a new $500 cook top.
These ignitors feel very light, compared to the OEM. The OEM have a ceramic insulator, which has become brittle and just crumbles. These worked for me.

text:
I was renovating my kitchen and needed a new "island" range hood. The previous vent hood that I had was only good from one side. I saw this one and it looked perfect. Rest assured that what you see is what you get - only it looks even better in my kitchen (see picture).
Sadly, I cannot give you many installation tips, because I had an expert installer put it in for me, who was an expert in all of the "trades", but I did watch and help a little. The end result was more beautiful than I imagined. He did mention that the installation manual was vague, the picture on front didn't even match my model, and I think the instructions say to mount it to the sheetrock - which we didn't think was nearly sturdy enough. It's a heavy, steel piece, so we came up with a new plan. He built a wood box frame, with the thickness of three 2"x4"'s, and secured that in my attic, and attached my new range hood to it. I could practically swing from it, now (but don't try that at home). We also used almost all of our own screws - with the renovation going on, I had plenty of additional hardware and tools on hand.
Because my ceiling was lower (8ft) in the kitchen, our unit didn't need such a long "neck" - but the 2 steel rectangular sleeves that come with it are meant to be "nested", so we had to cut both pieces almost in half but, because my installer was an expert, he made it look great - as you can see by the picture!
If you must have something blocking your newly opened view (we tore down a wall, between the kitchen and living room), then it should be this beauty!
It has 4 well-placed lights, one on each corner, for "full food disclosure" - it really lights up my stove top!. As a personal preference, I've already replaced my little lights with the LED white light version of the bulbs, because I like more white light and less yellow light - purely my choice - but I wanted people to know that replacement bulbs are easy to find. I bought them right off the shelf at my local hardware store, in the specialty lighting area.
All 4 speed settings of the fan work great and, of course, the higher the setting, the noisier the fan - but the more vacuum power you'll get, for getting rid of the smoke (not that I ever burn anything)(maybe once or twice) (a month). The lower speeds are pretty quiet compared to my old "hoody".
My old vent hood had knobs and it had 3 speeds, 1). noisy, 2). super noisy, 3). noisiest...I SAID NOISIEST!
This one is a touchscreen and I really like it. It looks super clean and modern and it is everything I expected and more. I would highly recommend this!
title: It works just as great as it looks!

text: I bought one of these because I want to be more verdant in my life and throwing those little K-cups in the trash just seems wasteful and environmentally wrong.  So, I ordered it and lo-and-behold it didn't work worth a dang. It leaked around the top and spewed hot water everywhere.  It is important to tighten the cap all the way.  The problem as I saw it was that the gray insert didn't seal well against the top input nozzle.  So, I found a suitably sized o-ring at Home depot that would slide up the base of the reusable cup.  It only sits below the cap about a mm.  But just enough to push it up against the upper pin so that the top of the reusable cap seals against the top of the Keurig Brewer (tighter to the water input nozzle).  Now it brews perfectly.  No leaks , no mess, and a fresh cup o' java every time.  After experimenting and being satisfied with my fix, I applied 3 small dollops of super glue to the outside of the reusable base so the o-ring is semi-permanently attached.  Jeez, you'd think the mfg or the after-marketer of this reusable filter could figure this out and design the extra mm necessary to make it fit more snuggle against the nozzle.  Bottom line,  I've had the $20 reusable filter for a week, and even though I read some reviews dissing the robustness of the filter, I think it is a good buy, and it should last quite a while if you just handle it with a little care.

text:
**Six month update: spinning drum will no longer spin which leaves me with half a washing machine. Rating would be two stars if customer support offered ANY help, but instead told me because I've had it more than four months that I'm SOL. Still, it was nice while it lasted.

I've currently washed about 10 "loads" in this washer and first impressions are that it's a great alternative to running to the laundromat or forking over $6 at the apartment's coin-op machines.
My typical washer load is two pairs of pants of either denim or scrub pants, a few pairs of underwear/socks, and two shirts. I need to spin dry them in three separate batches, however, but you can spin and wash at the same time so it isn't so bad.

Pros - convenient! I don't need to leave my apartment to wash mine and my girlfriend's clothes! We need to do laundry a little more often than with a standard washer/dryer but as long as we hang up the spun-dry clothes the night before they are good as new the next morning.
Another pro is it's pretty simple to use! The instructions were very clearly not written by a native English speaker but it is pretty straightforward - put your clothes in, put your detergent in, fill about 1/2 - 3/4 with water, set it to wash for 15 minutes then drain. Now refill with water and put in fabric softener and wash for another 5 minutes. Drain the water one more time then move a small batch of wet clothes to the spin dryer (wring out as much water as you can before this step if it's having problems spinning) and let it do its thing for two or three spin cycles of 5 minutes just make sure to move around the clothes each spin. Hang up the almost dry clothes overnight and tomorrow morning you'll have clean laundry!

Cons - loud! This machine rumbles and vibrates a LOT. A lot to the point where I place it on top of a few stacked bath mats to try to soften the sound it makes on the apartment beneath me. With the door closed and it in the adjacent room it is no louder than your standard washer/dryer machines but it can only handle about 1/3 of the total clothes at a time.
Another con is it uses quite a bit of water. Thankfully my landlord covers water but I could see this being a little wasteful especially if you use a lot of detergent/fabric softener.
Lastly the amount of clothes it can fit can be a problem. For someone who wears a lot of thick clothes or jeans this washer will slow down your laundry adventures but for my work clothes that are scrubs? This thing is FANTASTIC. I don't have much confidence that this washer can handle much bedding however.

After crunching some numbers this portable washing machine is a pretty safe investment of around $200 if your laundromat/apartment washer/dryers are $6 a load like mine are.

I give this gadget four clean socks out of five.
title: Six months for machine to break. Customer support was not helpful.

text:
This fit our Frigidaire/Electrolux stove very well, even though it was not listed for that application. The wire connections are angled slightly differently, but this made no difference in useability in my stove after a minor adjustment to the arrangement. It works as well as the original, but this one was significantly less expensive the standard replacement.

Replacing these surface elements is surprisingly simple. BE SURE TO UNPLUG YOUR STOVE, OR TURN OF THE CIRCUIT BREAKER FIRST, because some of the wires on the element have power all the time, as I was surprised to find out. Just remove two screws on the front of the oven, and lift the stovetop like the hood of a car, and prop it open with a stick of some kind. Look closely at style of wire connections you have, in order to make sure that you buy the least expensive element that will fit the size of your wire terminals. I had to re-arrange a few screws to make this element line up with my mounting clips, because it wasn't the factory original part that I could have bought for my stove. After about 5 minutes work with a screwdriver to move the mounting clips (the new element came with the screw holes already drilled in it), this element snapped right in place just like the original, for about half the price, and no service charge or appointment.

text: There are times when the ice maker on the refrigerator can't keep up with our ice needs. Usually that's when we're entertaining or going out and taking the cooler somewhere. This counter top ice maker will hopefully make life easier. We set this up and followed the directions. It didn't take long before we started making ice. It is a slow process. It took about 2 hours to fill the ice basket. This isn't something you can just start doing to get a lot of ice right away. However, if you plan in advance, it should be fine. We will start making ice the night before it's needed then bag it up and put it in the freezer. I love that this maker recycles the melted water. That's a great idea! While it is noisy, it's more of a white noise than anything else. We found it to not be distracting. We like the shapes of the ice cubes. My husband thought it would be nice if the front of the maker was see through so you could see how much ice you have without having to peer down into it. Overall, this works well and makes decent ice cubes.

text: No issues with it. I read a lot of online reviews on multiple replacement filters available for my fridge, and took the leap of faith on this one. It was the best reviewed, and I'm pilling on. I looked at the OE filter vs. this one, and the differences seem to be the square center hole vs. round and the burst pressure rating.  Regarding the square center hole: it is not the sealing interface the best I can tell, and it relies on the dimensions of the O-ring and outer diameter for seal-ability. I think if you change the filter once the fridge light comes on, you don't need to worry about the burst pressure rating, and its a mute point.  As for taste; I ran the water 3 times into a 32 oz. container and tossed it. Water tastes no different than the OE filter.  Bottom line: don't spend the money on the OE filter when this particular one is available.

text:
We were trying to stop feeding the global commerce machine and support our local community, so we decided to stop ordering capsules from Nespresso and give these reusable capsules a go. After a couple of false starts we've come to find the proper amount of espresso to put in the capsule for the water to flow freely yet still deliver a decent cup of coffee. Don't tamp down espresso grounds as that will block the flow and make your machine stuggle to deliver the water! Instead fill the capsule to a couple of millimeters below the top and let the lid apply the final compression.

Note: A top tip before you use up your last nespresso capsule, cut it open and inspect the fill and grind of their coffee. It's definitely not as fine as proper espresso grind but communicating that to grinders is tricky. We've found the Illy espresso roast grounds (in the metal canisters) to be the best store bought match, and gives very good results, but of course they don't tick the locally sourced box for fresh ground coffee).
title: Reusable capsules means local coffee sourcing and local coffee grounds composting

text:
I spent a lot of time researching products that would monitor my house for times we would be away during the winter months to avoid the disaster of frozen pipes. I considered Nest-type connected thermostats, but finally decided the risk of failure was too great. I just wanted to be alerted if the house temperature dropped to dangerous levels. Then I could call a neighbor or an HVAC company.

This product has performed perfectly. I can check the house temperature over the internet at any time, and if the temperature should drop below my set point, it alerts me. Exactly what I needed and simple to install and set up. The one call I did make to the manufacturer was answered fast and a helpful tech walked me through the solution in minutes. What a rarity that is.

I don‚Äôt need to know the relative humidity in my home, but that feature works well, too. The temp readings are accurate to within a degree. I can‚Äôt speak to the accuracy of the humidity readings, as my various humidistats all give widely varying readings. Who knows which is right?

text:
Two weeks into using this dishwasher daily and so far so good. I'll update this review if that changes.

Pros:
Simple setup
Easy to use
Heats water up well
Surprisingly roomy inside
Door sensor
Water sensor
3 cycle settings
Auto-shut off

Cons:
Unclear instructions
No detergent reservoir
Plastic fittings/cheap hose
No fan/drying function
Small & poorly placed utensil basket
No door latch

Setup was super simple, the only assembly was connecting the hoses. We did need an adapter to connect to our sink faucet, but that was expected and the hardware store recommended a very nifty quick-release adapter for our sink. Make sure your connections are snug but not over-tightened as the connections are only plastic, and the hose needs a little clearance so don't let it get pinched. The intake hose is vinyl, but the drain hose is cheap plastic, it could crack if pinched at lot. I would have liked to see better hoses. Also because the instructions were poorly translated and they really don't tell you much about the dishwasher's functions so you basically have to guess things for yourself.

There is no designated area to put dishwasher detergent. We filled a spray bottle with diluted liquid dishwasher detergent and then we give our (pre-rinsed) dishes a quick, very light spray right before we start the load and that seems to work great. You don't need a lot as this is a tiny dishwasher.

Speaking of tiny, I easily fit 6 dinner plates, 2 bowls, and 2 cups, plus some silverware into the first load. That's plenty for our 2-person household. I dislike the silverware tray, it's small and because your silverware is horizontal it doesn't get water between them very well unless you wash like... 2 forks at a time. I took the silverware wire basket from our draining rack and it happened to fit perfectly into the right side of the rack. That let me load silverware vertically and they get washed much better.

You do absolutely need to make sure nothing slips below the rack! It has only one sprayer, the spinner in the bottom. If that gets stuck, nothing will get cleaned. Despite being only one sprayer, spraying from below, it does a pretty good job getting water everywhere inside. It sprays hard enough to ricochet the water off the top and sides, everything gets wets. Note that the door has strong hinges but no latch - nothing keeps you from prying open the door mid-wash cycle while the sprayer is spraying high pressure hot water everywhere. It does have a door sensor though, so it will shut off if opened. It also senses if you forgot to turn on the water faucet and beeps at you until you do!

Noise level is okay, about what I expected. It does well heating the water, you only need to hook up cold water and it heats it up pretty hot. You need to make sure you have some clearance on top - that's where the steam vent is. The instruction shows the other vent is for air, but if it's for drying it doesn't seem to do much of anything and the dishwasher seems to shut off once the washing is done - no fan/drying cycle. You need to either open it up to let them air dry, or take them out and dry them by hand. This is also why I knocked down a star - if it just ran a fan for a while to force air circulation after the wash cycle, that would have been great. There is also a little drain trap in the back of the dishwashing space, to keep the hose from getting clogged which seems smart. It is easy to remove and dump out any junk it has caught.

Overall we are very pleased with it. It's doing what we expected and helping us keep our dishes clean. It isn't a fancy super-heated high-pressure dishwasher, so we didn't expect miracles. It obviously won't scrub off 2-day dried-on gunk or burnt pans, but it handles our daily dishes perfectly well. If doing dishes every day is a bit of struggle for you, then this ain't a bad option.
title: Simple, uncomplicated and easy to use

I replaced the Kenmore filters with these, you can immediately tell the improvement. You don't have to fit them, the come ready to install. The aluminum adds good reinforcement. The less dens material doesn't tend to get blocked with minerals as easily. The wicking properties seem to be as good as the original, but with the added airflow, I'm refilling the water bottles more often and the humidity level is higher.

On any filter, the pores of the filter stop working over time. The old filters won't wick up any water regardless of airflow. Same with these. But you can replace these much more frequently for the same equivalent price.

The kenmore filters are good and work well and wear out. Same with these. These work great right out of the box. I just ordered spares for next year.

text:
This is the OEM water filter for my Samsung refrigerator, so I knew it would fit correctly and would be the exact same filter specification as the one that originally came with the refrigerator. Although I generally find that the cost of disposable accessories like this is unreasonably high (and, let's face it, this water filter is not essential to the operation of the refrigerator since you can still use the water and ice features of the refrigerator without having the built-in filter in place), the price from Amazon was much more reasonable than the prices that the local home centers (both of them) wanted for it. The filter is a 6-month unit, meaning that it should be replaced every six months, and it comes with date stickers to place on the filter as a reminder of when it should be changed, although my refrigerator also has a digital display that alerts you every six months to change the filter.

If you follow the instructions, it installs easily, with no water leakage when installing or removing it; I don't even turn off the water supply to the refrigerator when I change filters. It arrives in the box as pictured, with the filter itself sealed in plastic shrink-wrap so it can be stored for long periods of time and remain fresh until you are ready to install it.

text:
[[VIDEOID:984e452c3142bfe732d078f4606ca13c]] After 3+ month of using this machine, I think it is the time to write the review.
Before I purchased this range hood, I had researched through the products on the market, including Broan E64E30ss+Broan Exterior blower. I chose Fotile because it is a reputable brand in China and they are specialized in designing and manufacturing range hood. I trust them more than those European brands. I think they have more experience of dealing with high heat cooking, such as stir fry, etc. And my family in China had used Fotile products for years, they all love Fotile. Plus I love the appearance of this range hood. I love the contemporary stylish design.

1. Suction power: Five stars. You can see clearly in the video clip.

I cook stir-fried dishes, Indian Curry, pan fried meat all the time, this machine had never let me down. Before I had it, I had to open the windows in my kitchen and dining room to let the smell go away. After we installed this machine, unless I am leaning over the stove top, I couldn't smell anything.

2. Noise: Five Stars. When I had to make the decision between this one and the Broan range hood with exterior blower, one of my major concern about Fotile product was the noise. I downloaded a noise testing app to test, when it was running on high suction, the noise was around 75dB. Of course, it was not tested under the ideal condition. I cannot isolate the background noise. The noise level is tolerable. Plus, I only need run it on high power when I am doing stir fry. It wouldn't last more than five minutes to complete the dish.In the other cooking situation, the medium power is sufficient to solve most of the problems.

3. Easy to Clean: Five Stars.I usually take off the filter every two weeks and wipe off the excess grease on the filter then dump it into the dish washer.
I feel like they put some thing like Teflon coating on the interior surface. I spray some all purpose cleaner on the panel between the fans, the grease is really easy to be wiped off.

-----------------------------Things they can improve--------------------------------
4.I wish the color temperature of the LED light bulbs could be 3000(warm light) instead of 6000(daylight). Daylight makes my food looks pale.

5.The installation is not so DIY friendly. I think the designers could refer to the design of over the range microwave to see how they hang the machine.

We installed this range hood by ourselves, including hanging the machine on the wall, anchoring it on the cabinet, modifying the cabinet, and setting up the air duct.Amazon's installation service only covers hanging the machine on the wall. I have consulted with some contractors, they would charge me over one thousand dollars for the project. If you want to DIY, you need to be comfortable with operating power tools, know how to find the studs and so on. If you don't have the basic knowledge about your home's structure, this project would be quite hard for you to accomplish. Another tip is most home power drills are not powerful enough to drive a 6-inch hole saw.You need commercial grade drill to drill such a big hole on your cabinet or you can see the picture how we managed to drill those holes.

It dosesn't have any spare hardware. The screws are in metric. We lost one screw during installation, but local hardware stores don't carry this sized screw. So we had to move the furniture and appliances away to look for this screw.
title: I trust them more than those European brands

text:
This is a poorly designed and poorly built refrigerator.
We have had ours for about 6 months, and we would gladly replace it with a cheaper, simpler unit.
It's 3am right now, and I have just finished wiping up a puddle of water from my wooden kitchen floor. I replaced the water filter on this unit last night (easily accessed in the center of the open refrigerator). Turns out you need to cut the water supply (behind your fridge) to your refrigerator to change the filter. So Samsung thinks its customers should have to pull this behemoth out from the wall once every 4-6 months to cut the water supply to change the water filter. At that point, why not just attach the filter to the in-line water supply?
In addition, this unit is loud and the ice-making is useless. I should add that the interior space configuration does not work well, at least for us.

text:
i really like this little thing, especially for the price.

+ This sucker is very loud.
+ It has very quiet reminder beeps.
+ It has four settings for how those reminders work and how long before the siren.
+ The installation video is very helpful. i wish i had watched it before installation.
+ It comes with extra double-sided tape, some thin. i recommend buy some double-back foam tape from the hardware store if you have to change it's location. i have a roll that is pictured and it works just as well.
+ Contrary to what another reviewer said, there is extra tape and the tape does not go over the battery door, so changing the batteries without removing the tape is not a problem.

The reason i gave it a 4:
- The manual instructions, which i uploaded here incase you or i need it later, has Chinese machine translated English and make it difficult to understand the 4 settings. Maybe it's me, but i am not clear on the differences.
- The manual nor the device shows which way the batteries goes, hence the complaints about replacing the batteries did not make it work again. So i picture them with this review for our edification.
- i could not find a download of the manual, so i picture it with this review.
- The installation video, like most wordless installation videos, has loud, annoying, porn-style music that interferes with hearing the sounds that are important for installation. Why do they put crappy music on wordless videos?
- The backing on the thin double-sided tape is very difficult to get off. i could not find the edge of the backing after sticking it to the device. i had to cut into it with a knife and scrape.

All in all though, this is a good device relative to cost. i recommend it.

text:
On more recent GE refrigerators, this is a common failure component. Mine lasted ~7 years, but started making intermittent noise (like a tiny little helicopter) a couple of years before complete failure.

Typical symptoms besides the noise is the upper part of the fridge feeling warm and the bottom drawer freezing up.

To replace it, the 2 rows of bottom drawers need to be removed, then the lower drawer top and side mounts. Only tool I needed is a 1/4" nut driver. This will expose the fan. Simple plug and play. Reassemble everything in reverse order.

With some routine cleaning, this is a relatively easy 20-minute DIY job.

The (superseded) part received appears to be genuine OE GE and matched the original physically and cosmetically.

Keep a spare on-hand as it will likely fail again before the end of the fridge's (compressor) service life, if you care to save your refrigerated food. I'd recommend replacing it as soon as it becomes noisy and not waiting for it to completely fail.
title: Common Cooling System Failure Component

text: First of all, we are limited by the nominal 12 volt power in a vehicle. This heater draws about 10 amperes, but that depends on the actual vehicle voltage. My vehicle will idle at about 14.5 volts, so it is able to put more power into the heater, so it boils water slightly faster. When the product description says "glass or ceramic" container, they mean it. If you try to use a metal container, the metal will radiate and waste heat. If you try to use something silly like foam plastic, it will likely melt. Plus, you want to choose the container volume carefully. If you use a large volume container, the heater coil will not sink down into the cold water far enough, so the whole thing will burn up and fail. We are trying to get some volume around 8 ounces to boil. If you try it with 6 ounces of cold water, it will boil relatively quickly. I found that I could get good results (about 8 minutes to boil) using 7 ounces of water in a glass/ceramic mug, and the heater coil sticks down into the cold water. YMMV. If your vehicle battery is different and if you have the heater plugged into a socket that is a long way from the battery over a poor choice of wire, then the power to the heater will be lower. Just don't make the mistake of letting the heater flip off of the mug lip. Then it will be out of the water, it will burn up, and fail. So, choose your pieces and parts carefully.
title: It works, but you want to be careful

text:
While a built-in ice maker in the refrigerator can be handy, it takes up a *lot* of freezer space, requires its own water line (and a new filter on a regular schedule) and can be a maintenance nightmare. In contrast, our Dreamiracle Countertop Ice Maker requires only minimal counter space (and can easily be moved to other locations or stored away), is completely self-contained (no water connection) and if it happens to break can be easily taken in for repairs or economically replaced. It's possible to bag and store the ice it produces, but because it can make enough fresh ice for a couple of iced teas or other drinks in just minutes and plenty of ice for a family gathering or small party on demand, we see no need to store it. The machine is almost eerily quiet in operation; when it's finished filling its ice basket it goes into a silent standby mode which consumes very little power.

Our Dreamiracle Countertop Ice Maker has a self-cleaning cycle which can be invoked when we feel it is necessary; we're leaning toward a once-a-week routine just to keep everything working well. Dreamiracle recommends wiping the machine down manually, inside and out, every now and then, which fits in well with our usual cleaning schedule and takes very little time or effort. It's also recommended to empty the machine if it won't be used for a few days or longer, and fresh water should be used for the best tasting ice. All in all, the operational demands are minimal and basically just common sense.

We find this Dreamiracle Countertop Ice Maker meets our needs perfectly, both in the kitchen and in the entertainment room. It produces a usable quantity of good-tasting ice quickly, is easy to operate, clean, and store, and requires nothing more than an AC outlet to use. The 120 watts it draws in operation is very economical and makes the machine usable almost anywhere. The convenience of fresh ice on demand in the kitchen or on the patio is hard to overstate. We love the Dreamiracle ice maker; now that we have it, we can hardly imagine how we got along without it.

text:
After living in my apartment for years and getting frustrated with either spending $40+ on dry cleaning or washing my loads with the washer and drier that literally was broken all the time with my landlord refusing to replace them, I looked for an alternative answer. I found this bad boy and I was pumped.
I have a very small bathroom and only a stand up shower so I can't really keep it in there but it is small enough where I just keep it in the kitchen next to my apartment size drier (also a brilliant idea)

I must say this machine REALLY does a great job cleaning out the clothes. My husband's clothes are always filled with dirt because he works in fencing and I only really have to wash it once and it gets out A LOOOTTT if not all of the dirt out. For the size of the machine, it fits maybe a few outfits per load. I don't usually put too much in there so it doesn't all bundle together but I can fit 2 pairs of jeans and a couple shirts or like 5 to 6 shirts and some underthings.

The only problems I really have is the hose that they give you is too small to fit on my faucets which is very inconvenient. I do have one of those removable shower hoses which makes it easy to fill the tub but when it comes to rinsing the clothes I have to drain the tub, spin the clothes, fill the tub with clean water and then put the clothes back in to wash the soap off, ( I reuse the water as to not be wasteful) It's a bit of a workout to have to go through all the steps but it does what it needs to over all.

I even tried to get a different hose that was recommended but that was too big. I did see a picture on here that I found to be a brilliant idea, cutting an X at the top of a turkey baster then running the hose, I haven't tried it yet but it looks promising.

Overall I do recommend this if you're looking to save money, (Not so much time because of the reasons above)

text:
My landlord purchased this three years ago as a pair washer/dryer. Both have worked intermittently since day 1. Dryer has been repaired twice and washer once and the washer is already broken again.

On it's best days, you have to push the buttons in just the right order, or it usually won't start. It never starts immediately when you push the "Start" button. It has a mind of its own where it randomly waits 3-5 minutes before starting. (I guess installing a frenetic personality on a washing machine makes it "green".) Some times it sounds like its starting, but you come back 2 hours later and it hasn't done anything.

My roommates and I all have different rituals for trying to get it to start. Mine is to push start, open the door real quickly, close it, then push start again, then wait for the audible *click*. But my other roommates have their own rain dances, too.

Sometimes it will forget to rinse or spin clothes. You can't see much through the tiny window, so when you open the door it spills two gallons of soapy water all over your floor. (Luckily I have tile floors. And lots of towels.)

On the other end of the spectrum, some times it spins clothes waaaay too long. I was downstairs last week and could hear the spin cycle starting. I went out to grab a bit to eat and came back a few hours later thinking my clothes would be done and it WAS STILL SPINNING. It must have spun for 4 hours straight. I had to pull the plug on it because it doesn't respond to pushing buttons.

Later in the week, my roommate started his laundry before work and came home to find it was stuck on the spin cycle. He also had to unplug it to stop it. It must have spun for over 8 hours! I can't believe it didn't burn out the motor spinning at high speeds for hours like that.

As we speak, my latest batch of clothes are LOCKED INSIDE this stupid machine, and it has no emergency release, so my three brand new shirts that I haven't even worn yet are just sitting in their mildewing and smelling terrible.

This is so bad I would recommend never to buy a whirlpool ever again. I don't care if my mom becomes a whirlpool sales person.I don't care if whirlpool donates 100% of the proceeds to saving kittens. It's unbelievably frustrating, really expensive to have repaired repeatedly, time consuming to troubleshoot, time consuming to take off of work every 6 months to wait for the repairman, etc.
title: Worst purchase ever of any type in any category

text:
If you really have a dead switch then you should buy the switch from this guy. He sells them for $20 bucks cheaper than other vendors, and he delivers quickly. But your switch may really not be dead... Read on

I ordered a switch because my washing machine would fill, but not start. The very next day I found out, quite by accident I might add, that it would start if the lid was slammed hard enough (made a mental note; try kicking and slamming first). Anyway, th e slamming worked for awhile but like all easy fix's it eventually got to the point that it did not matter how hard one slammed the lid. It would not agitate.

So, seeing as how I already had a new switch, I replaced the old switch with this new one. Figured I'd better do it now as the slamming was starting to take its tole, and I didn't want to have to replace the entire lid. Took me forever to figure how to get to it, but the replacing was really easy. Amost immediately, the new switch started to behave like the old one. After some serious head scratching, and electrical checking, it turns out that my old switch was working just fine, and so may yours.

All that was wrong was the lid hinge wire needs to be bent ever so slightly, to better engage the switch. I bent the wire a "little more", just to make sure it would never do this again, and left the new switch in as long as I had it in there. Now all is well....once again I'm "Slamless in Los Angeles"

(sorry, couldn't help myself there)

text: This was purchased new, through Home Depot and was professionally installed.  It worked okay, for just over 2 years, nothing special but not bad. Just a few months after the warranty expired the knob for the oven broke while the oven was on! This was a disaster, we had to turn off the circuit breaker and take the stove apart to get the knob in the off position.  Not only a huge pain but very dangerous to have an oven stuck in the on position.  This oven has been well cared for and maintained in our home, there is no explanation for the break other than catastrophic defect.  I believe that the knob and thermostat it is connected to are made with cheap metal and as a result the metal snapped after normal use, I.e. turning the stove on and off for cooking 1-2 per week.  The repair is looking like it will be about 1k between parts and labor.

text:
Material is medium/heavy BLACK nylon with mesh and clear panels. I would have preferred Grey fabric as pictures. Construction quality is only adequate with the stitching being the biggest weakness. I expect some frayed edges and unraveling stitches within 12-months. The foam insulation is adequate but it is pretty thin and doesn't extend to the edges of the bag.

Design is good with holes for the handles and all cables but a little weird in that it goes UNDER the fridge requiring you to lift the fridge off the ground to install the bag.

Performance is very good and significantly improves the performance of the Whynter fridge when used in the back of my Suburban. Performance would be even better if the fabric was not Black!

Overall this is a good addition to the Whynter 12V fridge. The weaknesses I mention above combine for a 4-star rating but it is still a good product and one of the only off the shelf covers for this type of fridge. The design has enough room that additional foam can be added between the bag and the fridge and construction weaknesses can be repaired.

Now if it only came in gray as pictured.
title: A must have for use in an SUV but construction could be better.

text:
When my spouse found out it was $100 off on prime day, he got me one as a present. I've been desiring one of these for a while now.

Warning 1: This thing will devour counter space. It's huge. It's a monster. It's a big monster of delicious ice making.

Warning 2: This thing is noisy. It clicks when it makes ice. It whrrrrrrsssss when it makes ice. It SQUEEEAAKKS when it needs to defrost. It grrrrs while defrosting. If your kitchen is near, say, where you work, your first week will be an adventure. Then it becomes background noise. But this thing is NOT quiet.

Warning 3: be careful about your side tank hose. Easy to crimp. If it crimps, the noise will be horrible, the maker will not make ice because it's not feeding water correctly, and it will auto preserve the pump by running water through the system. Watch your hose.

Now, those warnings aside, I love this thing. The ice is delicious, it does a really good job, and I will never be able to live again without an ice maker in my life.
title: Love this ice maker!

text:
With so many conflicting reviews I almost did not buy this dishwasher, but I'm glad I gave it a chance!
What I like about this dishwasher:
It fit the small space we had available 18" and not too deep 22"
It works GREAT! The dishes are coming out sparkling clean. Follow the directions, use only a tablespoon of powdered dishwasher detergent and use the rinse assist product like Jetdry. I am only using the lowest setting (glass ware) which I believe saves energy and is the fastest. There is only 2 of us so this dishwasher is perfect and is getting daily use. I don't have hard water so I am not using the salt and the instructions are limited on how to do that anyway. For those reviewers who stated it has standing water, make sure you install your waste line above that of your sink line. We watched a lot of videos on our new installation, did it ourselves and everything worked out well. Also, this unit is SUPER QUIET. We removed the attachments on the top drawer on one side as it prevented our tall coffee cups from fitting, but we find it useful on one side for cooking utensils to sit on.
What I don't like:
Really only one thing. It doesn't seem to dry the dishes. I've tried opening the door right away and leaving it closed but it doesn't seem to matter. My dishes are always wet. I think I will leave it open over night and empty the dishwasher in the morning. Overall I am extremely happy to have a dishwasher that works!!! The price was good and it looks nice in our little kitchen. Hope this helps!
title: Finally! A dishwasher that fits!

text:
Excellent replacement for my ~2001 era GE Gas cooktop.

Trouble shooting/installation instructions below

Problem Symptom: Unable to ignite a single burner, no clicking sound, gas works fine. You can ignite the burner with a match and/or setting an alternative burner to ignite and ignite both burners at the same time (be careful as you will be flooding gas as you reach for the second burner!)

Repair steps:
1. shut off gas
2. remove knobs (simply pull up)
3. remove grates, burners. remove 2 phillips screws per burner
4. gently pull up glass top and slide to the side (you can remove, but this will require removal of igniters as well)
5. remove wires from old gas valve switch (remember which side is which)
6. replace new gas valve switch.
7. Put everything back together

Good luck!

Dylan
title: Excellent replacement for my ~2001 era GE Gas cooktop.

text:
I own the LG LFXS28596S refrigerator with the original LG ADQ747935 water filter, also known as LT1000P. After performing the "Amazon Confirmed Fit" check I purchased the ICEPURE water filter. When I inserted the water filter, I was unable to twist it 1/4 clockwise. I inserted the LG ADQ747935 water filter multiple times to confirm that I was doing it correctly, however was not able to 1/4 twist the ICEPURE.

I contacted ICEPURE customer support and they informed me the following "Due to the refrigerator manufacture's design flaw, the LG LT1000P filter manifold gets stuck easily when the filter was installed and removed improperly. This caused the new filter unusable". They then instructed me to "insert a screw driver into the manifolder and slowly turn counter-clockwise to reposition the central component. If the central component can not be repositioned, you will have to replace the manifold assembly which will costs approximately $400."

I decided to err on the side of caution and just purchase from a different manufacturer. I purchased the PUREPLUS water filter, and experienced the exact same issue as the ICEPURE. When you place the ICEPURE and PUREPLUS water filters alongside each other, they are exact replicas, which makes me believe they are made by the same manufacturer. I am not quite sure what my next move is here. I did some research on the original LG ADQ747935 water filter, and their reviews on the LG site is 2.6.
title: Does not fit the LG LFXS28596S refrigerator

text:
Bought this to replace the filter in my fairly new LG fridge. It's fairly straight forward; the instructions to pop the old one out are printed on the box that this filter comes in. You open the cover, pull it down, and then it pops right out of the fridge. Pop the new one in, push it upwards into the filter cover, and shut the door. It requires no tools other than your hands and only took me about 60 seconds my first time doing it.

After the new filter is installed, don't forget to do the last step in the instructions, which is to run 2.5 gallons of water through the fridge water dispenser and discard it. 2.5 gallons is actually quite a lot of water (about 5 straight minutes of water pouring out of my fridge) and may be overkill, but I didn't want to risk it and still followed it as they said. You can clearly see in the first couple glasses worth that you discard, that the water is a little "grainy" looking as the filter cleans itself out. After all is said and done though, the water is perfectly clear and tastes great.

All in all, I guess this is a 5 star product since it works as expected and is well designed for ease of use.
title: Perfect replacement for our LG fridge

Tools are ok. DRY FIT PARTS FIRST. I found out the hard way the shaft bearing areas are oversized. Bearings locked up during press in and nearly was not able to pull it apart. text: This is a fairly easy replacement, provided you can get at the wires to which these connect. I used them on a cooktop on which one of the original igniter spark had stopped working and come loose from the wires. So, that meant taking the top of the cooktop off of the countertop to get at the wires. So, while I was in there, I replaced all four of these, along with the spark module that provides the current. These igniters were by far the easiest part of the project -- pull off the old, push on the new. If you're working with a stove that lets you simply pull up the stovetop, it'll be a snap. Anyway, when all was said and done, all the burners light up happily.

text:
Took me several weeks to really appreciate this DW & use it correctly. Here is what I've learned:

1) It Does have a 500 W water heater. See the label on top of the open door. It's fully functional and heats well. But start with the hottest water you can.
2) Press the left side power button.
3) Then repeatedly press the top right cycle button. I only use the pots/pans setting.
4) Then press the start button below the right side cycle choice button.
5) Then LEAVE IT ALONE for 1:45 at least. Resist the impulse to intervene when it appears to be doing NOTHING for an extended time. LEAVE IT ALONE! Hands off.
6) The final beeper indicating it's finished is nearly inaudible. No big deal.
7) Again, remember to LEAVE IT ALONE!

Hope this helps.
title: Exceptional Value!

text:
The RECAPS Stainless Steel Refillable Capsules Reusable Pods was the best investment ever! I had bought another reusable plastic brand pod which was 6 pods total that had the flip top...but I was not totally sold on it with how it brewed my espresso and how it tasted.

I saw this steel set 3 pods with adhesive caps and thought it was a bit too much for its price, but I read mix reviews, so I figured to give it a try. I bought the set late June 2018 and I continue to use it today and I am very pleased with it. Because I can use my own espresso Cafe Bustelo, Illy or make my own espresso mix. I love the look, smell and the taste of my espresso. I can confirm that the pod gives off the crema expected from the Nespresso machine with this Stainless Steel Refillable Capsules - I haven't tried with the regular coffee grind.

What comes in the set.
About (120? )Paper sleeves have 6 adhesive caps, heavy duty tamper, brush, 3 extra pod gasket, 3 steel pods.

Pros: Crema, taste, cost-effective in the long run, mix your own coffee grind or espresso, easy to wash.

Downside: Cleaning out the grinds (this is expected for reusables!). be mindful when you need to reorder caps before you run out(not sure how much to replenish the caps are. I still have a lot of caps to get through.

Well worth the purchase versus to the the plastic or the nespresso capsule option.
title: Taste and quality
