text:
Do not buy this range hood from this company.
We recently bought this model online and installed by a local handyman officially designated by Fotile. The number one reason we wanted to buy this brand was because it was advertised to be much quieter. But this is not true. The fan noise is loud even when set at medium level. It's not quiet at all compared to Â¶àÂ¶à‰πê PACair brand. I think it's louder compared to similar Â¶àÂ¶à‰πê PACair models.
The air flow speed and the suction force are mediocre at best, although the fan makes loud noise. I can't even tell if it does a better job than my old microwave range hood which was replaced by this expensive toy. Not impressed at all.
Then I found the stainless steel grease filter cannot be removed on this range hood. According to the owner's manual, the grease filter should easily come out if I hold both ends of the filter and pull it forward, but it simply doesn't come out no matter how hard I pull it and how many ways I wiggled it.
Then I found this company doesn't have any customer service at all in USA. I called their national customer service number 1-888-3150366 many times, but absolutely no one answers the phone. I also called the New Jersey phone number 973-644-4900 on their product warranty registration card for numerous times, and absolutely no one answers the phone either. Both numbers don't have voice mail boxes and you get no chance to leave voice messages.
This Fotile range hood is much more expensive than other brands. I expected it would do better, but I'm very disappointed with the product and the company's customer service. This company's customer service is a joke.
Overall, this product doesn't worth the money and the troubles.

Update on 1/20/2018
We figured out how to remove the grease filter after we asked for help in Wechat. The reason I failed to remove it many times in the beginning was mainly because I didn't know the exact locations of the snap-in lock pins and the correct angle to pull it out. The grease filter on this range hood model has two snap-in type of lock pins located on the top edge of the filter, and each is about 2 inches from the left and right end, respectively. To be exact, they are located right at the top end of the second air intake opening/slot from each end of the grease filter. When you try to remove the filter, you would need to grab the filter at both ends and apply your force at these two spots where the snap-in pins are positioned, and then pull it toward you with a 45 degree angle. Do no pull it forward horizontally or pull it downward vertically. You may need to use a significant amount of force to get it out for the first time.

Update on 6/10/2018
After I posted this review the Fotile customer service called me a couple of times to discuss the issue and the solution. I do appreciate that Fotile has upgraded their customer service telephone system. I haven't tried the new numbers yet.
The first installed duct pipe was a very soft and sloppy aluminum type. So the solution was to replace the duct pipe with a better one. Some time later the unhappy installer came in to replace it with an aluminum duct pipe but this one is more rigid. I figure a galvanized steel round metal duct pipe as suggested by the Fotile customer service would be better, but the installer didn't give me one. Steel pipe is harder to install, which is understandable. After this remodel the fan noise is slightly lower than before. Now we normally use the medium speed and are getting more used to the noise. At high speed the noise is still way too loud, while at low speed the air suction is inadequate.

I watched the videos posted by other reviewers here. In one video the fan noise is quite loud, perhaps as loud as mine. In other videos the fan noise is acceptable. But of course this also depends on which fan speed you use.
title: Aluminum duct pipe got upgraded, now getting used to the noise

text:
In the product picture is a plastic latch and strike, different from the latch and metallic strike i received. So i tried to make the best out of the situation and proceeded to install the latch and strike. Unfortunately the door would not hold into place without exaggerated force, and even then it would pop out after a few seconds. After inspection i realized the strike, which is in a pear shaped form, does not join together at the stem leaving the two metal pieces a few mm apart. So whenever i close the door the strike is not properly inserted into the latch, in order to stay in place.
After numerous attempts to fix it with pliers, the strike broke apart. Next time i will avoid metallic strikes (or products with misleading plastic latch kit pictures), and spend the extra dollar if i have to.

text:
Our dishwasher was installed by the previous owner/flipper. They used brackets with double sided adhesive that lost adhesion awhile back. While looking for a better solution, I stumbled upon brackets like these. This one was made in the USA, was a Prime item, and included the mounting screws so I purchased it.

Such an easy install. Pull the dishwasher out (unplugging it and removing the drain hose if necessary), bend the tabs on either end, test fit the bracket and mark for the screw holes, drill pilot holes, place silicone or construction adhesive where indicated (3 spots) on the bracket, attach the bracket to the cabinet frame using the pilot holes (with the provided screws), put the dishwasher back in, mount the dishwasher to the newly-installed bracket with the remaining screws that were provided, and plug the dishwasher back in (and reattach the drain hose if previously removed). Done!

Now our dishwasher won‚Äôt be moving when we open and close the door. Simple and brilliant solution! 10/10. Thank you very much!
title: Perfect to secure a dishwasher with stone countertops

text:
I first bought a different washing device (don't know what I was thinking) from Amazon, and while that washer DID work, everything was done by HAND. If you've ever used a hand powered washer or washed dedicates by hand, you know what I'm talking about. Since I'm a retired vet, on my pension, who doesn't drive and can't walk the 4 blocks down to the neighborhood laundromat the Haier is a godsend.

I can easily wash two days worth of clothes in a single mixed load, 3 pairs of jeans, on the "Heavy" load setting, come out beautifully, and the spin cycle means even I can lift them out of the washer drum and hang them outside or in my shower to dry (something I couldn't do with hand washing and wringing them out before hang drying), WITHOUT getting drip water all over the bathroom or getting the clothes I was wearing, soaked.

I live in Florida with a small yard so an outdoor clothes line is ideal 90% of the time, but on those days when we have 'Liquid Sunshine' the clothes can be hung inside without dripping on the floors and dry with a simple house fan in a few hours.
title: Disabled, Living Alone, Can't drive to a Laundramat

text: This works if you like wasting money on 12 grams of coffee to make weak tea (see photo of typical result). I purchased both the 8 oz. and 2.5 oz. versions of this CAPMESSO Coffee Capsule. We're using these in a Breville Nespresso Vertuo machine. Followed all instructions to the letter. Burned through a can of iIly beans trying to get a decent cup from either size capsule. Out of dozens of attempts, only got one 3 oz. cup from the 2.5 oz. capsule that was acceptable strength approaching what comes from the standard OEM Nestle Nespresso Vertuo capsule. Very disappointed. Even tried cleaning the flat metal surface / rim of capsule with 70% Isopropyl Alcohol to remove all oils before placing fold lid on the capsule. No luck. The steel capsule cup design is great but the foil lid will not stay on the capsule throughout brewing sequence. This is absolutely critical when capsule is pressurized during machine brewing cycle. Until the lid adhesive and capsule metal rim surface (its too smooth) are greatly improved and optimized, this is a DO NOT PURCHASE item.  If you are like me, you'll try the other offering from CAPMESSO (latest version 2022) - yeah, the all steel one with a screw-on lid with pre-drilled holes (rather than foil)... Don't bother.  That design doesn't work either unless you enjoy coffee flavored water and wasted high quality espresso beans. And we tried all kinds of coffee grinds from our conical burr grinder too.  Sure wish this worked but it isn't ready for the market yet. Great idea - poor execution. Yes its made in China.  Need I say more? Unfortunate this product is NOT RETURNABLE and thus will go to the trash. DO NOT PURCHASE.
title: Foil Lid Does Not Adhere = Weak Coffee - Not returnable Do Not Buy

text:
We purchased the Samsung front load dryer in 2010 and in 2015 it wouldn't heat. I bought a Heating Element, watched videos showing the step by step repair and switched out the element (the old one had a break in the coil) - easy! When it stopped heating again in Sept 2016, I was overconfident and just installed a new Heating Element. The dryer still wouldn't heat and I couldn't see where the old one had any type of failure. So I took out the voltmeter and tried to figure out if the thermistor or thermostat, connected to the heating element side, was bad (I didn't realize at the time that there's 2 of each). Back to the store to buy the part that I guessed was bad - I installed it and it worked!
In July 2019, the dryer stopped heating again! This time I wanted to see what was bad before I started replacing parts, so I took the dryer apart and saw one of the wires connected to the heating element was burnt and separated from the terminal (see red wire in 1st picture) . I looked up replacement parts online and found that all the wires in the entire dryer are on one wire harness, which was pricey. I also didn't want to attempt that repair, so back to the part's store where I showed them the terminal and wire to see if they had anything I could splice in. They did! It was a part for a different brand dryer and it had copper wire, so I had to buy a special connector for copper to aluminum wire splice (see purple box in 2nd picture).
Now it's Jan 2020 and the dryer wouldn't heat AGAIN! After opening the dryer back up I saw the other wire connected to the heating element was burnt (compare blue wire in each picture). Researching the problem online I realized I was the root cause of the problem - if you don't ensure the terminals are snug to the Heating Element then excess heat can cause the wires to overload and burn. I searched on amazon and found the same wire connection repair kit, but this one had aluminum wire so I was able to use the regular twist connector. The part is for whirlpool and it's called a "Dryer Heating Element Wire Adaptor Connecting Kit 279457". But, I'm writing about this so you won't have to buy it. When your Samsung Dryer won't heat (and your wires aren't burnt)- just buy this kit and replace everything (Heating Element and all 4 thermistors/thermostats) so you don't have to guess which part is bad and replace them one by one. When I replaced the second burnt wire the dryer still wouldn't heat. I saw this kit and for the price it's easier to replace all the parts at once so you don't waste your time. The burnt wire probably caused another part to fail but there was no need to determine what exactly happened as I replaced all the parts and now the dryer works again. AND, make sure you use a plyers to snug down the wire terminals connected to the Heating element coils, just enough so they aren't loose.
title: Replace it all with this kit, it's easier.... but make sure the terminals aren't loose

text:
This element worked fine for me, however my problem turned out to be a loose wire at the breaker in the electrical panel. Install took about 45 minutes. The element is in the front left corner of the dryer, it wasn't too bad to get out.

Our house was built 8 months ago and the electrician didn't properly tighten one of the wire to the dryer circuit. Eventually this caused the wire connection to heat up at the breaker, which caused the breaker to trip. Then the wire loosened completely, and the dryer would still run just fine since it had 120v, but would not heat since it did not have 240v. I tightened the lug on that wire and it works fine now.

$30 wasted due to a lazy contractor.

text: We purchased a new washer and dryer set so I wanted to start fresh with clean vents and hoses. When cleaning the dryer vent I found that the hose from the dryer to the wall was nearly pinched shut and had quite a bit of lint. I hated the idea of putting another length of collapsible hose that would get pinched when I pushed my new dryer back against the wall. Internet searches led me to MagVent. I work with neodymium magnets so I am very comfortable with the magnetic coupling and thought it was more likely to "find" its home than some of the other push in place connections.  It was easy to attach to the elbow exhaust pipe and the connection to the back of the dryer was easy too.  I just pulled the included hose out 8 inches and pushed straight back to the wall.  The magnets did the rest.  It has been working great for the past month.  Highly recommended.

text:
my original bucket cracked after the ice cubes froze to the side of the freezer and prevented the ice bucket from sliding out - during the process of breaking up the ice the bottom of the bucket cracked and started letting ice cubes fall into the main freezer compartment (a design issue with these Amana/Whirlpool fridges).

I don't expect this replacement (since it is exactly the same design with the same thin plastic walls) to be any sturdier in the same situation, so I now check the bucket every week and clear out any large chunks of frozen ice before they can accumulate and stick to the walls again. I also make sure the bucket doesn't overfill by lifting the ice maker arm to turn off ice making if the ice cubes are accumulating and starting to stick to each other.

As for "Value for money" this seems overpriced ($60 for a plastic bucket) and I can imagine I can get it cheaper if I order direct from the OEM manufacturer, but I was unable to find a direct link for this particular model so I had no choice but to get it off Amazon. If this unit breaks again I am going to seriously consider buying a whole new fridge.

text: I like that the hood can be either fully vented out your house, or circulating - so you can choose. The lights are excellent. We have really inconvenient lighting in our kitchen and this made a huge difference for us. It looks fabulous - we get compliments on it all the time. Works well enough for us, though we do plan on doing the actually exhaust vent soon. I like that the top is adjustable so you can get it to the height you need. It is a little loud (the fan noise is a tad loud and the button sounds are loud), so the other reviews that address that are correct, but we don't have any problems with that. text: I tested this by moving the device outside. It did plot the data fine in the Tuya app running on my Fire tablet. But I could not get an alarm sent to my email or to the Tuya app running on my Fire tablet. The product is advertised as providing "App Notification Alert" and "Remote Monitoring". Then I read  on the device's website page that "The device and mobile need to use the same Wi-Fi". So how is this "remote" if the Tuya device and my mobile device need to use the same Wi-Fi? text: Overall, these are a great buy! We have gone back for more multiple times because we now prefer to pass these back and forth with customers as opposed to the flimsier dozen containers we otherwise use. We provide eggs for a local restaurant and were looking for something that was sturdy and easy to clean/sanitize. These have absolutely fit the bill! They stack well and allow multiple layers to securely be on top of one another. I can easily carry 10 dozen eggs without worrying about dropping them because they don't slide like standard dozen egg cartons. They for large chicken eggs, but are not large enough to fit a full 24 duck eggs. They are generally tall enough to accommodate duck eggs, but can only hold 20-22 depending on the size of the duck eggs. They are not tall enough to hold double yolk chicken eggs, but nothing fits those well. The tabs that keep them closed are easier to break then I would like, but generally given the size, it is natural to pick them up from the bottom anyway so this does not pose much of a problem for us. Many of our cartons have been passed back and forth for several months and the only wear you can see is the few broken tabs. Definitely recommend for anyone looking for a sturdy, easy to clean carton!

text:
Sure it's beautiful with handsome styling, but it's also so much more.

Some of my favorite features include the two multi-size burners, warming zone, and melt function. All the burners, including the power boil (yes, that's right) heat up well and function very efficiently. Along with the electronic display are some stainless knobs that I think lend a richer look than the black ones.

The oven cooks evenly (there were some minor fumes briefly during its first use). And of the two cleaning options this model offers, I'll definitely choose steam clean as opposed to the energy hog self clean. It's also nice that GE engineered the heating element off the oven floor.

I haven't had any difficulty at all keeping the black cook top clean. But if I do, I'll just use Wieman Glass Cook Top Cleaner, which out-performs Cerama Bryte (comes with GE ranges) by a mile.

Now if this model had a dedicated clock pad, it would be absolutely perfect. Then, I wouldn't have to push so many unrelated buttons to set, display, or turn off the clock.

All things considered, though, this is a great looking / performing range and I'd definitely recommend it.

text: Received 3 Cuisinart boxes as listed. Each box contains 2 sealed filters.  Exact filters that were included with my new (2 months old) Cuisinart coffeemaker.  The only thing I would mention is that in my new coffee maker's instruction manual, it says to soak the new filter in a cup of water for 15 minutes, insert it in the filter holder and then rinse from the bottom for 10 seconds before inserting into the coffee maker.  The box says to just rinse from the bottom for 10 seconds. I just changed to one of the new filters a few days ago. I am already using filtered water from my refrigerator's water dispenser, my coffee maker is only 2 months old, and I can definitely tell a difference in the taste of the coffee since changing the filter.  The last few weeks it had been tasting a little bitter, that's why I ordered these filters. The price works out to be just a little over $1 a month if you change the filter every 2 months, so I think this is an excellent value.  I do love my morning coffee :)

text:
These liners make clean up a breeze and work as advertised!
These would be perfect if you have a standard 4 burner stove top all the same size and equal distance. To be fair I knew before purchasing that I would need to 'cut to fit', and that they were 'easy to cut'. My stove has 3 different size burners, 1 large, 1 small and 2 medium. I looked at the custom cut liners, fit to your make and model of range, but didn't want to spend $60 -$70 until I knew if I would like it. These were very reasonably priced at $11, and if they didn't work so great, then no big deal.
It did take a bit of time to fit these, and I had to 'cannibalize' one liner to fit the gaps between the others and the sides.
LOVE the performance and look.
Canned peaches recently, and there are always drips of hot syrup, that fuse to the range top. Not so with these liners, wipe under hot running water, and dry. A friend was helping, and she didn't even notice the liners until I pulled one out to clean it!! So any questions about appearance and if they look 'ugly' ---- they are not even noticeable! Even the patches aren't. If you look, you can see them, but they do not stick out like a sore thumb. And my friend said when she gets a new range soon, she wants to buy these.
title: Superb performance for splatters and clean up - not as easy to fit non standard stoves.

text: [[VIDEOID:8f7e18e3b251d50aa04f61aa5c886751]] Since I rent my home, I have a simple refrigerator, with no ice maker. I'd go thru five ice cube trays in less than two days; the trays took up a lot of freezer space, were awkward and messy. This ice maker solved my ice problems beautifully. My video shows how it works. Draining the "leftover" water is a bit annoying since you can't just move the ice maker over the sink; removing/replacing the drain plug is awkward. The only area at a freezing temp is the rods where the ice forms, so you can't leave the ice cubes in the ice maker.. Once the ice drops into the bin, the ice gets moist. When you empty the bin into a container in your regular freezer, the ice fully freezes and sticks together. An ice pick is very helpful to break the ice apart once it's frozen solid in your freezer (I found a very nice covered ice pick at Amazon!). The ice maker has a setting for small or large cubes, but I don't notice much difference. Each time you fill the ice maker, it takes 30-90min for the bin to fill with ice. After you remove and replace the bin, the next batch of ice comes faster. Those are minor issues compared with the ease and convenience of not fiddling with ice cube trays! I very, very highly recommend this ice maker!!
title: I sooo needed this ice maker!!

text: This washer is small and portable, yes, but the best feature it has is the truely low water settings for small loads. The low and even extra-low settings on most washers (due to their size) use gallons of water per cycle and more on top of that per rinse while this unit has a low setting that only fills the bottom third of the one cubic foot steel tub. The washer has a setting for a five minute wash with only a couple of minutes for a rinse and the rest of the cycle is fill/spin for a total of around 20 minutes on the low water setting so the electrical consumption is practically nothing compared to the Whirlpool this replaced (that one clocked in at 52 minutes and the low water setting took up half of a 3 cubic foot tub). If you are a conservationist and you wash underwear, bras, socks, delicates or handtowels, this is the washer for you. I hope they make these for the next twenty years.
title: Best Conservation Washer for Water and Electricity

text:
My friend teased me about buying a dryer fit for a Barbie camper. Well, it is perfect for my apartment sized washer. Yes, as previously reviewed, it's small but it does work very well. It will hold 2 large bath towels and they dried in less than an hour. "ONLY 2 BATHTOWELS?!@@#$#@" Yes, its a apartment sized dryer, don't pair it with a regular sized washer as you'll end up with a back log of wet clothes. I've a portable washer about the same capacity and they wash and dry in about the same time period.

I think it does get plenty "hot" enough to dry your clothes as I'm not a fan of inferno hot clothes dryers. My little washer REALLY spins the water out so they are not that wet to begin with.

The supplied vent hose is a little "cheap" but it's working so far. I've installed the dryer near the patio door leading from the bedroom to the back patio. Depending on the weather, I can stick the hose through the open door or vent it into the bedroom to add heat and humidity to the home (I'm in AZ so it's really dry).

text:
The Stainless Steel Stove Gap Covers are designed to fill the gap between your stove and countertop, preventing food crumbs, spills and other debris from falling through the gaps. These gap fillers are made of heat-resistant stainless steel and are easy to clean, which makes them a convenient addition to your kitchen.

However, while there are some positive aspects to this product, there are also some negative reasons why you may want to reconsider purchasing them. Firstly, the retractable length of the gap fillers is limited to 13.8" to 27.5", which may not fit all types of stoves and countertops. This means that you may end up having gaps on either side of the fillers, defeating the purpose of having them in the first place.

Another drawback of these gap fillers is that they are not very durable. Some users have reported that the stainless steel easily scratches and dents, and that the product may not last very long. This means that you may end up having to replace them sooner than you expected, which can be an inconvenience.

Finally, while the silver color may look nice at first, it is prone to showing fingerprints and smudges, which can make your kitchen look dirty and unappealing. This means that you may end up spending more time cleaning the gap fillers than you would like.

You need to cut the gap fillers to have exact size but that will create a minor gap which makes it look kind of cheap in my opinion.

In summary, while the Stainless Steel Stove Gap Covers may seem like a convenient addition to your kitchen, there are some negative reasons why you may want to reconsider purchasing them. The limited retractable length, lack of durability, and tendency to show fingerprints and smudges make them less than ideal for some users.

I would stay away from purchasing it!!

text:
I've had this model for about a month. I had some installation issues that needed to be fixed. And the spin does vibrate more than my previous washer. Other than these, it does a very good job.

Why did I buy this washer? My old fisher and paykel was needing repairs a bit too frequently... I wanted to replace it with the same kind of technology... the direct drive inverter. F and P have it, samsung too. I was pleased to see lg also has direct drive. This is why this machine is more powerful and efficient than standard washers like whirlpool,etc. Notice in the reviews a lack of any mechanical issues? Bingo! Most of the issues have to do with load settings.

How well does it clean? Very well. It is doing all cycles like I expect. I don't normally use detergents (gasp!... I have a device that oxygenates the water before reaching the washer). I spot clean when needed. Laundry is still a choir... There's no magic. Unicorns and rainbows don't return with each load. Now if the could make a washer that could load itself, that would be something.

text:
This is a bit of a mixed review. First off the unit I received was damaged in transit. Although well packaged and with no apparent damage to the box it arrived in, the blower housing was broken in two places. Of course this was only discovered by the crew remodeling our kitchen on the day they were ready to install the cooker hood. The blower motor housing was made of plastic and attaches to the top of the housing with four screws. That's the end of the bad news.

The good news is that Futuro Futuro technical service was brilliant. I sent photos of the damaged parts by email, Within a couple of hours I got a profuse apology email reply with a tracking number of a replacement blower that was dispatched 2-day air to me. The replacement blower came with a light alloy casting instead of plastic. Fitting was a bit fiddly but straight forward. Four screws and two electrical plugs.

Things I like. It is QUIET! Well on the low and middle settings it is. It's a beautiful piece of engineering and the fit and finish are superb. Clever magnetic catches keep the lovely brushed stainless steel panel in place below the filters. These are easy to remove and pop in the dishwasher to clean. The LED lights are nice and bright, but it would be nice to be able to choose the color temperature to match our other under counter lights. The remote control - who would have thought - is great and means that you don't have to put your hands above the pans on the range when cooking to control the extractor fan.

All in all very pleased with this cooker hood.
title: Very nice design and super quiet in operation.

text: Purchased these for our Office Keurig Coffee maker. Says it works in a B145 model Keurig, but it tore our Keurig cup holder up. Here's why: There are two small holds on each side of the bottom of this K Cup. If you don't line the holes up exactly right with the pin inside the Keurig cup holder part, it will bend and break off the pins. Without the pins, the Keurig does not work. There are other K Cups that the bottom is raised with holes already in it, and it never touches the Keurig pin. I had to call Keurig, who was kind enough to send me a free replacement K Cup Holder Part, but I know that as long as different people use these, they will continue to break, bend, and tear up the newly replaced K Cup Holder. I will be looking for the K Cups that have the raised bottoms in the future to prevent this from happening again.
title: Be Careful Not to Break Off the K-Cup Holder Pin in Your Keurig Coffee Maker With These!

text:
To be honest, I read a lot of the reviews (bad and good) before finally deciding to purchase the dryer. Upon receiving it I was immediately impressed! It's quite compact, so it fits in my linen closet when not being used. It has 3 separate internal lint filters that are easy to access and clean, an external vent (they included an elbow PVC pipe that locks it into place in the back) , an amazing shiny stainless steel drum, a huge glass window on the front, and the entire dryer is beautiful!

As to it's performance: Read your manual. The dryer is portable so at functions at 110 volts. This means slightly smaller loads (than what a full sized dryer would handle) and it may take only slightly longer to dry clothing, towels, bedding, etc.

I have used my amazing portable dryer at least 25 times and have had absolutely no problems whatsoever! Well worth the money and no more making Laundromat owners wealthy! I invested just a portion of laundromat money in my dryer and it's even more convenient!
I really like and appreciate my Black and Decker Portable Dryer!!
title: Amazing performance for being a portable dryer!!

text:
We purchased this dishwasher 3 weeks ago to replace a 5-year old Whirlpool that had begun leaking. First mistake: this "KitchenAid" dishwasher is made by Whirlpool. I never would've purchased the "premium" brand KitchenAid if I'd known it was made by the same people that made the poor unit it was replacing.

The main problem with this dishwasher: the interior design is just terrible. Even though it's a standard size, the inside layout is so poor that we can't fit nearly the amount of dishes as any previous dishwasher we've had. The upper rack is adjustable to two different heights. If you set it on the upper setting, glasses won't fit in the upper rack because they bang into the silverware tray. If you set it on the lower setting, normal size plates won't fit in the lower rack. Which means you're basically hosed. We've spent 3 weeks trying every combination we can think of to fit in a standard load of plates and glasses, and it's just impossible.

You can remove the silverware trays on the silverware rack, but you may as well then just buy a much cheaper dishwasher that doesn't have that feature. The store manager where we purchased it said to set one side of the upper rack high, and the other side low, so it would slide in "diagonally", allowing us to fit plates and glasses normally. But that won't work; the tabs that lock the rack into place won't engage if you try that.

So you can just forget washing anything other than small cups and small plates in this dishwasher.

Secondly, don't believe their hype about how "quiet" this dishwasher is. When it's washing, it's about as quiet as any regular dishwasher we've ever had (at probably less than half the price). But when the water is filling, which is frequently during the normal cycle, it's super loud. Loud enough to be heard in any room in the house.

As for cleaning ability, it's about average on plates and glasses. We've tried silverware in both the upper tray, and in the removable holder on the lower rack, and silverware comes out less clean, and more spotty, in both locations compared to any other dishwasher we've ever had.

The unit has a feature called "ProDry", which I guess is supposed to be a premium feature to ensure items come out dry despite the new energy efficiency standards which came into effect several years ago. But don't believe that one either: nothing that isn't loaded perfectly vertical, like a plate, comes out dry. We need to manually dry off probably half of the contents of each load, even after it's run overnight. Never had that problem in any previous dishwasher either.

And the cycle time for normal wash is incredibly long. Almost 3 hours total, and then a fan runs for another few hours (assumedly to dry the items inside, which doesn't work). That fan is also loud enough to hear in the next room.

Due to all these problems, we tried to return it just three days after it was installed, but the retailer wouldn't take it back. They said I would have to get approval from KitchenAid for that. So after over an hour on hold over the phone with KitchenAid, they told me I was out of luck, and they would not approve returning it, because it technically wasn't broken.

The list price on this dishwasher is $1849. Obviously making it priced as an extremely high end unit. But as these problems make clear, this is an extremely poorly designed product. I wouldn't recommend it an even 1/3 of that price.
title: very poor design

text:
Sick of the nasty coffee at the workplace?
Looking for a great way to make good coffee while camping?
Fed up with the mess of a French press (and the sludgy, gritty coffee)?

Then get the AeroPress.
It's easy to use and easy to clean.
It uses whatever grind you want, except espresso grind (although very fine drip works best, I find).
It allows you to completely control the strength of your coffee through grounds/water ratio and steep time.
And you'll get a fine cup of coffee.

It doesn't make a large volume of coffee in one go, but if you make it strong, you can easily make enough concentrate for two large mugs. Then, simply add hot water.

This is probably the biggest innovation in coffee in the last decade.
Other products have been improved and become more affordable, but this is a truly new idea.
And it's great.
title: Great for camping and at the office

text:
This thing works great! At home, I grind my beans fresh, and I use a percolator or a french press. And I love my coffee. I found the Brew Buddy while searching for something I could use as an alternative to the Keurig coffee at the office (sorry Keurig, I'm not a fan).
The Brew Buddy makes a cup of coffee very similar to french press. I grind enough beans at home to last me a couple days, and I bring it to work in a ziplock bag. Then I use hot water straight from the Keurig if I'm lazy, or microwave it (I like my water to start a bit hotter than the Keurig produces). Pour the water through the grounds in the Brew Buddy and let it sit 4-5 minutes.
The Brew Buddy is super-easy to clean. I just turn it inside-out over the garbage can to dump out the grounds, then give it a quick rinse at the sink. Blot it dry with a paper towel and put it away. By the way, the Brew Buddy works excellent for loose tea also.
title: Makes Excellent Coffee Similar To French Press

text:
This was really awesome. The old burner on our GE stove were, by the previous owners of the house, pretty badly torn up. It had been bothering me for about a year---let's replace these burners and drip pans. I was wondering if perhaps I was being a little crazy, and how much difference it would really make. Was it worth $50 (that's about how much replacing all 4 elements would be)?

Well I was shocked at what a difference it was. In terms of materials and performance, these are pretty much exact duplicates of our "Cal-Rod" elements from GE, the surface is nice and smooth, and I'm certainly getting full heating performance. And it's a huge, huge, visual improvement, very unexpected how much difference it made. It almost feels like a brand new stove.

The attached picture shows my four new elements, include the two 8" elements (this item), and the matching 6" elements from this same company. Highly recommended. If you think you might need a replacement, you do. Do it.
title: Was really shocked what a difference it made, visually, to have new elements.  These are great.

text:
If you, like me, are worried about whether it will work with your model or not, just eyeball it. I suspect that if your existing ice maker unit looks very similar to this, you're probably OK. Kenmore, Whirlpool, and who knows how many other brands all use the same core mechanism. Which makes sense - there's no point in reinventing the wheel for every fridge, and it makes it cheaper/easier for them to service.

I have a 14-year-old (or so) Whirlpool model ED5THAXMS00 - its ice bin is in the door, not a drawer inside the freezer. So my machine's ice tray is parallel with the face of the door, it does not go front-to-back like many others. I don't know what went wrong with it; I think the ice ejector motor just locked up or burned out.

So as you look at the photo of this, see how the white plastic lower edge, along the front, is at a 45-degree angle? Well, instead of a sloped front, like this, mine is flat. I realized that this model would not fit, as-is and I was about to box it back up. But, upon closer inspection, I realized I could swap out the front white plastic plate from my old one into the new assembly easily. It's the exact same basic mechanism, with the exact same dimensions. So I had to dismantle the motor housing (the black plastic part in the photo - it's 3 screws), and removed the sloped plate, and swapped in the flat front plate from the old one. Perfect fit. Took 5 extra minutes, if that.

Also, my fridge has a light sensor across the door frame that tells the machine when to make ice or not. If the bin is full, the light sensor is blocked, and it won't make more ice. This ice unit comes with a wire lever that "feels" if the bin is full or not. This is for the internal drawer type of ice maker. If you have the door bin with the light sensor, you can just remove that wire lever, it comes right off.

Seeing as my fridge was so old, my wife was looking at new refrigerators. And after doing this repair, I gotta say there's nothing more satisfying than a DIY repair in which you spend $40 instead of $1000 or more! Heck, a service call from an appliance shop probably would have run $300 surely. Very happy with this purchase, it was a surprisingly easy fix, even for an appliance novice like myself.
title: An easy fix - you can do it!

text: Replace my smelly, moldy old boot with this part.  Watched video, was pretty straightforward.  My machine slightly different, but I figured it out.  My wife was a critical assistant, as you definitely need at least four (4) hands to hold the boot onto the drum-flange, then cinch the cable with spring and hook onto other end of cable.  Took multiple tries, but eventually with determination and patience we got it.  Snapped other side into slots on door shroud, and worked fine.  Took approx 2 hours to remove, reinstall and put machine back together.  NOT an easy fix, but doable if you're skilled and patient.  Emphasis on patience!

Finally a product that unlocks the expanded capabilities of the Keurig 2.0 machines for tea drinkers.

Tea is difficult because the water needs to be on the leaves for a longer period. With the older Keurig I could brew my mug making two 8 oz passes through a teabag stuffed into a Solofill K3. Or I could grind loose tea in a spice grinder. Hmmm.

The SoloPod 2.0 allows me to use a variety of loose teas using the high temperature and the "strong" settings. 1 1/2 measures of loose tea is good for a big mug, and a carafe will use between 2 and 3 measures.
title: Lets you go to town with tea.

text:
I‚Äôm sometimes a kludge master and have to admit that I was using black electrical tape to cover the gap between my (replacement) stove and the countertops. It worked, and was probably heat- and fireproof, but it had to be changed every once in a while and would leave gummy residue.

So I decided to try this out. Installing took me literally minutes (like five), and it fit perfectly and securely in the groove between my stove and counters. I debated whether to cut it for length, and eventually did take about an inch or two off the top so it would seat flatly at the top end. It does lie flat on counter side and stove side.

I have no reservations about this product. I, personally, wish the counter side was not quite as wide, but I will get used to that, and that does seem like the standard size for these types of products. (Some are even wider.) This also has an unusual smell to it (which I‚Äôm sure will go away) but a good smell. It smells like some of the trees out in my yard‚Äîlike juniper or eucalyptus or something. I have no idea why that is; I brought it in from the mailbox and it was sealed in plastic. But, again, it‚Äôs a pleasant smell.

And I like that these seem easy to lift out and wash, if needed, though I think a quick sponge wipe is all they‚Äôd need. And I believe you can put them in the dishwasher, too! Pardon the condition of my stove‚Ä¶ it needs a good cleaning. (I cook a lot.)

text: I purchased it through another website and got a slightly better deal , but the price on Amazon is pretty close.  I bought the stainless steel dual tap version of this, which is essentially the same but I like the look better than black.  I have to qualify by saying I've only had it for about a 30 days so I can't comment on long term reliability.  As for looks, I love the stainless look which is worth the extra $40 over black.  Stainless really makes it look classy.  The fittings, hoses and connections were all flawless.  It came with all the o-rings, most of which were already attached.  The fridge setting I have is on the second lowest cold setting and it gets the beer in my keg really cold.  It makes a loud clicking and/or popping noise from time to time like my other small fridge but otherwise runs quiet (this noise is the defrosting as I understand it).  The fridge is probably pretty standard to other kegerators, but looks nice and the fittings should last a long time. I can fit two 1/6 kegs and a 5lb CO2 tank inside the fridge, with not much room to spare.
title: Would buy it again

I've had this range for a couple of months now, and I haven't used the oven feature much, so I'm not comment on that.
I've really wanted a gas stove, but my kitchen didn't have the gas input and the space for the range was smaller than normal, so I ended up with this range as pretty much the default.

The range top is pretty hard to clean. I've had electric range before, and it used to wipe clean pretty easily unless there was burnt food. I need to clean this range with the ceramic range cleaner every day, and even then it doesn't seem to get completely clean. It's a little hard to reach the back cooking elements, and when I lean over to reach it, sometimes I end up touching the control panel and turning on or off other elements.

I'm also pretty limited to the type of cookware that I can use on the range. I've had to throw away a few of the cookware that I've used on my other electric range because it leaves marks on this one.

text: The unit has good wireless range.  It has nice features but its temperature accuracy is poor.  I checked its humidity readings against other units and the accuracy was acceptable.  However, the temperature readings were off by 1-2F over a rather small tested range between 60F and 80F. Although the unit can be calibrated to match any single independent temperature reading, the temperature sensor has poor linearity so it can not be calibrated to be accurate over a range of temperatures. The specified temperature accuracy in the manual is +/-1F over the range of 30 to140F indoor and +/-1F over -40  to 140F outside. In reality, in my unit it is much worse. Considering the unit features versus its price, I rate it 4 stars.  1 star off because of the poor temperature linearity.
title: Nice features but poor temperature linearity

text:
Great little product. Keys to happiness: (1) don't overfill, and DON'T pack in the coffee (2) make sure the little disc in the top is in place, it can fall out (this is the 'washer' that should be snapped into the lid, which is normally fine - it can and does come out sometimes) IF YOUR COFFEE IS SPRAYING OUT THE TOP, the disk has probably fallen out - it just snaps back in, OR you're packing in the coffee. (3) wipe any grounds off the surface where the lid closes onto the basket of the cups. (4) use a strong enough coffee to get your desired strength, Folgers dark roast is just enough for me, regular is too weak on large cup size. There is a bit of water comes out the top when brewing leaving some sitting on the cup once brewing is done and you open the filter basket - this seems to be normal. The Keurig-supplied filter basket does exactly the same thing.

We had a defect in one of the cups (missing disc mentioned in #2 above), they responded within 24 hours and solved the problem without isee at no charge.

text: Already love this! This arrives in a good sized heavy box. After getting the Opal ice maker out, and on the counter, the manual says it should be sanitized before use. I loved how the ice scoop fits into the ice basket so I was clearly on the way to liking it. It has a nice sleek look to the display and also the overall unit. The unit notifies you when 100 hours of ice making has occurred by flashing the Clean button, and you need to perform a descaling. I loved the ease of draining the reservoir, the back of the unit has two clear tubes that easily detach for emptying into a pail or sink. The sanitization process for first time use took me about 30 minutes to complete all 3 three cycles. Then you fill up the unit with water and ice making starts! The unit is the quietest I have ever experienced, and the manual explains the noises you may hear. I loved the feature where when filling up the water for ice making -  when you have added enough water to fill it, the 'Add Water' light turns off. A small feature but such a nice touch. The unit also has an Defrosting light, in the event the auger becomes frozen and there is low ice production. There is an optional side tank, I will be looking into that, I would have liked to have that information or part number in the manual. A small point because I'm already enjoying this Opal nugget style ice maker. Quite a bit!

text:
This water filter will last around 6 months; and it definitely works! After about the fifth month, the water coming from the fridge tasted just like tap water; after a couple days with the new filter installed, my fridge's filtered water tasted more neutral/good again. Highly recommended!

** Installation Instructions **

Since it was difficult for me to find installation instructions online, and the instructions on the box worried me a little (you don't have to turn off the water to the fridge, really?), I went for broke and did the following (which worked great!):

1. Open the fridge, and pop down the cover on the existing water filter (usually on top left 'ceiling' of the fridge) by pinching the sides in.

2. Pull the filter downward (it's plugged into a swivel mount) from the front; there should be a little down arrow where you need to pull).

3. Pull the filter straight out (should be a 45 degree downward angle at this point); expect a few drops of water to squirt out into the cover.

4. Wipe the inside of the cover with a paper towel to dry it off.

5. Push the new filter straight in (at 45 degree angle), then push it up so it's flat against the top of the fridge. Snap the cover back in place.

Finally, its recommended you cycle water through the new filter for a few minutes before you start using fridge water for drinking. The first minute or so, water will be spitting out as if you had shut off the water to the house. Make sure you have a container that's not too open or small, otherwise you'll be cleaning the front of the fridge and drying off your shirt!
title: Installation Instructions

text: Fixed my dryer for 20 bucks rather than the 200 it would have cost to hire a repair man. My dryer is Amana NED7200TW but I think this part is used on multiple models. My dryer would spin but not heat. I first suspected the heating element but it looked fine, eventually found this part had rusted and was partially shorted. If you suspect this part needs to be replaced you should first remove it and test with a multimeter. When functioning normally the resistance of this part at room temp is around 10k ohms. If it is significantly lower or higher buy this (assuming it is the right one for your machine). Before buying any replacement parts clean your dryer vent and see if your problem resolves.
title: Save money and fix your own dryer

text:
Got this to cook those "smelly" foods outdoors as it's a lot easier to move a propane tank and this thing around than it is an electric induction cooktop, and for our use it's pretty good. Even with a pan that was small enough at the bottom to fit on the grooves, it was sturdy enough to pan fry some fish, though the burner supports don't offer any decent grip so if you load heavier foods unevenly it can cause the pan to slide around, not good. Next up was just a small pot to fry some chicken, again it functions as one would expect. It's small enough to not need much oil unlike the larger fryer we have, so this is perfect for a smaller family or individual.
The ignition worked perfectly and burner levels adjust properly. The glass top looks nice but would probably prefer just aluminum as I'm worried the glass will eventually break. Would also like to see if there's any replacement grate styles for this that can support different pots/pans better. Since this is the only small gas "stove" I have I don't have any grates to test but if I find any that fit I'll be sure to update the review. I hope others will do the same as a replacement grate could make this 5 stars.
title: Great for cooking those "smelly" foods

text:
I bought this to go outdoors to wash my nasty rags from working with my farm animals. Rags that I use to wipe animal feet, clean poop off of items, etc. I fill the drum and pre-soak for 10 minutes, then wash for 15 minutes. Then drain and put half the load in the spin for 3 minutes, then the other half for 3 minutes. Then put everything back in the drum and rinse for 5 minutes. Then spin each half for 5 minutes while starting another load in the other side. The spinner wrings out the water so well that it only takes a couple hours to dry on the clothesline.
Note: watch for corners of towels getting lodged in the bottom and stopping the wash cycle. It's an easy fix, just yank the towel out and it will start again. Also squish down your load real well when spinning so it isn't off balance. I rarely have to recenter a load.
title: I love this thing!

text:
Great stove, love almost everything about it.

HOWEVER, I've owned it for 4 years and since about a year ago (that's 3 years after purchasing new) it's been getting more and more difficult to press the "cancel" button. Finally, it stopped working all together. Then I started using the "bake time" feature; just setting it for 1 minute when I was done with the oven. Today I went to use it and now the "bake" button doesn't work. My only option now is "Pizza" or "Chicken Nuggets". Broil isn't an option as you can't "bake time".

Trying to locate what part I need has been a hassle and I haven't really gotten anywhere on that front. Not looking forward to having to pay a service charge to fix an almost new stove.

****UPDATE*****

I tried what the other user / 3 star reviewer, said: how they fixed this same problem by unplugging and plugging the wires back in. It worked! I have full use of all the buttons again, however I still have to press a little hard to "cancel". I guess I'll just keep doing this as maintenance every couple years.

I've uploaded a picture of the exposed panel. To access it, you have to remove the top metal piece. There are 4 sets of wires, I unplugged the stove first, then unplugged and re-plugged them all.

Good luck!

Here's a link to the picture of the stove back: http://imgur.com/lK5nmKo looks like you'll have to copy and paste it as Amazon apparently doesn't allow links.
title: Great stove, love almost everything about it

text:
Two things you care about with a third party replacement for a part you hated to buy in the first place. First, is it cost effective. Second, will it work flawlessly. So far both desires have been fulfilled so I'm a happy refrigerator.
Note to people worried about leaking connections: the o-rings are the seal, and that little package of white paste is silicone water-based lubricant. If you don't have it, think k-y jelly. Without this on the o-ring, you are making a simple replacement--it inserts by pushing in, then rotating till it is tight--a gambling event. The odds are with you if you use the lubricant on the o-ring--the little black rubber ring around the part of the filter that goes into the refrigerator. Please keep your mind clean on this...and your refrigerator leak-free.
title: Happy refrigerator, happy kitchen

text:
I had to purchase a new washer when my old one finally gave up after having been repaired twice. This one is very quiet and after the spin cycle, the clothes are very dry so that drying time is cut in half. I have seen negative reviews complaining about the water level. I just turned it to super and didn't use the precise fill selection. Also, I saw a tip from another owner that if you select the fabric softener rinse, you will get more water in the rinse cycle. I used to have to close the laundry room door, which is right off the family room where we watch TV when using the old one. This one was so quiet I had to go check to see if it was running. I did find that I don't have to use as much detergent so that will save some money, there is a speed wash cycle if I need something in a hurry and shorter drying time. My best friend has a front loading HE washer and hates it. She saw this one and now wants to come try it out to see if she wants to sell hers and get one. Apparently mold and mildew buildup in hers is a problem. As far as how long this washer will last remains to be seen, but initially I am very pleased.

Update 2/12/2013 I have been using the washer for a few weeks now and I still love it. I have read reviews where people have complained that it doesn't use enough water. If you learn to use the settings, you can get as much water as you want. I have to wash a lot of dirty jeans and towels. I use the super load setting and the fabric softener rinse setting. Both give plenty of water and my clothes get as clean as I could expect. No, not every stain comes out, but some of them are just permanent and no washing machine on earth could get them out. Spin cycle gets clothes very dry so my dryer only needs to run about half the time.
title: So Far I Love It

text:
Like many other people my item was received damaged. the spinner in the dishwasher was broken off so i can not review functionality. I have a replacement enroute so i will review that one when it arrives. The box it self was in perfect condition so i know the damage had to have happened at the manufacturer. Also the dimensions are off. the dimensions are of the machine it self but the drain hose sticks out in the back and adds about 2 inches. If you receive a non damaged one then it looks like a good product.

Now on to some of the comments other people made. Yes you have to rise you plate off so there are not chunks of food. the tubes for this are not huge. Nor is there a disposal attached.

the soap packets.... some people say to just toss them at the bottom. The instructions actually say to put them in the little cup attachment that sits on the coffee cup ledge to ensure they are exposed to the water. So the people who put them in the covered powdered compartment there is a reason the packets don't always melt. This also may account for peoples complaints about the short wash not working. packets may not be exposed long enough to fully melt. I would advise a powdered or liquid detergent for those quick washes.

Update 12/28/2016:

I would like to update my review since I have since received a working dishwasher. I am now convinced my first one left the factory broken. My new one came with some drips of water in the tubes and a damp (but not moldy) smell inside the washer. My old one did not. This tells me they tested this one.
Pros:
This machine is no louder than my air purifiers. Actually I cannot hear it over the air purifiers. Except when it dispenses the water back into the sink.
Set up is nice and simple. Getting it out of the box takes more time and is more complicated. They pack it well.
I have done 3 loads. In 2 of the 3 loads my cascade pack melted appropriately. It was placed in the little carrier on the correct side. This may lead to using liquid only.
Works well

Cons:
Till you get used to the sound of the dispensing water that quick jolt is kind of loud.

Weird things:
For some reason normal wash takes more time then heavy wash even with an extra wash with heavy wash.

text:
Not an easy install, but not that difficult either -- however, that is really an issue of how Samsung designed the install and has nothing to do with the heater element. You have to take the whole front off the dryer. Fortunately, there are a number of youtube videos on this. You need a medium phillips screwdriver, a pair of needle-nose pliers and maybe a small flat head screwdriver. One person can do this. It's mostly a matter of removing a dozen or so screws, replacing the heater in the housing it's in and reversing the process. The hardest part is getting the heater housing back into place. It's not too bad, but it didn't "just slip in". The whole process took me an hour. I probably could have done it faster if I didn't stop to watch the youtube video.

However, the part fit perfectly and I now have a functioning dryer with heat that cost me $35 and a bit of time instead of the $250 I paid the repair guy last time the heating element died.
title: Fit my samsung dryer perfectly

text:
I will never have an Electrolux dishwasher again! The reasons:
1. You can't find simple parts like door seals and hinge brackets. For example, the door bottom seal is not sold separately (~$25). You would need to buy the whole door liner for $350.
2. The metal brackets attached to the hinges rust too fast! In 6 years I got it completely corroded, so it started leaking at the door bottom. Both detachable metal brackets need to be replaced to stop the leak but you won't find this part.
3. Electronics periodically get into a glitch. The display indication periodically won't come up. The power cycling helps to reboot the internal microcontroller and get it working again. We dealt with this issue for 6 years pretty much on weekly basis.
4. The dishwasher has a touch control panel which is nice but the internal speaker is very quiet, you'd need to put your ear close to the door to hear it.

OVERALL IT'S ALL BAD ENGINEERING! STAY AWAY FROM ELECTROLUX DISHWASHERS! DON'T WASTE YOUR MONEY!
title: Bad engineering! No spare parts! Lasted only for 6 years!

text: This new clutch gear kit made our washing machine sound and operate like new again, for a while there I was noticing some suspicious grinding like sounds when the machine went through the different cycles. My wife claims it always sounded like that, so I didn't pay to much attention to what I thought were concerning sounds I was hearing occasionally. I came home from work one day and she told me the washing machine didn't finish all of the cycles on the last load. When I took it apart I found all of the teeth on both halves of clutch gears were ground away to almost nothing. Note: There is a small actuator motor that engages these clutch gears, when it starts to fail, the gears may not fully engage which will cause catastrophic damage to the teeth on the gears. The worn down gears are the result of a failed actuator, so make you sure to order the actor together with clutch kit.
title: Washing Machine Pulley Clutch Kit & Washer Drive Belt

text: We have had these for 20 months and they have worked very well. We had become used to taking our last sip from the cup with some care to avoid the sediment, but we now have a solution to that problem...paper filters. text: Like a lot of other people on here, I gave these filters a try as the price was so much less than the official GE ones.  I figured if they lasted even half as long, at least I would've broke even. Unfortunately for me, it didn't last at all. I flushed out a gallon or so of water after putting in the filter, just to be safe. I will say, the water pressure was amazing -- very fast (which is odd since others have commented that they had very little pressure).  But after filling up a glass, I noticed some tan-colored specs floating around. Figuring it just needed to be flushed more, I repeated another gallon.  Still debris.  This went on and on, but whatever it was, the water was not getting any cleaner.  After multiple gallons, I finally gave up, ordered the official (overpriced) GE filter, swapped out, and now I at least have clean water again.  Looking around at the reviews, it really seems like this product is a shot in the dark -- maybe you'll get one that works, maybe you'll get one that's actually new, maybe it'll leave stuff in your water, maybe it'll shoot out of your fridge.... it goes on and on.  I'm tempted to save the cartridge in case I ever get my hands on a good saw to slice it open and see what's actually inside this thing.  For the extra $20, I'd recommend staying with the official filter and pass over this cheap product.
title: Particles in Water

the parts it comes with allow you to do one of the following
1. connect the washer to a sink to fill it
2. manually fill the washer for each load

also , the adapter parts it comes with did not fit our sink
plus our sinks are all too far away from any outlets to connect to

you could buy an extension cord , but you should check if adapters work with your sinks first before doing that

otherwise you‚Äôll be doing what i do
‚Ä¢ connect washer to outlet in kitchen
‚Ä¢ connect water out hose to washer hookup
‚Ä¢ manually fill washer for each load
the washer will drain the water before it starts if you have to manually fill , so it won‚Äôt work the same as if it connected to a sink where the wash cycle will auto fill for you

(hope that makes sense)
so i suggest pouring detergent in , filling with water , sloshing clothes around and let them sit for 30 mins before you spin
mode ‚Äú10‚Äù will spin for 1 hour , this is the mode i use
sometimes i‚Äôll spin for 3-6 hours then i‚Äôll hang dry clothes and they‚Äôll be 100% dry the next day !

i can fit a king size duvet in this washer and the bed sheets , mind you out duvet isn‚Äôt super thick though
you have to be careful about the weight and size of the loads you do otherwise it will stop and beep because it will shake due to the imbalance

that‚Äôs all you need to know !
this thing is a major life saver.
before this i was hand washing clothes in our tub !
wet clothes are really heavy and it was very exhausting , i‚Äôm so glad i got this washer.
it arrived in perfect condition.
the manual is a little confusing, but you really only need to know what each mode does and if it can connect to your sinks or not etc to get it working well.

even manually filling it doesn‚Äôt bother me.
it‚Äôs WAY less work than hand washing in a tub , believe me.

get it !

‚Äî other things to note ‚Äî

do not use hot water in the washer , it says so in the manual i believe
cold water only

the spin cycles are spin only - no hot air

there is a lint catcher but i‚Äôve never pulled anything out of it , it must all get rinsed out or it sticks to clothes (a small downside for the price you pay)

my apartment has no ac , only windows that open and a radiator system

luckily , my apartment is also in a mostly dry climate that doesn‚Äôt see high humidity
so hand drying clothes after the spin cycle throws some water off clothes works great
if you live somewhere more humid you might have to wait a few days for clothes to dry all the way , or you‚Äôll need a separate dryer if that bothers you

text:
We paid almost $2K for this thing. We also purchased the extended warrenty for 3 years. The repairman was out every 6 months. The cheap plastic inside breaks and cracks continually and after the first 2 years, the plastic parts are NOT covered by warranty any more. The rubber seal on the door came off and that required replacement of the entire door - twice -- which they put on crooked so when you look at the front of the fridge, one door is higher than the other. It also required a special order so we had to take 2 days off, one for the diagnosis and another for the actual repair. The humidity control on the cheese drawer broke. The pulls on the veg drawers cracked. The veg drawers fall out of the track if you put anything heavy in them like onions, tomatoes, carrots, or lemons. My drawers are just resting on the bottom of the fridge.

After 3 1/2 years the motherboard went - $600 (out of pocket).

When the doors are closed, the "Open Door" alarm starts beeping. Somtimes if you pull out and push back in the basket and the drawers in the freezer, it will stop beeping. Sometimes I have to open the fridge doors and press the two door buttons to get it to stop. Still haven't figured out what that is.

Having the water dispenser inside the fridge is not a good idea. The water pressure is too low and it takes too long. You have to stand there for a whole minute filling a water bottle with the door open. And if you fill two, the door alarm beeps. The ater filters are $30 each. You can get them as cheap as $26 - if you buy a case of 6!

One repairman said he spends 80% of his time fixing just GE Profiles. The model is poorly designed, poorly made, with inexpensive parts that wear quickly. I cannot reccommend this appliance at all. I know now, almost 4 years later, that it was a fad, something shiney, new, and novel, but not worth the box it came in -- like a pet rock.
title: Not reliable, not practical, disappointed

text:
I bought this board to replace and existing board on a GE Profile series double door refrigerator. Not sure if this board is specific to any model but it fit mine perfectly after researching correct part number from GE. Previously, the refrigerator would show wild swings in temperature, including so much in freezer that Ice would melt together in a ball and re-freeze. This simple screw in and plug in board was easy to install (with some mechanical and basic electronic experience.) It has a metal cover that is removed by screws in back of refrigerator and was easy to access. I noticed my old board had a swollen capacitor which was probably the issue.
After replacing control board, the refrigerator acts as new. Ice production is solid and non-stop and compartment temperatures hold steady without variation. Now I can get foods to last a week beyond expriation dates. Just make sure your compressor coils aren't dirty or clogged first!

I bought one of these a little over a year ago to replace an older bosch model which I actually liked for the most part. Big mistake on my part.

So this thing has 3 alarms: a temperature alarm for the fridge, a temperature alarm for the freezer and a door is open alarm. These go off constantly, sometimes immediately after your open the fridge door. Sometimes they go off AFTER you already closed it, sometimes several minutes later, which is just insanely horrible and thoughtless design. Imagine dealing with this every day, multiple times a day.

The control panel is awful. Sometimes you have to press it 3-4 times to get it to dispense water or ice.

The plastic door bins are designed in such a way that the only thing supporting them is a thin strip of plastic at the top. This apparently causes too much stress on the the low quality plastic these things are made from, and causes stress cracks. 2 of the bins have already cracked, even though nothing heavy or oversized was stored in them.

Keep in mind this thing is over 3,000 bucks. Do not buy. Avoid like the plague.

text:
this little washer is excellent!
i checked reviews on several machines before buying this one. wanted the washer/dryer combo from thor, but there seem to be numerous mechanical problems. especially surprising considering the price. also looked at the little "wonder washer" mini portable washer and rejected it for the same reason. it's apparently cheaply made, doesn't work well and got more bad reviews than good.
the haier reviews made me a little nervous, too, until i noticed that all the bad ones said the same thing. it leaks if connections are not tight enough, it makes a horrible sound if the plate is put on upside down, and it mustn't be over-loaded or have too much detergent put in. all of this amounted to consumer error. i really needed the washer and decided to take a chance. it's one of the best decisions i ever made. the only problem i had was with installing the plate. as everyone has mentioned, the holes don't match and the screws are too large. i remedied this by very gently enlarging the holes on the bottom of the machine with an ice pick, being careful not to damage any working parts. got the machine running soon and i've been using it several times a week since it arrived two months ago.
one other thing. in reference to the metal plate being improperly installed, there were comments about instructions not being clear. something may have changed since those reviews were written because the instruction book i have is quite explicit, and the plate is clearly marked. the directions are actually pressed into the metal. there is no way i would have put it on wrong. either people were ignoring this or (more likely, i think)haier took note of the problem and did something about it.
anyway, if you're in need of a washer and short on space, do get one of these. it's well worth the money.
my sincere thanks to everone who wrote reviews, good and bad. you were all instrumental in helping me make this choice.

text:
The product arrived on time and packaged in a clear bag with instructions clearly written on it. At the time they arrived I had just replaced my Keurig filter, so I didn‚Äôt use them right away. Today I replaced it. I followed the soaking and rinsing instructions on the bag and which are the same as the OEM instructions. When I began soaking the filter I also pushed the filter under the water manually for a few seconds to insure the filter was completely soaked. I noted air bubbles escaping from the larger side of the filter, which is the bottom when installed. One of the negative remarks I read mention a clogging of the filter. The trapped air bubbles were probably the culprit clogging the intake manifold. So I suggest pushing the filter under water to insure the filter is fully soaked and any air bubbles allowed to escape. I always use filtered water in my Keurig either from the refrigerator or our Brita. As I always do, I ran 2 hot water cycles through our Keurig after installing a new filter. This operation cleans out any debris and allows me the check the water clarity. I read in another review about cloudy grayish colored water. The first hot water cycle produced a few bits of debris and the second was absolutely clear.
So in conclusion, the K&J filters perform just as well as the OEM Keurig filters at a fraction of the cost. Problems with the product posted by others were found to probably be a failure on their part to follow procedural details recommended by Keurig and K&J.
title: Perform as well as Keurig OEM filters.

text:
We have had the dual fuel 48 inch 5 burner for 6 years. It is terrific. I have cooked in restaurants and I love the large griddle (compared to the useless narrow griddle on many high end ranges) for breakfasts, grilled sandwiches etc. The low simmer on the burners is the best in the business and can simmer all night without scorching. The convection oven is superfast. The high BTU burner (better than Viking) is great for stir fry, though a commercial wok range has more BTU's but is single purpose.
We have the integrated hood and stainless backsplash so cleaning after frying is easy. The hood baffles go through the dishwasher.
We have flooded the cook top from the pot filler and the burners must dry out before the igniter works again.
Overall this is a commercial- look work horse and much easier clean up, better high BTU burner, better simmer, bigger griddle than the more expensive competitors we compared or have used like Viking, Wolf, thermador etc. Real commercial ranges are brutally tough for long use but are usually open burner design and hard to clean up. They are not good for home use without a hired crew. They do not have the simmer setting or the closed burner design.

text:
I did a lot of research on range hoods before deciding to buy this one. The build quality is true to their YouTube videos, which poke fun at the quality of other similar looking range hoods, and prompted my extensive Google searching. I couldn't find a more powerful hood at the advertised sound level anywhere near this price point.

Although it is not recommended by the manufacturer, I was able to install it by myself. The instructions make you put the mounting plate on the hood before you put it against the wall to make the marks for your drill holes, but I did that with just the mounting plate, which made a one man install very easy. Also, the manufacturer doesn't account for if you have tile behind the hood, so make sure you have some good toggle strap anchors for the body of the hood (pending you have no studs where the mounting plate screws will go), and some regular wall anchors for the top chimney bracket. The instructions to install are adequate, but could be better. They didn't make any mention of the bottom chimney bracket until it was time to put the chimney up, nor did they give good instructions on the order the parts at the bottom of the chimney need to go in. Through a bit of trial and error, I think the order from bottom up is: bottom chimney bracket, black square rubber gasket (which is mentioned nowhere), and then air diverter. The bottom chimney holes were not perfect as other reviewers have mentioned, and I too had the clamp that holds the power cord be in the way of the bottom chimney bracket fully seating itself. I think it would have been fine to just remove the clamp, but I shaved mine enough to allow the bracket to slide all the way on. I also opted for a rigid pipe between the air diverter and my connection to the exhaust pipe rather than their flexible pipe, but that was personal preference.

Performance is great. What I find interesting is that it barely gets louder as you go through the speeds, but you can definitely tell that it is moving more air. The 300 CFM microwave range hood we had before was louder and did way less. My wife loves that she can cook the greasiest of things and her clothes don't smell like it afterwards. I spilled some flour in the bread machine cavity that started burning when the bread started baking about 15 ft away, and the fan cleared the room quickly. The lights are great, though I wish they matched the LED under cabinet lighting I installed, which has a warmer (yellower) look, or vise versa. The remote is gimmicky, but it works fine. I haven't tried the fan timer yet, but it sounds very useful. My only complaint is that there is no way to illuminate the panel to see the clock other than putting it in automatic mode, and my automatic mode seems to come on randomly sometimes. I may call the manufacturer about that.

All in all, I am very satisfied with the hood and would recommend it to others.
title: Best bang for your buck range hood

I love my Keurig, but the amount of waste caused by single use K-cups is a real issue for me. It's amazing how we added more plastic waste to a system that used very little to begin with. I was in need of a solution - I had previously bought some plastic refillable cups (same brand) but they made my coffee taste awful. The water drains out too fast and gives you a weak, plastic tasting cup.

BUT let me tell you, this stainless steel pod has changed everything. The holes inside are tiny and allow the water to run through the pod more slowly, the result is a much stronger and fuller cup of coffee! I use small paper filters in mine to make cleanup easier. It's amazing to have delicious coffee again and none of the guilt associated with K-cups.

text: I had purchased a new coffee maker. It was the first coffee maker I owned that used the basket filters. It's easy to grab a cone filter but after opening my first bag of basket filters well let's just say I didn't want to go through that every morning. That's when I found the Camco 43653 Coffee Filter Dispenser. After reading the reviews the only concern I had was the complaint about it not staying sticky which meant it stop working. When it arrived and I saw what was being used for the sticky stuff I knew exactly what it was. Sure enough about two months later it became harder to get the filters out. The sticky stuff is Duct Seal which is non toxic and you can buy at any home improvement/hardware store for about $3. Just make sure it says non toxic on the packaging since I don't know if there is a brand out there that might be toxic. Pinch a small amount off and roll it around in the palm of your hand until soft and pliable then just press it on. Don't use to much, no more than twice the size of the piece you removed. I gave it 4 stars because I had to buy the duct seal, they should included some for replacement. With the renewed sticky part it works good as new. I bought this product to replace the factory washer door hinge. The main reason I purchased it was because of the cheaper than factory price.
