title: Spend the extra money and buy the factor hinge

text:
I have only used this washer once so far, as I just received it a few days ago, but overall I'm very happy. First impression was that It's a lot lighter than I thought (lots of plastic). It's not as sturdy seeming as I initially thought it might be, either. But, at this price point, you can't ask for much more. It can hold more than I thought it might, as well. The way it works is, once again, different than I envisioned. You fill it up using the provided hose or other method, add the soap, and run. there is a hose attached to the bottom that is the draining hose‚Äîit works with gravity. You hang the hose off of a hook on the top side of the washer, and to drain you just unhook and flop it into a sink or tub. For rinsing you empty and refill with clean water, run again for a shorter time and then drain. The hose doesn't quite reach the top of the machine when it's hanging up, so if the washer is overfilled, water will spill out of the top of the hose.

It's very simple, which is kind of a good thing for this product. Less moving parts=less to go wrong. The weak point will probably be the construction (guessing if it gets knocked hard enough, something will crack), the hose is quite thin and may be prone to cracking or ripping, and the motor (although it seems strong) may go at some point. Basically, be careful with it and don't overload it and you will probably be fine.

Overall it's quite decent. I think it'll be a good alternative to making trips to the laundromat for smaller items. It's basically a step above washing by hand, though. You still have to wring the clothes out (no spin cycle), and manually drain, and refill for a rinse cycle, and so on. There's not much automation other than the motor which agitates the water. But, for a small washer I can stash under my kitchen table, I think I'll be using it quite often.
title: Not bad!

text:
This is not a bad emitter. It works fairly well, and did a good job as a backup/alternate IR emitter to control my air conditioner while I was away on a week long trip.

I configured it using the Smartlife app. It wasn't in the device list, but I was able to program it using the remote from my air conditioner.

The app isn't the best, and is a little rough around the edges, but it gets the job done. One thing I wasn't able to find was a library of user submitted device profiles. You can program an unsupported device using the remote, which is what I did for my air conditioner, but I've lost the remote for my fan. Fortunately, I also bought another IR emitter which does have a library of user submitted profiles, and was able to find one that worked with my fan.

I ended up using it quite a bit to control my conditioner, in conjunction with my other IR emitter. It worked very well, and never became unavailable, or needed to be rebooted.

The Alexa integration works. I can now command my TV with Alexa.
title: App Could Use Some Work, the Emitter is Good However

text:
I see the bad reviews. I just installed, and yes I have been there with you with electric power.

After almost 50 years as a DIY guy, just a year back I finally self taught how to read schematics. Before that issues, blaming products etc. Not to say this is made with the best materials... But we shall see longevity, when it fails I always let you know.

This one, is one of the easier ones let me explain if you stuck. Power to light and fan are the only two wires you will put together with the Black (power in house) then the rest is easy, ground takes copper wire, and the other two are on white.

Now my old fan had two switches. So i unscrewed them both from wall. (Turn breaker off unless good with wire). The bottom wire on both was black power, which they jumped when installing. The white wire to fan, went to white wire controlling fan on new switch(im going off memory of the colors of switch). and the white wire went to the white on light. I think the switch maybe a diffrent color, but maybe marked as 1 & 2. Then as I stated i connected both power wires on switch together to the one black power wire.

I then screwed in and put the 1 old switch back to fill hole. It wont do anything, not connected. Put plate on and looks liks picture attached.

When programming hold light button for 8 seconds until solid light. Press the light button 1 to 4 times depending on which part you want to program.. Only one at a time though. After i got into program, i pressed light switch 1 time, then I was in 1 program, and pressed 1 through 4 and then made sure it blinked the amount of times 1-4 on which i pressed. If switch working correct, hold light switch and wait for the green light to blink 3 times, and release. Then start over again to get into program mode and select what you want, press light button wait for green light to blink three times, and saved....

If you do not hold button amd wait for the light to blink three times that mode will not be saved.. Hard to explain in words, im no author... But if you need assistance ask..

Good luck all Happy Summer 2017
title: Works Perfect (only day 1 though)

text: These are not difficult to fill or put the lid on(much easier if you use the stand that comes with it to support the pod), not even messy. Just don't overfill. The filter hangs over the edge but doesn't hinder snapping on the lid.  Toss the filter and you can reuse the rest.  Be sure to line up the hole made the first time so you don't punch more when you lower the handle. The k-cups that are designed for reuse leave sludge in your cup, but when I put a filter in it, works just like the expensive filled pods.  It even works in the My-K-cup.  The plastic filter that comes with it also leaves muck, but not when I put one of these paper filters inside the plastic.  Great coffee.  To reuse the cups above, just take off the lid, toss the filter, rinse pod and lid, and ready for another cup of coffee.  I have a drawer that holds 36 pods, fill it up once a week, and good to go. A box of 100 filters is less than $9.00. The original lids I bought have been reused at least 10 times and are still good. The filled K-cups are too expensive since I drink a lot of coffee and am basically "thrifty".  I was saving the filled pods, tearing the paper lids off, scraping out the used grounds, cleaning them, then filling with my grounds and using a replaceable lid.  Difficult to get the lid on without a stand but I figured it out. THEN I found these. SO EASY. This is the way I'm going from now on.

text: My wife was distraught when our 9 year old LG front loading washer started making grinding noises and the tub would no longer spin.  After checking some online appliance repair sites, I narrowed it down to a very likely cause - splines on the original rotor assembly had sheared off by the metal teeth of the tub shaft.  I believe the original rotor may have had a plastic splines, which is a straight-up design flaw, but this unit has metal splines, so I don't expect to replace this unit again.  Dump the words "replace rotor assembly LG washer" into your favorite search engine and you'll find the video that explains the fix. You will only need to remove four screws to remove the access cover in the rear, and then a a socket wrench to knock loose the bolt that holds this in place.  You can find this slightly cheaper online elsewhere, but when the laundry is piling up and Mamma's not happy, Amazon Prime to the rescue!
title: You can do it - Unleash your inner Appliance Repairman!

text:
I have done RV repairs for years and worked on several thousand refrigerators. Norcold problems started a number of years ago when
Theford corp. that makes RV toilet stools bought Norcold then things literally started going into the crappier. They reduced the quality
in the most important part of the refrigerator the boiler this is where the heat is exchanged with the fluid. Their grand plan was to
put in very thin metal witch will deteriorate very quickly. However part of the fluid in them was flammable and caused fires.
So did they fix this problem? absolute not they just put a band aid fix on it called an over temp sensor. Also they changed how the
cooling units were made it went from being hand welded to robot welded (you know they had to cut cost some how)
So keep this in mind if you own an RV with a Norcold in it.
title: Use with caution

text:
My 16-year old Whirlpool Duet washer had been making some loud bangs during the spin cycle and Google led me to the verdict that it was probably bad shock absorbers (the cement counterweight was slamming into a front panel at a harmonic suspension spring frequency during spin-up/down) and showed me a nice video of how to replace them. A well-known department store's parts store wanted the same price for one as this four-pack cost, so I called it a worthwhile bargain.

I'd read a few other reviews about getting broken parts, and unfortunately I got a package that had obviously been opened and returned, and one of the end brackets of one shock was broken. one of those reviews had mentioned swapping a broken end out for an original end, so I did that in the interest of getting the repair done today, but it was a royal pain getting the end piece off.

Otherwise, these new shocks seem fine and illustrate that the old ones were definitely shot, offering no thrust resistance at all. Installation wasn't nearly so easy as the video made it look, and I had to lightly file some plastic on both the last back shock and its mount on the washer tub, as the washer plastic was a little too thick to let the shock twist into place (but this problem had obviously affected the original parts too).

I believe the washer will behave better; first test will be tomorrow. I'll update this review if these shocks seem to fail in short order or anything, but I hope we should be good for a few more years. EDIT: The first day with the new shocks had a lot of new high-frequency/low-amplitude tub/washer vibration during the spin cycle, but I think that may be the shocks' break-in period, and I vaguely recall the washer behaving that way a long time ago. There were no giant knocks as before the change-out.
title: Amazon sent broken returned parts, but I made it work.

I am SOOOO unhappy with my 6000 series Maxima washer. I purchased it after 3 months of investigation, having happily had a Maytag set for all of my adult life (top loader), and hating the ugly eyeball type front loaders currently popular. The problem: IT DOES NOT SPIN OUT THE WATER in heavy duty loads... (pretty bad for a HEAVY DUTY washer!!!) Towels, rugs, or light blankets/bedding, they sometimes take 3 complete cycles, before I give up, get a bucket, and take them outside to hang and dry for two days. They have so much water left in them, the bucket is needed to keep from making a mess through the house to get outside. On rainy and icy days, I don't know what I am supposed to do.... Maytag DOESN'T CARE ! Their answer: send a Service man out, and get ANOTHER SERVICE CHARGE.... and oh, by the way, we have a wonderful program to help you alleviate further service charges.... blah, blah, blah.... I am so annoyed that I spent nearly $ 2000.00 for this awful washer, and I am stuck with it, because, (being a bit older) my husband said..."this is the last washer and dryer set we are going to own"....
So, DON'T BUY THIS.... DON'T BUY THIS... DON'T BUY THIS ! ! ! and Maytag, if there really IS a qualified engineer / product designer, who cares about what you sell, (Maytag won't let me reach you), please call Maytag and get the complaints from them, and backtrack us, the unhappy losers, who bought your poor merchandise. text:
I had a love hate relationship with this thing at first. After 5 loads, the door lock mechanism stopped working. Edgestar customer service was great. When I emailed them and asked for a replacement part they wanted to replace the meachine; however, due to the difficulty I had getting this one into my second story place, I asked them to try the part first. It was very easy to replace, took less than 5 minutes. Now that we were up and running again, I ran into two issues 1- extremely long dry time, over three hours 2 - regular wash cyles left clothes will wet, even after two additional spin cycles.

After reading up on HE washers, I figured out it was HE washer ignorance/ operator error. I have never owned a high efficiency washer before. I basically was using too much detergent, which caused suds to hamper the pump functionality. This caused the clothes to be somewhat wet when entering the dry cycle, which caused it to take hours to dry. I put a shallow pan under the front, removed the coin catch plug, and poured water through the drain hose to flush out the pump and then I ran about 4 loads through rinse/ spin cycle. I now use just two to three tsp detergent per wash and the dry time is reduced to 1-2 hours depending on the material of the clothing.

As Douglas M mentioned, the dry timer will hit 15 minutes then stay there. According to customer service, there is a moisture sensor that stalls the timer till it is at the appropriate level, then it finishes the countdown. I don't like this feature. I have found that if I pause it earlier, once the door unlocks, the clothes are sometimes almost dry. There are three preset drying times that can not be changed. I wished there was a timed dry option that did not utilize the sensor. If I pause it before the timer starts the final count down, it takes about 20 min to cool to where the safety will allow the door to unlock. There is no override for this, which has caused me to be late for work when trying to get a load done in the morning. (Gotta take everything out to avoid permanent press wrinkles)

So, what I learned:
1- use very little detergent
2- washer/ dryer works best when 1/3 full if going to use dryer
3- don't leave clothes in machine after it stops unless you like serious wrinkles
4- although clothes feel damp when removed after dryer stops, they will be dry once they cool down

Basically, this little machine is perfect for my needs. I have a small home that will not accommodate a regular size washer/ dryer. I do one load three or four days a week rather than one laundry day a week and it is working great. The one star off was for lack of the dryer timer options.

James from Edgestar customer service was very patient with me on all my questions throughout my learning process and was always prompt with his responses.
title: Perfect for my needs... with learning curve

I was in search of a product to organize eggs in the fridge, but most of them only offered basic organization. What I loved most about this product is that it not only organizes the eggs without any risk of breakage, but it also allows you to easily remove the eggs you need without having to remove the entire piece from the fridge.

One of the standout features is its space-saving design. If you have enough room, you can even place other items on top of it without worrying about damaging the eggs. This adds an extra level of convenience and efficiency to your fridge organization.

I must say, this product has truly transformed the way I store and access my eggs. No more clumsy handling or the fear of accidentally dropping and wasting eggs. With this solution, my fridge stays tidy and I can effortlessly grab the eggs I need for cooking or baking.

Overall, I highly recommend this egg organizer to anyone looking for a practical and efficient solution for fridge organization. It not only keeps your eggs safe and secure but also offers the added convenience of easy access. Say goodbye to the hassle of traditional egg storage methods and enjoy a more streamlined and enjoyable cooking experience!

text:
We have had a compactor since 1967. They normally last 10 years+. The last one though, a Whirlpool lasted only 2 years and that was a troublesome 2 years. I decided to replace it with the more expensive Broan with it's bigger motor.

My main complaint after a week's use. Instead of just kicking the toe piece and having the drawer pop out as other compactors build them you must open the cabinet door on the Broan, then bend over and pull out the drawer. No handle on the drawer either! What's with this? Open a door, bend over, pull out the drawer, throw your napkin in the bin, push the drawer shut, then close the drawer! I'm in my twilight years. Bending over is not high on my list of want to do things. What genius engineered that? Couldn't they at least have spring loaded the drawer so that it would pop out a bit when the door was opened?

Now the good part. The compactor cycle is quiet and VERY powerful! Sounds like a swiss watch with no squeaks and groans. The extra PAC works well. Don't buy a compactor without this feature. The drawer does slide out easily and it just appears sturdier then the other compactors. Also the drawer is not accordion pleated like most compactors. That should make it much, much easier to clean. The bags are much easier to put in it because you don't have that interference at the front where the drawer and the door are of one piece design.

Bottom line: Worth the extra expense but the two step process to throw away garbage is definitely two steps backwards! Are you listening Broan?
title: A heavier compactor of a different design

text:
I am submitting this review to warn others about our experience with this refrigerator

We purchased this refrigerator on January 17, 2021 for $579.73. By mid-April the food in the freezer portion was thawing and the refrigerator was not cooling properly. We called Frigidaire. We were directed to A&E Factory Service. It took 2 weeks for them to come out and another two weeks to come back to make the necessary repair (after obtaining the part). So, four weeks without a working refrigerator. Fast forward to October 13, 2021. The food in the freezer was completely thawed (some food had to be thrown away). To say we were annoyed is putting it mildly. My husband contacted Frigidaire. He was first hung up on by the first Customer Service rep. Then, after being put on hold for nearly an hour, was told we would have to have another service call. The customer service representative had a bad attitude and neglected to put in the service request. We had to go through the painful process all over again. This time the request was put in, but the wrong contact information was given. The repair person did came out and we were informed that the previous repair person had not cleared the refrigerant line and an air bubble was causing the problem. He cleared the air bubble and we were told it should now work fine. Here we are on December 29, 2021 and the freezer has again failed and the refrigerator is not cooling either. After three failures in less than a year, and due to all the inconveniences to include repairs not being correctly performed, terrible customer service experiences (to include failure(s) to request repairs and rude customer service representatives), all we wanted was a refund for what we paid ($579.73). Frigidaire does not stand behind their products and seems to have little regard for their customers. Consumers should not be asked to make due with products that do not work correctly/are defective with no real way of getting what they paid for: a reliable appliance that is also dependable and safe.

We submitted a complaint to the Better Business Bureau and Frigidaire responded saying that the "product may be covered for functional repairs under the terms of our limited one-year warranty."

Basically, we are out of luck and out $579.73 and stuck with a product that doesn't work. We can't even sell/donate it in good conscience because of it's inability to work correctly. I will never purchase another Fridgdaire/Electrolux product again.
title: Don't make our mistake; stay far away from Frigidaire

text: Diagnosed the problem with a family members dryer while visiting them in their new house. Something in the heating circuit was bad being that the heat was not working but the tumbler was. I didn't have an ohm meter on hand at the time to pin point what the main problem was so that's why this kit with everything in it is awesome. When I went back to replace these components I ohm tested everything and found the original high temp cutoff was blown. This made me wonder so I pulled off all the exhaust piping going out of the house and found multiple lint blockages causing excess build up of unexhausted heat. I cleared all the blockages and rerouted the poorly installed pipes so there are no sharp elbows where any lint that passes by the catcher can get hung up and clog again. I ohm tested all the new components and all was in good order. No complaints of any failures so far. Thanks for making this kit available!

text: Puchased this unit in June of 2009.  Paid between $600 and $700 for it. This past weekend the unit stopped working.  The control panel is not responding.  In doing a little research online, I am seeing that others have issues with the control panel.  Looks like the average cost is about $300 to repair.  Now, I bought this because it was touted as extremely energy efficient.  Well, it looks like all the money I have saved in electric over the past 27 months is going to get wiped out with a large repair bill.  I have owned dryers for 10 and 15 years (at half the cost)without incident.  When I called LG customer service, I was told to unplug the unit and hold the start button for 10 seconds and then plug it back in.  After doing that, it still did not turn on.  The customer service person then asked if I had purchased an extended warranty.  I did not.  I never purchase extended warranties.  I feel that if you are selling me a product, this expensive, I should not have to fork out even more money to make sure it works for more than a year.  Here's an idea, why not make a dependable, quality product that lasts?!?!?!?!?  I bought this upon the suggestion of Consumer Reports.  I can say I will never spend another penny of my money on an LG brand product.  They have lost me as a customer.
title: Unbelievably frustrated.

text:
well I in the process of ripping out the kitchen. it had a old large dishwasher that didn't work very well . ( I hate to do dishes ) anyway the dishes started piling up in the large wash sink next to washer dryer. so looking at alternatives and possibly something I could use in the rv after I came across this and read reviews.

even though many positive reviews I still thought sure like what's that capable of 6 dishes oh wow and will it clean.

when it arrived the box was damaged. it is packed very well and didn't see any damage on the dishwasher though water had gottin on it i guess the water left over from factory testing had spilt out some how when it was dropped. now what I did notice is the front is plastic and the edges of the plastic looked as if some one on the factory assembly line used a razor or something of that nature to trim the plastic and did not look very professional. in any case you don't see it unless inspecting . the build quality is so, so, with the plastic as for the rest, inside and out it looked like a normal dishwasher build just smaller. so even after it was opened and setup I still though how much can this little thing wash ( remember I have weeks of dirty dishes with crud all over them and the last time i washed that many dishes by hand it took over a hour ) after watching many video reviews of this dishwasher I didn't read the manual completely and just started loading it up. filled the soap dispenser and the rinse aid. ("cascade complete", powder). since I had so many dishes I set it to 45 min wash. so I could do more loads in a faster time.

when it was done I was amazed. I haven't seen dishes this clean in years and that's on 45min cycle. i though it would take days to get all the dishes clean but 5 washes latter and done. ( I had about 3 full normal dishwasher loads of dirty dishes) and i even did the pots and pans in it. oh did I mention its quiet at least 1/2 of the old large dishwasher .

I really like the LCD display lets you know how much time is left and what cycle to choose. if you pack this dishwasher correctly you be surprised how many dirty dishes will fit and it gets them clean. now I read some reviews on it not cleaning well or spots on dishes. well i did pack it funky the second time and 3 dishes did not come out clean. one was a cup i had packed in the corner and one was a lid the bottom got clean but not the top of the lid did not and the other was a bowl that was also packed in a corner, it was half clean, like half was washed and other half still had the crusted on food. i learned fast to pack it right and everything came out clean from then on .

one thing I noticed doing dishes with this washer is its fun. I have a bad back and hated bending over to load up the full size dishwasher even didn't do it many times from my back pain .

I have this washer table top height and is a pleasure to load and also fast unloading

so in the end this washer saves money easy to use, works great . small, fits where normal dishwashers cant. can be hidden in a closet if need be. and gets dishes clean. as long as it lasts its a win win even more so if i use it in rv

just remember its small for a dishwasher, yet big enough like a large microwave oven, a large microwave oven . not small i have a small GE microwave that's half the size of this washer.

to some it up " I LOVE THIS DISHWASHER "

note , I have a $1,800.00 kitchen aid dishwasher for the new kitchen . now I just don't know if I going to use it or sell on craigslist. anybody contact me LOL: why? well i trying to be energy efficient and save the planet and all that stuff. even trying solar and wind power.why use a big over kill dishwasher, sure it be great when family comes over but how often is that. 2 people this dishwasher is more then enough. the only reason I can see installing the expensive big dishwasher is just for resale if I sell the place that I don't plan on doing. sure it has every possible certification even can be used in a restaurant. hmmm just me and girlfriend. I not a catering service. its just for the 2 of us and possible company sometimes occasionally. I don't think so I can use the extra space that this dishwasher gives me and cost efficient save a couple of bucks in the process

and to honest when using it I load it up but then I just cant help feeling the craze and don't run it k knowing I can load more dishes I actually make more dishes dirty on papas before running it . I love it . great if you have back pain use it at counter height and your world will change. dishes are no more of a problem. did I mention it works great and at this time it seems to be the most advanced in this type of dishwasher. you cant go wrong. I told I a slob and or told I have ocd all depends on the person. this washer works! you don't need more unless 5 or more people in family and you save money in the process

text: If your icemaker takes this motor (I know, it's one of the more expensive ones, but it's the right part) and it's running but not dispensing ice when you press the lever, the motor contains a gearbox that may be the problem like it was on mine. To make sure the ice tray isn't jammed, remove it and press the switch at the top (to make it think the door is closed) and then operate the lever on the door to see if the shaft is turning. If you hear the motor turning but the shaft isn't turning, you need a new motor/gearbox assembly.  Super easy install: remove two cover plate screws from underneath, unplug it, and remove four screws (all are 1/4" head size).
title: Icemaker is working perfectly again

text:
Here is how I approached the installation:
1. First of all, if the oven is turned off, there is no need to shut off power to the oven outlet.
2. If you are careful, the removal and replacement can be done entirely from within the oven, without pulling it out to expose the back.
3. When step #2 is being executed, there is a chance that one or both of the connecting wires will drop back behind the oven wall.
4. If that happens, one can get a coat-hanger, bend it into a hook, and attempt to fish the wire back into the oven cavity.
5. It turns out that even with the oven turned off, there is a hot terminal within reach of the said coat-hanger hook.
6. When coat-hanger hook contacts hot terminal, step #1 becomes a moot point if you are lucky enough that the circuit breaker pops.
7. If you are not so lucky, your family and/or friends will find you dead with your head stuck into the cavity of an ELECTRIC oven.

Or you can bypass the above steps, cut power to the oven, pull it out from the wall, remove the back panel, and do it the right way. Aside from my self-inflicted foolishness, the replacement element fit and works great.
title: Installation for Dummies

text:
I hope Amazon lets me post this before buying. -- to help everyone else.

So after looking around and trying to understand this "Left and Right" slope thing. Turns out - The original fridge is shipped with one of each; L and R. Then when you choose how your doors should open, the installer would just flip it for the desired side. In fact, the freezer handle and the fridge handle are essentially the same but with opposite slopes.
BUT, when buying a replacement you still have to decide which one is which. The pictures that the sellers show are confusing because they backwards - from the perspective of the appliance "looking out" into the handle, and not from the from the "customer's" perspective. We want to be able to just look at our fridge and then look at the part and order it. You have to do some visualizing mental gymnastics to figure out whether you're ordering the correct slope part.
SO, I did the visualization for you. -- see pics.
title: My analysis before buying.  Slopes?!?!

text:
I don't know what I was expecting when I purchased these, but I was definitely surprised by the size when they arrived. While they were much bigger than I was picturing, they fit perfectly under the feet of my washing machine.

Installing them was a bit tricky for me, but not due to the product at all, just due to my laundry room set up.

Before they arrived I wanted to try lifting the washing machine up to see if I could do it on my own or if I needed additional help so I would be ready when they came. Didn‚Äôt take long to realize that I would most likely not be able to achieve success with just my 2 hands and a determined attitude (I have a bad lower back so I couldn‚Äôt lift with my knees and slide the pad into position at the same time), so I ended up buying a furniture lifter to help ease the process.

The lifter was essentially a small dolly, with the straight edge sliding under the machine, the wheels acting as a fulcrum and the handle as a lever to lift the unit off the ground. Luckily, I only had to keep it lifted just long enough to slide the foot pads under it so I was able to do it by myself in a matter of a few minutes (not including the planning time and moving everything around to make enough space for me to use the lifter).

I wish that I had taken video before and after installation to show the difference, but I didn‚Äôt even think of that until after the pads were under the unit so I apologize for not thinking of taking a video before but I don‚Äôt feel bad about not wanting to do it all over again just for a video lol. So, you‚Äôll have to take my word for it and trust that it did indeed help quite a bit. As I previously stated, my laundry room is pretty small and tight, so the washer and dryer are right next to each other which makes the spin cycle pretty noisy at times. It also doesn‚Äôt help that the floor is smooth concrete so the washer would boogie around and knock into the dryer, or violently eject anything that was accidentally left on top of the washer before the cycle was finished. Once the pads were in place, the washer still boogies but this time it does so in its designated spot and items left on top may slide a little but for the most part stay put.

Overall, I would definitely recommend this product for anyone that is tired of hearing their washer moving an‚Äô a shaking, but make sure to plan ahead so you don‚Äôt hurt yourself (or your floor for that matter) when moving your washer.
title: They really do work!

text:
Totally loving this for full timing in our travel trailer! It‚Äôs been 2 weeks and I‚Äôve washed so many loads!

This washer is a little over a half of the standard load that I‚Äôm used to and does great job at cleaning the clothes. There are 7 of us, including a 3 & 4 year old that love dirt/mud, and this thing does the job with ease. Hooks right to the sink with the the included adapter. The drain hose fits PERFECTLY into that little hole in the cutting board thingy that covers the sink, which also holds the hose stable when draining.

This is best for full hook up camping, as it uses around 18 gallons to run a full load. BUT if full hook up isn‚Äôt available, I can totally foresee me filling it with 6 gallon jugs of water from the spigot and letting the drain hose run out on the ground (with eco safe detergent).

It does NOT have wheels, so I bought an adjustable rolling appliance cart to keep it out the way of the sink when not in use. We pair it with a 30 pint dehumidifier to hang dry in the camper bathroom. This washer spins the clothes so well that all light weight clothing is dry within 2 hours. Heavy jeans and towels only take 3.

Beats the laundromat any day and will pay for itself within 2-3 months! As long as it holds up over time, I haven‚Äôt found one thing I‚Äôd change about this washer. It‚Äôs perfect for us!
title: Great for full timing in our travel trailer!

text:
A very good stove for the money, though it is not true convection, it is fan convection, which means the convection fan does not have an electric heating element. All gas convection stoves only have the fan going when the flames are off, true convection has the fan on more and the flames on less (after pre-heating) because of the electric supplemental heater. So true convection is a little better at browning meat and cooks a little more evenly (than fan convection), but most stoves with that cost about $500 more. Not worth it! (to me). Any convection is way better than any non-convection for even cooking and browning roasts. It works great.
This is free standing. Slide-ins are nice because you get a little more stove top area than a free standing. Again, about $500 more, not worth it! (to me).
The best stove I have ever had, a major upgrade for me. If you are a very serous cook and want it all, and money is not an option, get a slide-in (if you have counters on both sides) with true convection like NX58H9950WS, but be prepared to part with about $1000 more.
Does anyone know what the actual difference is between the bake and roast settings? I watched my cooking for bake and roast, both ran the lower burner with the fan going between firings. I could see no obvious difference, I thought the roast setting might turn on the top burner for some cycles but it never came on. I could find no real explanation of what the oven is supposed to do that is different.
The griddle is great. I thick slab of aluminum so it heats perfectly evenly when paired with the oval burner. For those that think the griddle is too thin, remember that aluminum has 3 times the thermal conductivity of cast iron. The griddle burner does not get it very hot because the oval burner has a moderate flame, making bacon took a bit longer that when I made it in a frying pan. However, the bacon comes out better because it is more evenly cooked. A great design, keeping the heat moderate will make the teflon last long time. Too much heat and metal spatulas are what kill teflon. I like the Teflon coating so it is easy to clean. Fits in the dishwasher.
title: Great stove for the money.

text:
I've been using OEM filters as well as other third-party filters for my LG fridge (BTW, don't buy an LG fridge... but I guess if you're reading this you know that and it's too late). These filters are a great deal and work perfectly well.

They come in cardboard boxes with a red cap over the business end, which is great to keep them safe from damage in transit or storage. They include a handy set of stickers so you know when you changed it (though my fridge reminds me to change them anyway).

The instructions say to run 4 gallons of water through before using. The first couple of quarts of this 4 gallon run have some sediment, but after that it runs very clear. Once you've watered all your plants and hit the 4 gallon mark, the filters work great. There's no off odors or flavors (I had this issue with different third-party filters for my old GE fridge). Water flows well and tastes great. What more do you need?

And the best part, of course, is the value. These are a killer deal. I probably wouldn't stock up more than a 3-pack as these filters all have shelf-lives, but at that rate you are getting perfectly good filters for a great price. Recommended.
title: Works Perfectly, Awesome Price

text:
LG designs great refrigerators. They're functional, efficient and attractive. Unfortunately, LG uses linear compressors. The LG Linear compressor has a poor life expectancy when compared to different types of reciprocating compressors like the piston or scroll typically found in AC units, or the digital inverter compressors used by Samsung and others. Piston compressors last 20 to 30 years, but the government wants them gone, so companies are stuck with lower life compressors.

Linear compressors are cheaper and there are a few other advantages for refrigerators: however, none of that makes up for the failure rate of the design used by LG.

The failure rate is so high, LG has settled two class action lawsuits in the last few years regarding the compressor, yet LG refuses to change the design, switch to a more reliable compressor type, or even admit the problem.

All appliances produced now days have reliability issues. Part of the problem is US and European governments forcing companies to make more and more efficient appliances. The more efficient compressors and refrigeration equipment become, the less reliable they are. Add that to the poor quality control in Chinese and Korean factories, and the consumer is losing big.

For example, AC units that have a very high seer rating (high energy efficiency) fail more often and cost more to repair than low seer units. Any savings on energy is over shadowed by repair costs over the life of the equipment. The government doesn't care how much we spend replacing and repairing appliances because they want to show everyone how much they're doing to help the environment. It's a bogus objective that comes at a very high cost to consumers. And there is more of it coming--water heaters (barely work now), washing machines and more refrigerator crap.

Of course, LG has more reliable options so who knows what their internal costs are and the internal politics. You can bet that LG has looked closely at the economics of replacing the sealed cooling system with a more reliable one versus paying the claims, etc. They do what's in their best interest not yours.

I've personally had two new $3000 LG fridges both fail within 5 years. I don't bother repairing them, I just buy new ones. In my experience, repairing sealed systems using linear compressors is usually a very short lived solution (as in likely to fail again within 2 yrs). But others may disagree.

I won't buy any more LG refrigerators until they change the cooling system despite how much we like all the other LG features.

As an aside: in my opinion Samsung closed systems are better than LG's, but they've got ice maker problems that they can't or won't fix. They've had to settle claims also. The Samsung design is not nearly as functional as the LG, but it may last longer.
title: Great Design Very Poor Mechanicals
